{"title_page": "List of Germany international footballers", "text_new": "{{Short description|Players of the Germany national football team}}\n{{Hatnote|This page lists men's footballers with 25 or more caps for Germany. For fewer appearances, see players with [[List of Germany international footballers (1\u20134 caps)|1\u20134]] and [[List of Germany international footballers (5\u201319 caps)|5\u201319]] caps. For the current national team squad, see [[Germany national football team#Players|Germany national football team \u00a7 Players]]. For players of the women's national team, see [[List of Germany women's international footballers]].}}\n{{Featured list}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:6423 Lothar Matth\u00e4us.JPG|thumb|160px|[[Lothar Matth\u00e4us]] earned 150 caps for Germany, a team record, and went to nine major international tournaments, captaining the [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990 World Cup]]-winning team.]]\n\nThe [[Germany national football team]] played its first international match on 5 April 1908 during the era of the [[German Empire]], losing 3\u20135 to [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] in [[Basel]].<ref>[http://www.fussballdaten.de/freundschaftsspiele/1908/schweiz-deutschland/ Schweiz \u2013 Deutschland 5 April 1908] Fussballdaten.de. Retrieved 14 May 2009</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/index.php?id=500001&no_cache=1&action=showMatchesByYear&lang=D&liga=Nationalmannschaft&year=1908&cHash=4b53145136 |title=DFB \u2013 Alle Spiele der Nationalmannschaft im Jahr 1908 |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |access-date=19 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118043056/https://www.dfb.de/index.php?id=500001&no_cache=1&action=showMatchesByYear&lang=D&liga=Nationalmannschaft&year=1908&cHash=4b53145136 |archive-date=18 November 2007}}</ref> The team has been one of the most successful national sides in world [[Association football|football]]. They won the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] in [[1954 FIFA World Cup|1954]], [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974]], [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]] and [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]], as well as the [[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]] in [[UEFA Euro 1972|1972]], [[UEFA Euro 1980|1980]] and [[UEFA Euro 1996|1996]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=ger/countryInfo.html |publisher=[[FIFA]] |title=FIFA.com \u2013 Germany: country information|access-date=19 November 2008}}</ref> In doing so, twenty of its players have won both titles, and six have won gold, silver and bronze medals at the World Cup. [[Lothar Matth\u00e4us]] has played in a [[List of FIFA World Cup records and statistics|record]] 25 World Cup matches, and his participation in five World Cup tournaments is a joint record, shared with [[Antonio Carbajal]] of [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]].<ref name=\"WCrecords\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mcwc/ip-301%5f04a%5ffwc%5fsuper%5fnew%5f2465.pdf |format=PDF |title=FIFA World Cup Superlatives |publisher=FIFA |access-date=20 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614230256/http://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mcwc/ip-301_04a_fwc_super_new_2465.pdf |archive-date=14 June 2010}}</ref> [[Miroslav Klose]] is the highest [[List of FIFA World Cup goalscorers#Top goalscorers|goalscorer]] in the tournament's history with 16 goals, while [[Gerd M\u00fcller]] is third with 14.<ref name=\"WCrecords\" /> Former team captain [[Franz Beckenbauer]] is one of only three men to win the World Cup as a player and as a [[Manager (association football)|manager]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/players/player=25113/bio.html |title=Franz Beckenbauer |publisher=FIFA |access-date=20 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722023258/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/players/player%3D25113/bio.html |archive-date=22 July 2011}}</ref> German goalkeeper [[Bodo Illgner]] became the first ever goalkeeper to keep a clean sheet in the [[List of FIFA World Cup finals|final of a FIFA World Cup]] in [[1990 FIFA World Cup Final|1990]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/west-germany-s-1990-winners-in-numbers-2903123 |title=West Germany's 1990 winners in numbers |work=FIFA |access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref> [[Oliver Kahn]] won the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Bal|golden ball]] award at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]], thus becoming the only goalkeeper in the history of the competition to be selected as the best player of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/oliver-kahn-wins-adidas-golden-ball-award-for-the-2002-fifa-world-cupt-82639 |title=Oliver Kahn wins adidas Golden Ball Award for the 2002 FIFA World Cup |work=FIFA |access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nMatth\u00e4us was the inaugural winner of the [[FIFA World Player of the Year]] award in 1991,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/awards/playeroftheyear/winnermen.html |title=FIFA World Player of the Year \u2013 Previous Winners |publisher=FIFA |access-date=20 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528002627/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/awards/playeroftheyear/winnermen.html |archive-date=28 May 2010}}</ref> and is one of five Germany players to have been awarded [[Ballon d'Or]]; two of which, Franz Beckenbauer and [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]], have each won the award twice.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.francefootball.fr/FF/ballon_or/index_bo.html |title=France Football \u2013 Ballon d'Or \u2013 Palmares |work=[[France Football]] |language=French |access-date=19 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081114025309/http://www.francefootball.fr/FF/ballon_or/index_bo.html |archive-date=14 November 2008}}</ref> Beckenbauer was also voted in eighth place for the [[FIFA Player of the Century]] award, and was selected for the [[World Team of the 20th Century]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/06/10/sports/10iht-soccer.t_2.html |title=A Wave of Enthusiasm for the Lingua Franca of Kicking a Ball : From Pele and the Streets, Hope |first=Rob |last=Hughes |work=[[International Herald Tribune]] |date=10 June 1998|access-date=13 February 2011}}</ref> Ten German players were named in the [[FIFA 100]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/3533833.stm |title=FIFA names greatest list |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=4 March 2004| access-date = 19 November 2008}}</ref>  a list of the 125 greatest living footballers chosen by former footballer [[Pel\u00e9]], and ten are in the [[List of footballers with more than 100 international caps|FIFA Century Club]], having earned 100 or more [[Cap (sport)#Association football|cap]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/centclub/centuryclub%5fmen%5f55985.pdf |title=FIFA Century Club (Men) |date=25 June 2008|access-date=19 November 2008 |publisher=FIFA |format=PDF}}</ref> Lothar Matth\u00e4us's 150 international appearances make him the ninth-most capped player in world football, and Miroslav Klose's 71 goals is the [[List of footballers with more than 50 international goals|eleventh-most of any international player]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/century.html#goals |title=Players with 100+ caps and 30+ international goals |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation (RSSSF)]] |access-date=20 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628192800/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/century.html |archive-date=28 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[Captain (association football)|captain]]s of the national team may be awarded the title of honorary captain ({{lang-de|Ehrenspielf\u00fchrer}}) by the [[German Football Association]]. To date, six former players of the men's team have received this award: [[Fritz Walter]] (1958), [[Uwe Seeler]] (1972), Franz Beckenbauer (1982), Lothar Matth\u00e4us (2001), [[J\u00fcrgen Klinsmann]] (2016) and [[Philipp Lahm]] (2017).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/historie/ehrenspielfuehrer-innen/ |publisher=German Football Association |title=Ehrenspielf\u00fchrer |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn total, 947 players have represented the Germany national team. This list covers players with twenty or more caps for the national team organised by the German Football Association, including West Germany. The players are initially ordered by number of caps (in descending order), then by alphabetical order of surname. All statistics are correct up to and including the match played on 19 November 2019 against [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]].\n\n==Selection history==\n[[File:Deutsche Fu\u00dfball-L\u00e4nderspiele Briefmarke 2008.jpg|thumb|200px|Commemorative stamp for the 100th anniversary of the first German international in 1908]]\n\nWar and the political situation of Germany in the 20th century had an impact on the country's [[Territorial evolution of Germany|borders]], as well as the the make-up of the German football team. Germany played 30 internationals until the outbreak of the [[World War I]], with the last match occurring on 5 April 1914 against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]]. During the war, no internationals were played. In the new [[Weimar Republic]], the team played its first post-war match on 27 June 1920 against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]. Only six players that appeared before World War I returned to the post-war side: [[Otto Harder]], [[Adolf J\u00e4ger]], [[Eduard Pendorf]], [[Hans Schmidt (footballer, born 1893)|Hans Schmidt]], [[Josef Sch\u00fcmmelfelder]] and [[Karl Wolter]]. After the [[Nazism|Nazis]] came to power in January 1933, players of Jewish origin were banned from the team.<ref>{{cite news |last=Br\u00fcggemeier |first=Franz-Josef |url=https://www.bpb.de/izpb/8763/juden-im-deutschen-fussball |title=Juden im deutschen Fu\u00dfball |trans-title=Jews in German football |work=[[Federal Agency for Civic Education]] |date=4 May 2006 |access-date=24 April 2020 |language=de}}</ref> Due the [[Anschluss|annexation of Austria]] in 1938, the [[Austria national football team|Austrian team]] was absorbed into the German team, resulting in the inclusion of several Austrians in Germany's [[1938 FIFA World Cup squads#Germany|squad]] at the [[1938 FIFA World Cup|1938 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=5/overview.html |title=FIFA.com \u2013 1938 FIFA World Cup France |access-date=19 November 2008 |publisher=FIFA |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080913232744/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition%3D5/overview.html |archive-date=13 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sch\u00f6ggl |first=Hans |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/oostduit-recintlp.html |title=Austrians in the German National Team |work=[[RSSSF]] |date=27 September 2012 |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> With the outbreak of [[World War II]], Germany did not cease to play internationals, but was limited to facing neutral, allied and [[puppet state]]s. The country played 35 internationals during the war, its last on 22 November 1942 against [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]].<ref name=\"internationals\">{{cite web |last=Arnhold |first=Matthias |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/duit-intres.html |title=(West) Germany \u2013 International Results |work=[[RSSSF]] |date=2 April 2020 |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War II]] and the team's reinstatement into [[FIFA]], the [[German Football Association]] (DFB) was in charge of football in the [[West Germany|Federal Republic]] and [[West Berlin]]. During this period, the team was commonly referred to as West Germany. The team played its first post-war international on 22 November 1950 against Switzerland.<ref name=\"internationals\"/> Only four players selected before the war were capped for the nation afterwards: [[Herbert Burdenski]], [[Andreas Kupfer]], [[Jakob Streitle]] and [[Fritz Walter]]. Due to the break-up of Germany, two breakaway national teams were formed: [[Saarland national football team|Saarland]] (in 1950) and [[East Germany national football team|East Germany]] (in 1952).<ref name=\"DDR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/index.php?id=53 |publisher=German Football Association |title=DDR-Fu\u00dfball |language=German |access-date=19 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080604150032/https://www.dfb.de/index.php?id=53 |archive-date=4 June 2008}}</ref> [[Franz Immig]] of Saarland was the only player in either team to have been previously capped for Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/saar-intres.html |title=Saar \u2013 List of International Matches and Line-Ups |publisher=RSSSF|access-date=19 November 2008}}</ref> Saarland played their final match in 1956, after which control of the [[Saar Protectorate]] was given to West Germany. Three of the Saar team's players later represented Germany: [[Karl Ringel]], [[Gerhard Siedl]] and [[Heinz Vollmar]]. Upon [[German reunification|Germany's reunification]] in 1990,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=76/overview.html |title=FIFA.com \u2013 1990 FIFA World Cup Italy |publisher=FIFA |access-date=19 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204061444/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition%3D76/overview.html |archive-date=4 February 2012}}</ref> the East German team was reintegrated into the German national team.<ref name=\"DDR\"/> Eight players capped for East Germany later appeared for the reunified team: [[Thomas Doll]], [[Ulf Kirsten]], [[Olaf Marschall]], [[Matthias Sammer]], [[Heiko Scholz]], [[Dirk Schuster]], [[Andreas Thom]], [[Dariusz Wosz]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/historie/ddr-fussball/rekordspieler/ |title=DDR-Fu\u00dfball: Rekordspieler |trans-title=East German football: Record player appearances |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |access-date=24 April 2020 |language=de}}</ref>\n\n==Key==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center; margin-left:1em; float:right;\"\n|+ Positions key\n|-\n!GK\n|[[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n|-\n!DF\n|[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n|-\n!MF\n|[[Midfielder]]\n|-\n!FW\n|[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n|}\n{{glossary}}\n{{term|Player}}\n{{legend|#FBEC5D|This color background and the * symbol indicate that the player is currently active at the club level.}}\n{{term|Position}}\n{{defn|[[Association football positions|Playing positions]] are listed according to the player's primary position while playing for the national team.<ref>{{cite web |last=Strack-Zimmerman |first=Benjamin |url=https://www.national-football-teams.com/statistics.html?nft_storebundle_player_filter%5Bcountry%5D=71 |title=Statistics: Germany |work=National Football Teams |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>}}\n{{term|Caps and goals}}\n{{defn|[[Cap (sport)#Association football|Caps]] and goals comprise those in the [[FIFA World Cup]] and [[UEFA European Championship]], their associated qualification matches, as well as [[UEFA Nations League]] matches and international friendly tournaments and matches.}}\n{{glossary end}}\n\n==Players==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Germany national football team players with at least 20 caps\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Player\n! rowspan=\"2\" | {{abbr|Pos.|Playing position}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Caps\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Goals\n! colspan=\"2\" | Debut\n! colspan=\"2\" | Last or most recent match\n! rowspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|- class=\"unsortable\"\n! Date\n! Opponent\n! Date\n! Op