.dfb.de/index.php?id=12337 |title=DFB \u2013 Nationalmannschaft \u2013 Statistik |work=German Football Association |access-date=17 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080913175432/https://www.dfb.de/index.php?id=12337 |archive-date=13 September 2008}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/index.html |title=FIFA.com \u2013 Previous World Cups |work=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association (FIFA)|access-date=17 October 2008}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://en.euro2008.uefa.com/history/index.html |title=Euro 2008 \u2013 History |work=Union of European Football Associations (UEFA) |access-date=17 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012002802/http://en.euro2008.uefa.com/history/index.html |archive-date=12 October 2008}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.dfb.de/die-mannschaft/statistik/alle-spieler-von-a-bis-z/ Player list] from DFB {{LL|de}}\n*[https://www.worldfootball.net/teams/deutschland-team/12/ All-time appearances] at WorldFootball.net\n*[https://eu-football.info/_players.php?id=86&data=9 Germany national team caps] at EU-Football.info\n\n{{Germany national football team}}\n{{Football in Germany}}\n{{Association football players}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of Germany international footballers| ]]\n[[Category:Association football player non-biographical articles]]\n", "name_user": "S.A. Julio", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlayers:colour", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Germany_international_footballers"}
{"title_page": "Yan Yan Mak", "text_new": "{{BLP unsourced|date=August 2017}}\n{{infobox person\n| name        = Yan Yan Mak\n| image       = Yanyanmak 2019.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Mak at the 2010 [[Hong Kong Asian Film Festival]]\n| birth_place = Hong Kong\n| module      = {{Infobox Chinese\n| child=yes\n| t = \u9ea5\u5a49\u6b23\n| s = \u9ea6\u5a49\u6b23\n| p = M\u00e0i W\u0103nx\u012bn\n| j = Maak6 Jyun2 Jan1\n}}\n}}\n'''Yan Yan Mak (Man Yuen-Yan)''' is a [[Hong Kong]] based female award-winning director. She graduated from the [[Hong Kong Academy for Performing Arts]]; as a student, Yan Yan had worked for the film industry as assistant director, production manager, art director and wardrobe designer. Her graduation short film ''Snapshots'' won the Distinguish Award at the International Short Film & Video Awards of [[Hong Kong]] in 1998.\n\nAfter directing number of short dramas for [[Radio Television Hong Kong]], she established her own production company Dragonfly J Ltd., to make her own film. Her debut feature film, ''Gege'' (''Brother''), although using a very limited budget, a small crew and an all non-actors cast, was awarded the [[FIPRESCI Award]] at the 25th [[Hong Kong International Film Festival]], the POVEGLIA Award at the International Week of Film Critics of the 58th [[Venice Film Festival]], the Woosuk Award at [[Jeonju International Film Festival]] in [[South Korea]], as well as the Ecumenical Hury Prize at the [[International Film Festival Bratislava]] and [[Fribourg International Film Festival]] 2001.\n\nHer second film ''[[Butterfly (2004 film)|Butterfly]]'' [http://www.cinaoggi.it/english/CINEMA/movies/butterfly.htm (''Hudie'')] was chosen as the Opening Film at [[Venice Film Festival|Venice Film Festival Critics Week]] (La Biennale di Venezia), The Hong Kong Gay & Lesbian Film Festival 2004 and [[Cr\u00e9teil International Women's Film Festival]] in France 2005. The film won the Best Feature award at the [[Paris Lesbian and Feminist Film Festival]]. [[Tian Yuan (singer)|Tian Yuan]] was awarded as the Best New Artist at the [[Hong Kong Film Awards]] in 2005. The film was also nominated at the Taiwan [[Golden Horse Awards]] in 2004 for Best Adapted Screenplay (Yan Yan Mak) and Best Supporting Actor ([[Eric Kot]]). Butterfly has been screened in he Hong Kong Retrospective section in the Hong Kong Gay & Lesbian Film Festival 2019.\n\nFrom 2005, after become the collaborator with Hong Kong [[Cantopop]] singer [[Denise Ho]], Yan Yan has produced numeral music videos, music short films and TV Commercials. ''The Scarlet Robe'' has won the Best Drama in [[BigScreen Festival]], China 2007. They had finished their first feature-length film [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hw3R1PXUzq8 ''The Decameron'' (a documentary about madness, under the music project \"10 Days in the Madhouse\")] in 2009. Recently, Yan Yan has collaborated with [[Denise Ho]] as her concert producer and director in ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JC8WxXx5ow0 Reimagine Hong Kong]'' (2015), ''Macpherson Woods'' (2015), ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wBgt4RkF4LE Dear Friend],'' (2016) and [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ADBuROuLOsU On The Pulse Of Hocc Live 2018]. She had also produced 'Galactica', concerts of singer [[Endy Chow|Endy Chow Kwok Yin]] in 2017/18.\n\nYan Yan completed her another feature [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nwV8TG8pn_k ''Merry-Go-Round'' (''Dong Feng Po'')] in 2010 at Hong Kong. It had been elected as the Best Chinese-Language Film from Film Critics China, nominated at The Hong Kong Film Award 2011 for the Best Cinematography Award and won the Best Film Song Award ([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cYrItHVkdAs \"Here to Stay\" by Jun Kung]), won the Best Actress ([[Ella Koon]]) and the Best Actor ([[Teddy Robin]]) at Australia Golden Koala Film Festival.\n\nHer another feature work ''The Great War'' (2013), a documentary about Grasshopper x [[Softhard]] Concert 2012, has had its Gala premiere at the [[New York Asian Film Festival]] 2013 as also selected as the closing-film of the film festival. \n\nYan Yan's latest advertising work 'Numbers'  for The Women's Foundation has been awarded at Film Craft section of AD STARS 2019 (Korea).\n\n<br />\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of female film and television directors]]\n* [[List of LGBT-related films directed by women]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=4191104}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mak, Yan Yan}}\n[[Category:1970s births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong film directors]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong women writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of The Hong Kong Academy for Performing Arts]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong women artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP unsourced|date=August 2017}}\n{{infobox person\n| name        = Yan Yan Mak\n| image       = Yanyanmak 2019.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Mak at the 2010 [[Hong Kong Asian Film Festival]]\n| birth_place = Hong Kong\n| module      = {{Infobox Chinese\n| child=yes\n| t = \u9ea5\u5a49\u6b23\n| s = \u9ea6\u5a49\u6b23\n| p = M\u00e0i W\u0103nx\u012bn\n| j = Maak6 Jyun2 Jan1\n}}\n}}\n'''Yan Yan Mak (Man Yuen-Yan)''' is a [[Hong Kong]] based female award-winning director. She graduated from the [[Hong Kong Academy for Performing Arts]]; as a student, Yan Yan had worked for the film industry as assistant director, production manager, art director and wardrobe designer. Her graduation short film ''Snapshots'' won the Distinguish Award at the International Short Film & Video Awards of [[Hong Kong]] in 1998.\n\nAfter directing number of short dramas for [[Radio Television Hong Kong]], she established her own production company Dragonfly J Ltd., to make her own film. Her debut feature film, ''Gege'' (''Brother''), although using a very limited budget, a small crew and an all non-actors cast, was awarded the [[FIPRESCI Award]] at the 25th [[Hong Kong International Film Festival]], the POVEGLIA Award at the International Week of Film Critics of the 58th [[Venice Film Festival]], the Woosuk Award at [[Jeonju International Film Festival]] in [[South Korea]], as well as the Ecumenical Hury Prize at the [[International Film Festival Bratislava]] and [[Fribourg International Film Festival]] 2001.\n\nHer second film ''[[Butterfly (2004 film)|Butterfly]]'' [http://www.cinaoggi.it/english/CINEMA/movies/butterfly.htm (''Hudie'')] was chosen as the Opening Film at [[Venice Film Festival|Venice Film Festival Critics Week]] (La Biennale di Venezia), the Hong Kong Gay & Lesbian Film and Video Film Festival 2004 and [[Cr\u00e9teil International Women's Film Festival]] in France 2005. The film won the Best Feature award at the [[Paris Lesbian and Feminist Film Festival]]. [[Tian Yuan (singer)|Tian Yuan]] was awarded as the Best New Artist at the [[Hong Kong Film Awards]] in 2005. The film was also nominated at the Taiwan [[Golden Horse Awards]] in 2004 for Best Adapted Screenplay (Yan Yan Mak) and Best Supporting Actor ([[Eric Kot]]).\n\nFrom 2005, after become the collaborator with Hong Kong [[Cantopop]] singer [[Denise Ho]], Yan Yan has produced numeral music videos, music short films and TV Commercials. ''The Scarlet Robe'' has won the Best Drama in [[BigScreen Festival]], China 2007. They had finished their first feature-length film [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hw3R1PXUzq8 ''The Decameron'' (a documentary about madness, under the music project \"10 Days in the Madhouse\")] in 2009. Recently, Yan Yan has collaborated with [[Denise Ho]] as her concert producer and director in ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JC8WxXx5ow0 Reimagine Hong Kong]'' (2015), ''Macpherson Woods'' (2015), ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wBgt4RkF4LE Dear Friend],'' (2016) and [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ADBuROuLOsU On The Pulse Of Hocc Live 2018]. She had also produced 'Galactica', concerts of singer [[Endy Chow|Endy Chow Kwok Yin]] in 2017/18.\n\nYan Yan completed her another feature [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nwV8TG8pn_k ''Merry-Go-Round'' (''Dong Feng Po'')] in 2010 at Hong Kong. It had been elected as the Best Chinese-Language Film from Film Critics China, nominated at The Hong Kong Film Award 2011 for the Best Cinematography Award and won the Best Film Song Award ([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cYrItHVkdAs \"Here to Stay\" by Jun Kung]), won the Best Actress ([[Ella Koon]]) and the Best Actor ([[Teddy Robin]]) at Australia Golden Koala Film Festival.\n\nHer another feature work ''The Great War'' (2013), a documentary about Grasshopper x [[Softhard]] Concert 2012, has had its Gala premiere at the [[New York Asian Film Festival]] 2013 as also selected as the closing-film of the film festival. \n\nYan Yan's latest advertising work 'Numbers'  for The Women's Foundation has been awarded at Film Craft section of AD STARS 2019 (Korea).\n\n<br />\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of female film and television directors]]\n* [[List of LGBT-related films directed by women]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=4191104}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mak, Yan Yan}}\n[[Category:1970s births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong film directors]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong women writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of The Hong Kong Academy for Performing Arts]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong women artists]]\n", "name_user": "219.77.96.205", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(adding information)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yan_Yan_Mak"}
{"title_page": "Keith Wookey", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = <!-- Keith Wookey -->\n| image         = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by the blind and visually impaired's speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software  -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = 1 January 1912\n| birth_place   = Lincolnshire, UK\n| death_date    = November 1963 at the age of 51\n| death_place   = United Kingdom\n| nationality   = British\n| other_names   = W.K.C. Wookey\n| occupation    = Assistant District Officer, District Officer, Resident and Senior Official of British Colonial Government of North Borneo\n| years_active  = 1936 to 1963 \n| children      = 4\n}}\n[[File:KeithTenku.jpg|thumb|Keith Wookey & \n[[Tunku Abdul Rahman|Tunku]] Abdul Rahman\n]]\n'''Keith Wookey''' (1912 - 1963) also known as ''W.K.C. Wookey'', was a [[District Officer]] and later Resident in the post-war British Colonial Government of North Borneo who rose to prominence after the [[Second World War]]. At the height of his authority, Wookey was the most senior official stationed in Sandakan as [[Resident (title)|Resident]] (known as Resident Commissioner in full) and was also appointed by the [[Queen Elizabeth I|Queen]] to the Executive Council, North Borneo.<ref name=\"auto\">The London Gazette, 12th of February 1960. Retrieved from: www.thegazette.co.uk</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early life ===\n\nWalter Keith Caple Wookey, known as \u201cGentleman Keith\u201d to his family and friends, was born in Sleaford, Lincolnshire and soon after moved to Barbados Lodge, Bath, Somerset, schooled at Lewisham, Bristol, UK and went on to further his studies at Oxford. His mother, Elizabeth Walker, died in 1921 at the birth of Keith\u2019s sister Betty. Soon, both Keith & Betty were taken to their grandparents, Francis & Alice Wookey who raised them at Stones Cross House, Somerset. After his graduation, Keith got a job in a bank which allowed him to indulge in his passion for Motor Bike Racing on his [[Velocette]] 'K' series motor bike at the [[Isle of Man TT]] race. From 1933 to 1935 Keith joined the Royal Navy Reserve. \n\nIn 1936, Keith made an announcement that he is going to [[Borneo]] the next day for the 'far east', leaving his family stunned and question why anyone would possibly want to go so far away. {{citation needed|reason=Keith's life was detailed on a Facebook page linked to the North Borneo's Historical Society page|date=January 2016}}\n\n=== Pre-war ===\n\nOn 17 April 1936 Keith came to [[North Borneo]] as a cadet (trainee government official), joining the [[British North Borneo Chartered Company]] administrators. He arrived in [[Sandakan]] with Mr. J.H. Macartney by S.S. Kajang on 18 April 1936.<ref>1st May 1936. The British North Borneo Herald, No. 9 \u2013 Vol. LIV.</ref> At the beginning of his career as a trainee government official, Keith was placed within the Secretariat, although he was also supervised most of the time by the Under Secretary. From then on, Keith transferred from various branches of Government taking short posts while doing his study of the Laws of the State and of the Malay language.<ref name=\"auto1\">North Borneo Historic Society, http://www.northborneohistory.com</ref>\n\nIn 1938, two years after his arrival in Sandakan, Keith became Assistant District officer at Mempakul (today as the westernmost part of Sabah, Malaysia; known as Kampung Mempakul) and then was posted to Kota Belud after a year. During his stay in [[Kota Belud]], Keith met his first wife Tampusis who was the daughter of a priestess from [[Ranau]]. After their traditional wedding, Tampusis gave birth to two girls, Agnes (born 1940) and Susan (born 1941). {{citation needed|reason=Keith's life was detailed on a Facebook page linked to the North Borneo's Historical Society page|date=January 2016}}\n\nDuring his later years, Keith would often reminisce about the part of his life where he went into the jungle, riding his horse under the magnificent [[Mount Kinabalu]]. During this time, Keith lived in various [[Kampong (village)|Kampong]]s for weeks at a time and would take time to speak with locals, during this time Keith also became proficient in various dialects of Dusun, [[Kadazan]] language.<ref name=\"auto2\">Keith Wookey. Personal Diary entry dated 1961.</ref>\n\n\"When I go into the jungle, I think in Malay & Kadazan. I find peace when I go into the jungle. I used to visit the native chief(s) and we would talk and banter a lot together. We became friends.\"<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nNot long after Susan\u2019s birth in 1941, Keith\u2019s family moved to [[Lahad Datu]] where he was appointed as an Assistant District Officer.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n=== Life during the War ===\n\nIn January 1942, while Keith was posted in Lahad Datu, the rule of the British North Borneo Chartered Company was abruptly ended and North Borneo was taken over by Japanese Imperial forces after their  landing in Jesselton (presently known as [[Kota Kinabalu]]).  Despite the impossibility of resisting the Japanese naval and military forces, the chartered company ordered its posted officials to stay in their assigned places and aid in protecting the locals by giving advice in the face of the invasion. Keith, during this time, was badly beaten and taken away from his family, while Tampusis was forced to remarry in order to protect herself from the Japanese Imperial Army. The Japanese shipped Keith first to Sandakan at Berhala Island with Harry Keith and other fellow officers. Later on, he was moved to [[Kuching]], spending his next three years in [[Batu Lintang camp]] which was under the command of [[Tatsuji Suga|Lieutenant-Colonel Tatsuji Suga]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n\"The behaviour of the population during this period was, with very few exceptions, exemplary, and many paid for their loyalty with their lives. The British Military Administration, which contained a few former Chartered Company senior officers, found the Colony in a state of appalling devastation.\"<ref name=\"auto3\">North Borneo Annual Report, 1951, p. 93</ref>\n\nFor more than three years, North Borneo remained under the control of the [[Japanese Imperial Army]] until the units of the [[9th Division (Australia)|Ninth Australian Division]] landed in Labuan on 10 June 1945.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> In Keith\u2019s personal journal entry dated 20 August 1945,<ref>Keith Wookey. Personal Journal dated 20th of August 1945.</ref> he states that this was the first time he was given a piece of paper to write on since the Japanese invasion.\n\n=== Post War ===\n\nIn September 1945, Keith and his friend [[Marcus Clarke (doctor)|Dr. Marcus Clarke]], who was then a surgeon captured by the Japanese and stationed in Batu Lintang as well, were released from internment. Shortly thereafter, Keith traveled to Sydney, Australia for recuperation in 1946. Upon his return to North Borneo in 1947, Keith played a key role in the rebuilding and the development of Sandakan in the aftermath of the Second World War. During this time, the territory changed status from a protectorate of England and administration by the Chartered Company to a [[Crown Colony]], overseen by the government of Britain in London.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nDuring a short stay in Australia while on leave, he met Eleanor Farrell who he soon married. Upon his return to North Borneo with Eleanor in 1948, Keith was posted in [[Tenom]] as a [[District Officer]]. Two years later, Keith and Eleanor moved to Jesselton and in May 1950, their first son Michael was born. It was here, during the early 1950s that Keith became close friends with Governor [[Roland Evelyn Turnbull|Roland Turnbull]]. In 1956, after a five-year service, Keith was appointed as a permanent member of the Executive Legislature and was appointed in 1957 as Resident of Sandakan. At the same year, his second son Robin was born. {{citation needed|reason=Keith's life was detailed in a Facebook page linked to the North Borneo's Historical Society page|date=January 2016}}\n\nAs published within [[The London Gazette]] dated 12 February 1960, Keith was appointed by the Queen as an Official Member of the Executive Council of the Colony of North Borneo.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  Keith, as a senior official in the Colonial Government of North Borneo, was notable in his opposition to the succession by the crown of the colony of North Borneo to join the Malaysian federation.  Indeed, as mentioned in an article published in [[The Straits Times|The Strait Times]] dated 12 March 1962, Keith, along with other senior British Civil servants, was accused of obstruction by [[Tunku Abdul Rahman]], Malaysia's first Prime Minister.<ref>Article Retrieved from: http://britishnorthborneohistory.blogspot.com</ref> Keith felt, after a career spent engaging in a dialogue with the Kadazan tribes, teaching the reigns of government at native chiefs conferences, that North Borneo ought to, at some stage, be governed by the Kadazan tribes themselves, with he disputing the wisdom of the British Government in facilitating the transfer of the governance and sovereignty of North Borneo to [[Malaysia]].<ref>Keith Wookey. Personal Diary entry dated 1962.</ref>\n\nDuring Keith\u2019s appointment as Sandakan\u2019s Resident, [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] and [[HMY Britannia|Britannia]], the Queen's yacht, visited Sandakan in 1959 where a rousing reception was put on for the young prince. {{citation needed|reason=Keith's life was detailed on a Facebook page linked to the North Borneo's Historical Society page|date=January 2016}}\n\nIn November 1963, Keith unexpectedly died of a heart attack shortly after North Borneo (now known as [[Sabah]]) was granted self-governance on 31 August 1963, preparing to join Malaya, Sarawak and Singapore in forming the [[Malaysia|Federation of Malaysia]]. {{citation needed|reason=Keith's life was detailed on a Facebook page linked to the North Borneo's Historical Society page|date=January 2016}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.northborneohistory.com\n\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:British colonial officials]]\n[[Category:British Borneo]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = <!-- Keith Wookey -->\n| image         = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by the blind and visually impaired's speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software  -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = 1 January 1912\n| birth_place   = Lincolnshire, UK\n| death_date    = November 1963 at the age of 51\n| death_place   = United Kingdom\n| nationality   = British\n| other_names   = W.K.C. Wookey\n| occupation    = Assistant District Officer, District Officer, Senior Official of British Colonial Government of North Borneo\n| years_active  = 1936 to 1963 \n| children      = 4\n}}\n[[File:KeithTenku.jpg|thumb|Keith Wookey & \n[[Tunku Abdul Rahman|Tunku]] Abdul Rahman\n]]\n'''Keith Wookey''' (1912 - 1963) also known as ''W.K.C. Wookey'', was a [[District Officer]] and later Resident in the post-war British Colonial Government of North Borneo who rose to prominence after the [[Second World War]]. At the height of his authority, Wookey was the most senior official stationed in Sandakan as [[Resident (title)|Resident]] (known as Resident Commissioner in full) and later was appointed by the [[Queen Elizabeth I|Queen]] to the Executive Council, North Borneo.<ref name=\"auto\">The London Gazette, 12th of February 1960. Retrieved from: www.thegazette.co.uk</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early life ===\n\nWalter Keith Caple Wookey, known as \u201cGentleman Keith\u201d to his family and friends, was born in Sleaford, Lincolnshire and soon after moved to Barbados Lodge, Bath, Somerset, schooled at Lewisham, Bristol, UK and went on to further his studies at Oxford. His mother, Elizabeth Walker, died in 1921 at the birth of Keith\u2019s sister Betty. Soon, both Keith & Betty were taken to their grandparents, Francis & Alice Wookey who raised them at Stones Cross House, Somerset. After his graduation, Keith got a job in a bank which allowed him to indulge in his passion for Motor Bike Racing on his [[Velocette]] 'K' series motor bike at the [[Isle of Man TT]] race. From 1933 to 1935 Keith joined the Royal Navy Reserve. \n\nIn 1936, Keith made an announcement that he is going to [[Borneo]] the next day for the 'far east', leaving his family stunned and question why anyone would possibly want to go so far away. {{citation needed|reason=Keith's life was detailed on a Facebook page linked to the North Borneo's Historical Society page|date=January 2016}}\n\n=== Pre-war ===\n\nOn 17 April 1936 Keith came to [[North Borneo]] as a cadet (trainee government official), joining the [[British North Borneo Chartered Company]] administrators. He arrived in [[Sandakan]] with Mr. J.H. Macartney by S.S. Kajang on 18 April 1936.<ref>1st May 1936. The British North Borneo Herald, No. 9 \u2013 Vol. LIV.</ref> At the beginning of his career as a trainee government official, Keith was placed within the Secretariat, although he was also supervised most of the time by the Under Secretary. From then on, Keith transferred from various branches of Government taking short posts while doing his study of the Laws of the State and of the Malay language.<ref name=\"auto1\">North Borneo Historic Society, http://www.northborneohistory.com</ref>\n\nIn 1938, two years after his arrival in Sandakan, Keith became Assistant District officer at Mempakul (today as the westernmost part of Sabah, Malaysia; known as Kampung Mempakul) and then was posted to Kota Belud after a year. During his stay in [[Kota Belud]], Keith met his first wife Tampusis who was the daughter of a priestess from [[Ranau]]. After their traditional wedding, Tampusis gave birth to two girls, Agnes (born 1940) and Susan (born 1941). {{citation needed|reason=Keith's life was detailed on a Facebook page linked to the North Borneo's Historical Society page|date=January 2016}}\n\nDuring his later years, Keith would often reminisce about the part of his life where he went into the jungle, riding his horse under the magnificent [[Mount Kinabalu]]. During this time, Keith lived in various [[Kampong (village)|Kampong]]s for weeks at a time and would take time to speak with locals, during this time Keith also became proficient in various dialects of Dusun, [[Kadazan]] language.<ref name=\"auto2\">Keith Wookey. Personal Diary entry dated 1961.</ref>\n\n\"When I go into the jungle, I think in Malay & Kadazan. I find peace when I go into the jungle. I used to visit the native chief(s) and we would talk and banter a lot together. We became friends.\"<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nNot long after Susan\u2019s birth in 1941, Keith\u2019s family moved to [[Lahad Datu]] where he was appointed as an Assistant District Officer.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n=== Life during the War ===\n\nIn January 1942, while Keith was posted in Lahad Datu, the rule of the British North Borneo Chartered Company was abruptly ended and North Borneo was taken over by Japanese Imperial forces after their  landing in Jesselton (presently known as [[Kota Kinabalu]]).  Despite the impossibility of resisting the Japanese naval and military forces, the chartered company ordered its posted officials to stay in their assigned places and aid in protecting the locals by giving advice in the face of the invasion. Keith, during this time, was badly beaten and taken away from his family, while Tampusis was forced to remarry in order to protect herself from the Japanese Imperial Army. The Japanese shipped Keith first to Sandakan at Berhala Island with Harry Keith and other fellow officers. Later on, he was moved to [[Kuching]], spending his next three years in [[Batu Lintang camp]] which was under the command of [[Tatsuji Suga|Lieutenant-Colonel Tatsuji Suga]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n\"The behaviour of the population during this period was, with very few exceptions, exemplary, and many paid for their loyalty with their lives. The British Military Administration, which contained a few former Chartered Company senior officers, found the Colony in a state of appalling devastation.\"<ref name=\"auto3\">North Borneo Annual Report, 1951, p. 93</ref>\n\nFor more than three years, North Borneo remained under the control of the [[Japanese Imperial Army]] until the units of the [[9th Division (Australia)|Ninth Australian Division]] landed in Labuan on 10 June 1945.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> In Keith\u2019s personal journal entry dated 20 August 1945,<ref>Keith Wookey. Personal Journal dated 20th of August 1945.</ref> he states that this was the first time he was given a piece of paper to write on since the Japanese invasion.\n\n=== Post War ===\n\nIn September 1945, Keith and his friend [[Marcus Clarke (doctor)|Dr. Marcus Clarke]], who was then a surgeon captured by the Japanese and stationed in Batu Lintang as well, were released from internment. Shortly thereafter, Keith traveled to Sydney, Australia for recuperation in 1946. Upon his return to North Borneo in 1947, Keith played a key role in the rebuilding and the development of Sandakan in the aftermath of the Second World War. During this time, the territory changed status from a protectorate of England and administration by the Chartered Company to a [[Crown Colony]], overseen by the government of Britain in London.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nDuring a short stay in Australia while on leave, he met Eleanor Farrell who he soon married. Upon his return to North Borneo with Eleanor in 1948, Keith was posted in [[Tenom]] as a [[District Officer]]. Two years later, Keith and Eleanor moved to Jesselton and in May 1950, their first son Michael was born. It was here, during the early 1950s that Keith became close friends with Governor [[Roland Evelyn Turnbull|Roland Turnbull]]. In 1956, after a five-year service, Keith was appointed as a permanent member of the Executive Legislature and was appointed in 1957 as Resident of Sandakan. At the same year, his second son Robin was born. {{citation needed|reason=Keith's life was detailed in a Facebook page linked to the North Borneo's Historical Society page|date=January 2016}}\n\nAs published within [[The London Gazette]] dated 12 February 1960, Keith was appointed by the Queen as an Official Member of the Executive Council of the Colony of North Borneo.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  Keith, as a senior official in the Colonial Government of North Borneo, was notable in his opposition to the succession by the crown of the colony of North Borneo to join the Malaysian federation.  Indeed, as mentioned in an article published in [[The Straits Times|The Strait Times]] dated 12 March 1962, Keith, along with other senior British Civil servants, was accused of obstruction by [[Tunku Abdul Rahman]], Malaysia's first Prime Minister.<ref>Article Retrieved from: http://britishnorthborneohistory.blogspot.com</ref> Keith felt, after a career spent engaging in a dialogue with the Kadazan tribes, teaching the reigns of government at native chiefs conferences, that North Borneo ought to, at some stage, be governed by the Kadazan tribes themselves, with he disputing the wisdom of the British Government in facilitating the transfer of the governance and sovereignty of North Borneo to [[Malaysia]].<ref>Keith Wookey. Personal Diary entry dated 1962.</ref>\n\nDuring Keith\u2019s appointment as Sandakan\u2019s Resident, [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] and [[HMY Britannia|Britannia]], the Queen's yacht, visited Sandakan in 1959 where a rousing reception was put on for the young prince. {{citation needed|reason=Keith's life was detailed on a Facebook page linked to the North Borneo's Historical Society page|date=January 2016}}\n\nIn November 1963, Keith unexpectedly died of a heart attack shortly after North Borneo (now known as [[Sabah]]) was granted self-governance on 31 August 1963, preparing to join Malaya, Sarawak and Singapore in forming the [[Malaysia|Federation of Malaysia]]. {{citation needed|reason=Keith's life was detailed on a Facebook page linked to the North Borneo's Historical Society page|date=January 2016}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.northborneohistory.com\n\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:British colonial officials]]\n[[Category:British Borneo]]\n", "name_user": "Wookee12000", "label": "safe", "comment": "correction of timeline", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keith_Wookey"}
{"title_page": "All Saints School, Bhopal", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n|\nname = All Saints School, Bhopal|\nestablished = 1980|\ntype = [[Private school|Private]]|\nreligion =|\nhead_name = Headmaster|\nhead = |\ncity = Idgah Hills|\nstate = [[Bhopal]]|\ncountry = [[India]]|\ncampus = |\nenrollment = 2,500 total|\nfaculty = |\nclass = |\nratio = |\nathletics = |\ncolors = |\nmascot = |\nhomepage = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|23.265728|N|77.388821|E|display=inline}}\n|pushpin_map            = India Bhopal\n|pushpin_map_caption            = Location in Bhopal, India\n}}\n\n'''All Saints' School, Bhopal''' is an English medium school located at Idgah Hills [[Bhopal]], [[India]]. It was founded in 1980 by Iris Cynthia Philomene Auer. Miss Auer came to India after she retired as principal of a school in England. From seven pupils in July 1980, the strength has grown to over 2,500 pupils.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.asctbhopal.com/The_Foundress.html\n|title=All Saints ' College of Technology - Bhopal, India\n|publisher=www.asctbhopal.com\n|accessdate=2008-06-07\n|last=\n|first=\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080522050220/http://www.asctbhopal.com/The_Foundress.html\n|archivedate=22 May 2008\n|url-status=dead\n|df=dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> Miss Auer's was appointed Member of the Order of the British Empire ([[MBE (Order of the British Empire)|MBE]]) in the [[Elizabeth II|Queen]]'s Birthday Honours List in 1989.\nThe Principal and Chairperson of All Saints' School is Mrs. Kaiser Zaman (popularly known as \"Bia\") . She is an alumnus of [[University of Oxford]], B.Ed and was a student of Miss Auer. She founded All Saints' College Of technology  which is an engineering college of Bhopal M.P. It was visited by Former president late [[Dr. APJ Abdul Kalam]] in 2013.\n\n==Motto==\n''To the Highest''.\n\n==Houses==\nThe school has four houses: Vindhya, Himachal, Yamuna and Ganga. There is an annual House Competition with contests, including dancing, singing, [[elocution]], and drama.\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\nThere are dance classes, [[Karate]] lessons, [[cricket]], [[Association football|football]], [[throwball]], and other sports teams. Students participate in tournaments, the most notable being the yearly All Saints versus. [[Scindia School|Scinidia Boys School]], [[Gwalior]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2007}} The school has ten black belts in Karate. All Saints has a choir. One of the formal events is the annual farewell party thrown by the 11th grade in honour of the outgoing batch of students\n\n==Office bearers==\nThe [[Head Boy]] and Head Girl occupy the highest office in the school, followed by Coordinator, Head [[Prefect]], Prefects, and Sub-Prefects. There are other posts assigned to students like Sports Coordinator, Cultural Coordinator. The houses have house captains and vice captains.\nList of Head Boys and Head Girls so far is:\n\n1989-1990 - Ashish Jaiswal - Pushpa Hingorani (elected)\n\n1990-1991 - Ashish Jaiswal - Pushpa Hingorani (elected)\n\n1991-1992 - Ashish Jaiswal - Pushpa Hingorani nominated SCHOOL CAPTAIN\n\n1991-1992 - Vinay Shrivastave - Sheran Mendiratta (elected)\n\n1992-1993 - Neeraj Agarwal - Puja Rai\n\n1993-1994 - Deepak Choukse - Shveta Malik\n\n1994-1995 - Naved Masood - Ritu Induria\n\n1995-1996 - Abhay Raj Lodhi - Priyanka Pandey\n\n1996-1997 - Bir Singh Bagga - Sonia Kanjani\n\n1997-1998 - Shekhar Arora - Moushmi Nema\n\n1998-1999 - Amit Nathani - Sabina Sultan\n\n1999-2000 - Janab Choudhuri - Pragti Nagar. Himachal House Captain - Shadab Masood.\n\n2000-2001 - Adnan Abbasi - Payal Pisal\n\n2001-2002 - S M Farooq - Anita Kanjani\n\n2002-2003 - Rohit Singh - Mariyam Saulat\n\n2003-2004 - Md. Karam Abbasi - Jigayasa Balwani\n\n2004-2005 - Nandan Narula - Chani Singh.\n\n2005-2006 - Mohammad Sohaib Iqbal - Richa Manchanda\n\n2006-2007 - Mohd Arshil Muheet -Hena Agarwal\n\n2007-2008 -Rajat agarwal - Mehwish Sajid\n\n2008-2009- Syeda Anam anwar - Rohit Anandani\n\n2009-2010 - Jehangeer hussain- Priyanka Rohera\n\n2010-2011 - Zeeshan Siddiqui - Ayushi Paliwal.\n\n2011-2012 - Anchal Sahu - Anam Habeeb\n\n2013-2014 - Ravish Gurbani - Tasneem Safi [M.P BOARD]\n\n2013-2014 - Abhishek Upadhyay - Yoshita Kaushal.[CBSE]\n       \n2013-2014 - Suboor Ahmed-Zoya Fatima.\n\n2014-2015- Ankit Singh - Syeda Zia Irshad.\n\n2015-2016- Pulkit Ingle - Meghna Dagaur\n\n2016-2017- Udit Ingle - Samya Khan\n\n2017-2018- HASHIR KHAN -ARSHMAH KHAN\n\nCaptain Yamuna House - HASHIR KHAN\n\nCaptain Ganga House-  ARSHMAH KHAN\n\n2018-2019- Akbar Mohammad Khan - Madiha Khanam\n\nCaptain Ganga House- Akbar Mohammad Khan\n\nCaptain Yamuna House -  Madiha Khanam\n\n==Alumni association==\nSaints' Circle is the alumni association for students.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{City of Bhopal}}\n\n[[Category:Schools in Bhopal]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1980]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:1980 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n|\nname = All Saints School, Bhopal|\nestablished = 1980|\ntype = [[Private school|Private]]|\nreligion =|\nhead_name = Headmaster|\nhead = |\ncity = Idgah Hills|\nstate = [[Bhopal]]|\ncountry = [[India]]|\ncampus = |\nenrollment = 2,500 total|\nfaculty = |\nclass = |\nratio = |\nathletics = |\ncolors = |\nmascot = |\nhomepage = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|23.265728|N|77.388821|E|display=inline}}\n|pushpin_map            = India Bhopal\n|pushpin_map_caption            = Location in Bhopal, India\n}}\n\n'''All Saints' School, Bhopal''' is an English medium school located at Idgah Hills [[Bhopal]], [[India]]. It was founded in 1980 by Iris Cynthia Philomene Auer. Miss Auer came to India after she retired as principal of a school in England. From seven pupils in July 1980, the strength has grown to over 2,500 pupils.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.asctbhopal.com/The_Foundress.html\n|title=All Saints ' College of Technology - Bhopal, India\n|publisher=www.asctbhopal.com\n|accessdate=2008-06-07\n|last=\n|first=\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080522050220/http://www.asctbhopal.com/The_Foundress.html\n|archivedate=22 May 2008\n|url-status=dead\n|df=dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> Miss Auer's was appointed Member of the Order of the British Empire ([[MBE]]) in the [[Elizabeth II|Queen]]'s Birthday Honours List in 1989.\nThe Principal and Chairperson of All Saints' School is Mrs. Kaiser Zaman (popularly known as \"Bia\") . She is an alumnus of [[University of Oxford]], B.Ed and was a student of Miss Auer. She founded All Saints' College Of technology  which is an engineering college of Bhopal M.P. It was visited by Former president late [[Dr. APJ Abdul Kalam]] in 2013.\n\n==Motto==\n''To the Highest''.\n\n==Houses==\nThe school has four houses: Vindhya, Himachal, Yamuna and Ganga. There is an annual House Competition with contests, including dancing, singing, [[elocution]], and drama.\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\nThere are dance classes, [[Karate]] lessons, [[cricket]], [[Association football|football]], [[throwball]], and other sports teams. Students participate in tournaments, the most notable being the yearly All Saints versus. [[Scindia School|Scinidia Boys School]], [[Gwalior]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2007}} The school has ten black belts in Karate. All Saints has a choir. One of the formal events is the annual farewell party thrown by the 11th grade in honour of the outgoing batch of students\n\n==Office bearers==\nThe [[Head Boy]] and Head Girl occupy the highest office in the school, followed by Coordinator, Head [[Prefect]], Prefects, and Sub-Prefects. There are other posts assigned to students like Sports Coordinator, Cultural Coordinator. The houses have house captains and vice captains.\nList of Head Boys and Head Girls so far is:\n\n1989-1990 - Ashish Jaiswal - Pushpa Hingorani (elected)\n\n1990-1991 - Ashish Jaiswal - Pushpa Hingorani (elected)\n\n1991-1992 - Ashish Jaiswal - Pushpa Hingorani nominated SCHOOL CAPTAIN\n\n1991-1992 - Vinay Shrivastave - Sheran Mendiratta (elected)\n\n1992-1993 - Neeraj Agarwal - Puja Rai\n\n1993-1994 - Deepak Choukse - Shveta Malik\n\n1994-1995 - Naved Masood - Ritu Induria\n\n1995-1996 - Abhay Raj Lodhi - Priyanka Pandey\n\n1996-1997 - Bir Singh Bagga - Sonia Kanjani\n\n1997-1998 - Shekhar Arora - Moushmi Nema\n\n1998-1999 - Amit Nathani - Sabina Sultan\n\n1999-2000 - Janab Choudhuri - Pragti Nagar. Himachal House Captain - Shadab Masood.\n\n2000-2001 - Adnan Abbasi - Payal Pisal\n\n2001-2002 - S M Farooq - Anita Kanjani\n\n2002-2003 - Rohit Singh - Mariyam Saulat\n\n2003-2004 - Md. Karam Abbasi - Jigayasa Balwani\n\n2004-2005 - Nandan Narula - Chani Singh.\n\n2005-2006 - Mohammad Sohaib Iqbal - Richa Manchanda\n\n2006-2007 - Mohd Arshil Muheet -Hena Agarwal\n\n2007-2008 -Rajat agarwal - Mehwish Sajid\n\n2008-2009- Syeda Anam anwar - Rohit Anandani\n\n2009-2010 - Jehangeer hussain- Priyanka Rohera\n\n2010-2011 - Zeeshan Siddiqui - Ayushi Paliwal.\n\n2011-2012 - Anchal Sahu - Anam Habeeb\n\n2013-2014 - Ravish Gurbani - Tasneem Safi [M.P BOARD]\n\n2013-2014 - Abhishek Upadhyay - Yoshita Kaushal.[CBSE]\n       \n2013-2014 - Suboor Ahmed-Zoya Fatima.\n\n2014-2015- Ankit Singh - Syeda Zia Irshad.\n\n2015-2016- Pulkit Ingle - Meghna Dagaur\n\n2016-2017- Udit Ingle - Samya Khan\n\n2017-2018- HASHIR KHAN -ARSHMAH KHAN\n\nCaptain Yamuna House - HASHIR KHAN\n\nCaptain Ganga House-  ARSHMAH KHAN\n\n2018-2019- Akbar Mohammad Khan - Madiha Khanam\n\nCaptain Ganga House- Akbar Mohammad Khan\n\nCaptain Yamuna House -  Madiha Khanam\n\n==Alumni association==\nSaints' Circle is the alumni association for students.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{City of Bhopal}}\n\n[[Category:Schools in Bhopal]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1980]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:1980 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "Paradoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "dab", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/All_Saints_School,_Bhopal"}
{"title_page": "National Autistic Society", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{primary sources|date=January 2016}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = The National Autistic Society\n| logo = File:National Autistic Society Logo 2018.png\n| Non-profit_type = Registered charity\n| founded_date = 1962\n| founder = {{longitem|Group of London-based parents}}\n| location = London, UK\n| origins = | key_people = \n| area_served = United Kingdom\n| focus = {{longitem|Supporting the rights and interests of all autistic people}}\n| method = \n| revenue = {{cn span|\u00a388 million|date=April 2018}}\n| revenue_year = 2012\u201313\n| endowment = \n| num_volunteers = \n| num_volunteers_year = \n| num_employees = {{cn span|3,630|date=April 2018}}\n| num_members = 20,000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autism.org.uk/shop/nas-membership.aspx|title=National Autistic Society membership|access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n| num_members_year = 2020\n| subsid = | owner =\n| Non-profit_slogan = {{longitem|\"Until everyone understands\"}}\n| homepage = {{URL|www.autism.org.uk}}\n| dissolved = | footnotes = \n}}\n{{Autism rights movement |orgs}}\n\nThe '''National Autistic Society''' ('''NAS''') is a British charity for [[autism|autistic people]]. The purpose of the organisation is to improve the lives of autistic people in the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n==Activities==\nIn addition to a wide range of adult and children's services for autistic people located across England, Scotland, Northern Ireland and Wales, the charity has an Autism Helpline open 5 days a week, a range of products for professionals working with autistics and a campaigning function.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/get-involved/jobs/office.aspx |title=Office-based opportunities - NAS |publisher=Autism.org.uk |accessdate=2017-06-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cypnow.co.uk/cyp/feature/1050719/childright-interview-sarah-lambert-head-of-policy-national-autistic-society |title=ChildRIGHT Interview: Sarah Lambert, head of policy, National Autistic Society &#124; Children & Young People Now |publisher=Cypnow.co.uk |date=2011-06-13 |accessdate=2017-06-27}}</ref> Sarah Lambert, the head of policy at the National Autistic society is a member of the [[All Party Parliamentary Group on Autism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.appga.org.uk/about-us/advisory-group.aspx|title=Advisory group - All Party Parliamentary Group on Autism|website=www.appga.org.uk|access-date=15 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126210003/http://www.appga.org.uk/about-us/advisory-group.aspx|archive-date=26 January 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the NAS consulted with numerous police agencies in developing [[identity card]] schemes designed to ensure a tolerable environment for autistic individuals during inquiries; participating agencies included the [[Wiltshire Police]], the [[Essex Police]], the [[Norfolk Constabulary]], the [[Suffolk Constabulary]], and the [[Cumbria Constabulary]].<ref>[http://www.wiltshire.police.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2895 Autism Alert Card] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709102008/http://www.wiltshire.police.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2895 |date=9 July 2011 }}, Wiltshire Police, Retrieved 6 May 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.autism-anglia.org.uk/services/alert_card.htm Autism Anglia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810003350/http://www.autism-anglia.org.uk/services/alert_card.htm |date=10 August 2011 }}, Retrieved 6 May 2011</ref>\n\nThe NAS is also a founding member of [[Autism-Europe aisbl|Autism-Europe]], an umbrella organisation bringing together 80 autism organisations from over 30 European countries. As a member of Autism-Europe, the NAS collaborates and shares examples of learning and good practice with other associations throughout the continent.\n\nThe current Chief Executive is Caroline Stevens. She took over from Mark Lever in 2019, after being Chief Executive at Kids for six years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autism.org.uk/get-involved/media-centre/news/2019-06-28-new-ceo-announced.aspx|title=National Autistic Society appoints new Chief Executive (28 June 2019) - National Autistic Society|website=www.autism.org.uk|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\nThe NAS is organised into four regions and currently run by an elected Board of Trustees and an elected Council through a Strategic Management Group. The president of the NAS is [[Jane Asher]] and the patron is [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex|The Countess of Wessex]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/structure |title=Our structure and people |publisher=National Autistic Society|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref> The NAS is funded through UK government grants and voluntary contributions.  {{cn span|In 2012\u20132013, it employed around 3,000 people and spent \u00a385.2 million directly on its charitable activities, out of \u00a391.2 million in expenditures (approx 93.4%).|date=April 2018}}\n\nThe National Autistic Society has the following names registered with the Charity Commission:\n*The National Autistic Society\n*National Society for Autistic Children\n*Autism UK\n*Action for Autism\n\n==List of NAS Schools and facilities==\nThe NAS manages a number of residential schools in the United Kingdom.\n\n*Anderson School in [[Chigwell]], [[Essex]] for children between 11 and 19 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autism.org.uk/services/nas-schools/anderson.aspx |title=NAS Anderson School, Chigwell |publisher=National Autistic Society |accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n*Broomhayes School & Children's Centre (alternatively Kingsley House) near [[Bideford]], [[Devon]], which has now been turned into an adult residential facility since the school got close to reaching its 30th Anniversary.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.autism.org.uk/~/media/nas/documents/about%20us/nas-agm-2014-minutes.ashx | title=The National Autistic Society Minutes of the Annual General Meeting And Family Day | date=22 November 2014 | accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n*Church Lawton School in Church Lawton, Stoke-on-Trent<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/churchlawton|title=Church Lawton School - The National Autistic Society -  NAS|publisher=National Autistic Society}}</ref>\n*Daldorch House School in [[Ayrshire]], Scotland for children 5\u201318 years old{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n*Helen Allison School near [[Meopham]], [[Kent]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/helenallison|title=Helen Allison School - The National Autistic Society -  NAS|publisher=National Autistic Society}}</ref>\n*Robert Ogden School in Thurnscoe near [[Rotherham]], [[Yorkshire]] for pupils/students aged between 5 and 19 years old<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/robertogden|title=Robert Ogden School - The National Autistic Society -  NAS|publisher=National Autistic Society}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/inspection-reports/find-inspection-report/provider/ELS/106965|title=The Robert Ogden School|publisher=OFSTED}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/inspection-reports/find-inspection-report/provider/CARE/SC032154|title=SC032154|publisher=OFSTED}}</ref>\n*Radlett Lodge School in [[Radlett]], [[Hertfordshire]] for pupils/students aged between 4 and 19 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/RadlettLodge|title=Radlett Lodge School - The National Autistic Society -  NAS|publisher=National Autistic Society}}</ref>\n*Sybil Elgar School in [[Southall]], [[Ealing]] and [[Acton, London|Acton]], [[West London]] for students aged between 4 and 22 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/SybilElgar|title=Sybil Elgar School - The National Autistic Society -  NAS|publisher=National Autistic Society}}</ref>\n*Thames Valley School in [[Reading, Berkshire]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/thamesvalley|title=Thames Valley School - The National Autistic Society -  NAS|publisher=National Autistic Society}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nFounded in 1962 as the Autistic Children's Aid Society of North London, {{Citation needed|date=December 2018}} it has around 18,000 members. In 1963 Gerald Gasson, a parent and member of the Executive Committee, designed the primary symbol for autism: a puzzle piece with a picture of a crying child inside of it, which was first used as logo by the NAS itself.<ref>{{cite web  |title=National Autistic Society Timeline - 1963. First NAS logo developed |url=http://www.tiki-toki.com/timeline/entry/21729/Our-story-so-far/#vars!panel=193670! |work=tiki-toki.com |accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=[[Roy Richard Grinker|Grinker, Roy Richard]] |author2=Mandell, David |title=Notes on a puzzle piece |date=1 June 2015 |journal=[[Autism (journal)|Autism]] |publisher=[[SAGE Publications]] |volume=19 |issue=6 |pages=643\u2013645|doi=10.1177/1362361315589293 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Debra |last=Muzikar |title=The Autism Puzzle Piece: A symbol that\u2019s going to stay or go? |url=http://the-art-of-autism.com/the-autism-puzzle-piece-a-symbol-of-what/ |website=The Art of Autism |date=20 April 2015 |accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref> The National Autistic Society originated from the foundation of the Autistic Children's Aid Society of North London on 23 January 1962 by parents of autistic children living in the area, with the assistance of a member from The [[Cerebral Palsy|Spastic]]s Society (later [[Scope (charity)|Scope]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nas.org.uk/nas/jsp/polopoly.jsp?a=2183&d=364|title=Perspectives on a puzzle piece|last=Allison|first=Helen Green|date=June 1997|publisher=National Autistic Society|accessdate=1 July 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20040225071530/http://www.nas.org.uk/nas/jsp/polopoly.jsp?a=2183&d=364|archivedate=25 February 2004}}</ref> [[Sybil Elgar]] was asked by the parents to be their first teacher for their children.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Story So Far|url=http://www.tiki-toki.com/timeline/entry/21729/Our-story-so-far/#vars!date=1951-09-02_06:02:12!|publisher=National Autistic Society|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref> The Society school for Autistic Children was established and later renamed as the Sybil Elgar School with her as the first principal. The current name was adopted in 1975 when the charity extended its interest to the whole of the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Year !! Association !! Category !! Nominee(s) !! Result !! Refs\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|2017 || rowspan=\"1\"| Diversity in Media Awards || Marketing Campaign of the Year || ''Make it Stop'' || {{nom}} ||<ref>{{cite web |url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:www.diversityinmediaawards.com/2017-shortlisted-creative.html+%22The+National+Autistic+Society%22%22Make+It+Stop%22 |title=2017 Shortlisted Creative - Diversity In Media Awards |accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xHHwZJX67-M |title=Make It Stop |publisher=The National Autistic Society |date=28 March 2017 |accessdate=17 April 2018 |via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|National Autistic Society}}\n*[http://www.autism.org.uk Official website]\n\n{{Autism resources}}\n{{Pervasive developmental disorders}}\n\n[[Category:Health charities in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Autism-related organisations in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1962 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1962]]\n[[Category:Charities for disabled people based in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{primary sources|date=January 2016}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = The National Autistic Society\n| logo = File:National Autistic Society Logo 2018.png\n| Non-profit_type = Registered charity\n| founded_date = 1962\n| founder = {{longitem|Group of London-based parents}}\n| location = London, UK\n| origins = | key_people = \n| area_served = United Kingdom\n| focus = {{longitem|Supporting the rights and interests of all autistic people}}\n| method = \n| revenue = {{cn span|\u00a388 million|date=April 2018}}\n| revenue_year = 2012\u201313\n| endowment = \n| num_volunteers = \n| num_volunteers_year = \n| num_employees = {{cn span|3,630|date=April 2018}}\n| num_members = 20,000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autism.org.uk/shop/nas-membership.aspx|title=National Autistic Society membership|access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n| num_members_year = 2020\n| subsid = | owner =\n| Non-profit_slogan = {{longitem|\"Until everyone understands\"}}\n| homepage = {{URL|www.autism.org.uk}}\n| dissolved = | footnotes = \n}}\n{{Autism rights movement |orgs}}\n\nThe '''National Autistic Society''' ('''NAS''') is a British charity for [[autism|autistic people]]. The purpose of the organisation is to improve the lives of autistic people in the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n==Activities==\nIn addition to a wide range of adult and children's services for autistic people located across England, Scotland, Northern Ireland and Wales, the charity has an Autism Helpline open 5 days a week, a range of products for professionals working with autistics and a campaigning function.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/get-involved/jobs/office.aspx |title=Office-based opportunities - NAS |publisher=Autism.org.uk |accessdate=2017-06-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cypnow.co.uk/cyp/feature/1050719/childright-interview-sarah-lambert-head-of-policy-national-autistic-society |title=ChildRIGHT Interview: Sarah Lambert, head of policy, National Autistic Society &#124; Children & Young People Now |publisher=Cypnow.co.uk |date=2011-06-13 |accessdate=2017-06-27}}</ref> Sarah Lambert, the head of policy at the National Autistic society is a member of the [[All Party Parliamentary Group on Autism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.appga.org.uk/about-us/advisory-group.aspx|title=Advisory group - All Party Parliamentary Group on Autism|website=www.appga.org.uk|access-date=15 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126210003/http://www.appga.org.uk/about-us/advisory-group.aspx|archive-date=26 January 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the NAS consulted with numerous police agencies in developing [[identity card]] schemes designed to ensure a tolerable environment for autistic individuals during inquiries; participating agencies included the [[Wiltshire Police]], the [[Essex Police]], the [[Norfolk Constabulary]], the [[Suffolk Constabulary]], and the [[Cumbria Constabulary]].<ref>[http://www.wiltshire.police.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2895 Autism Alert Card] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709102008/http://www.wiltshire.police.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2895 |date=9 July 2011 }}, Wiltshire Police, Retrieved 6 May 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.autism-anglia.org.uk/services/alert_card.htm Autism Anglia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810003350/http://www.autism-anglia.org.uk/services/alert_card.htm |date=10 August 2011 }}, Retrieved 6 May 2011</ref>\n\nThe NAS is also a founding member of [[Autism-Europe aisbl|Autism-Europe]], an umbrella organisation bringing together 80 autism organisations from over 30 European countries. As a member of Autism-Europe the NAS collaborates and shares examples of learning and good practice with other associations throughout the continent.\n\nThe current Chief Executive is Caroline Stevens. She took over from Mark Lever in 2019, after being Chief Executive at Kids for six years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autism.org.uk/get-involved/media-centre/news/2019-06-28-new-ceo-announced.aspx|title=National Autistic Society appoints new Chief Executive (28 June 2019) - National Autistic Society|website=www.autism.org.uk|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\nThe NAS is organised into four regions and currently run by an elected Board of Trustees and an elected Council through a Strategic Management Group. The president of the NAS is [[Jane Asher]] and the patron is [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex|The Countess of Wessex]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/structure |title=Our structure and people |publisher=National Autistic Society|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref> The NAS is funded through UK government grants and voluntary contributions.  {{cn span|In 2012\u20132013, it employed around 3,000 people and spent \u00a385.2 million directly on its charitable activities, out of \u00a391.2 million in expenditures (approx 93.4%).|date=April 2018}}\n\nThe National Autistic Society has the following names registered with the Charity Commission:\n*The National Autistic Society\n*National Society for Autistic Children\n*Autism UK\n*Action for Autism\n\n==List of NAS Schools and facilities==\nThe NAS manages a number of residential schools in the United Kingdom.\n\n*Anderson School in [[Chigwell]], [[Essex]] for children between 11 and 19 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autism.org.uk/services/nas-schools/anderson.aspx |title=NAS Anderson School, Chigwell |publisher=National Autistic Society |accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n*Broomhayes School & Children's Centre (alternatively Kingsley House) near [[Bideford]], [[Devon]], which has now been turned into an adult residential facility since the school got close to reaching its 30th Anniversary.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.autism.org.uk/~/media/nas/documents/about%20us/nas-agm-2014-minutes.ashx | title=The National Autistic Society Minutes of the Annual General Meeting And Family Day | date=22 November 2014 | accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n*Church Lawton School in Church Lawton, Stoke-on-Trent<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/churchlawton|title=Church Lawton School - The National Autistic Society -  NAS|publisher=National Autistic Society}}</ref>\n*Daldorch House School in [[Ayrshire]], Scotland for children 5\u201318 years old{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n*Helen Allison School near [[Meopham]], [[Kent]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/helenallison|title=Helen Allison School - The National Autistic Society -  NAS|publisher=National Autistic Society}}</ref>\n*Robert Ogden School in Thurnscoe near [[Rotherham]], [[Yorkshire]] for pupils/students aged between 5 and 19 years old<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/robertogden|title=Robert Ogden School - The National Autistic Society -  NAS|publisher=National Autistic Society}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/inspection-reports/find-inspection-report/provider/ELS/106965|title=The Robert Ogden School|publisher=OFSTED}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/inspection-reports/find-inspection-report/provider/CARE/SC032154|title=SC032154|publisher=OFSTED}}</ref>\n*Radlett Lodge School in [[Radlett]], [[Hertfordshire]] for pupils/students aged between 4 and 19 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/RadlettLodge|title=Radlett Lodge School - The National Autistic Society -  NAS|publisher=National Autistic Society}}</ref>\n*Sybil Elgar School in [[Southall]], [[Ealing]] and [[Acton, London|Acton]], [[West London]] for students aged between 4 and 22 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/SybilElgar|title=Sybil Elgar School - The National Autistic Society -  NAS|publisher=National Autistic Society}}</ref>\n*Thames Valley School in [[Reading, Berkshire]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autism.org.uk/thamesvalley|title=Thames Valley School - The National Autistic Society -  NAS|publisher=National Autistic Society}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nFounded in 1962 as the Autistic Children's Aid Society of North London, {{Citation needed|date=December 2018}} it has around 18,000 members. In 1963 Gerald Gasson, a parent and member of the Executive Committee, designed the primary symbol for autism: a puzzle piece with a picture of a crying child inside of it, which was first used as logo by the NAS itself.<ref>{{cite web  |title=National Autistic Society Timeline - 1963. First NAS logo developed |url=http://www.tiki-toki.com/timeline/entry/21729/Our-story-so-far/#vars!panel=193670! |work=tiki-toki.com |accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=[[Roy Richard Grinker|Grinker, Roy Richard]] |author2=Mandell, David |title=Notes on a puzzle piece |date=1 June 2015 |journal=[[Autism (journal)|Autism]] |publisher=[[SAGE Publications]] |volume=19 |issue=6 |pages=643\u2013645|doi=10.1177/1362361315589293 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Debra |last=Muzikar |title=The Autism Puzzle Piece: A symbol that\u2019s going to stay or go? |url=http://the-art-of-autism.com/the-autism-puzzle-piece-a-symbol-of-what/ |website=The Art of Autism |date=20 April 2015 |accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref> The National Autistic Society originated from the foundation of the Autistic Children's Aid Society of North London on 23 January 1962 by parents of autistic children living in the area, with the assistance of a member from The [[Cerebral Palsy|Spastic]]s Society (later [[Scope (charity)|Scope]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nas.org.uk/nas/jsp/polopoly.jsp?a=2183&d=364|title=Perspectives on a puzzle piece|last=Allison|first=Helen Green|date=June 1997|publisher=National Autistic Society|accessdate=1 July 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20040225071530/http://www.nas.org.uk/nas/jsp/polopoly.jsp?a=2183&d=364|archivedate=25 February 2004}}</ref> [[Sybil Elgar]] was asked by the parents to be their first teacher for their children.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Story So Far|url=http://www.tiki-toki.com/timeline/entry/21729/Our-story-so-far/#vars!date=1951-09-02_06:02:12!|publisher=National Autistic Society|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref> The Society school for Autistic Children was established and later renamed as the Sybil Elgar School with her as the first principal. The current name was adopted in 1975 when the charity extended its interest to the whole of the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Year !! Association !! Category !! Nominee(s) !! Result !! Refs\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|2017 || rowspan=\"1\"| Diversity in Media Awards || Marketing Campaign of the Year || ''Make it Stop'' || {{nom}} ||<ref>{{cite web |url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:www.diversityinmediaawards.com/2017-shortlisted-creative.html+%22The+National+Autistic+Society%22%22Make+It+Stop%22 |title=2017 Shortlisted Creative - Diversity In Media Awards |accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xHHwZJX67-M |title=Make It Stop |publisher=The National Autistic Society |date=28 March 2017 |accessdate=17 April 2018 |via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|National Autistic Society}}\n*[http://www.autism.org.uk Official website]\n\n{{Autism resources}}\n{{Pervasive developmental disorders}}\n\n[[Category:Health charities in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Autism-related organisations in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1962 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1962]]\n[[Category:Charities for disabled people based in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Pkbwcgs", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eActivities:Added comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Autistic_Society"}
{"title_page": "Charity Anderson", "text_new": "{{Infobox dancer\n| name          = Charity Anderson\n| image         = \n| alt\t        = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|2000}}\n| birth_place   = [[Springville, Utah]], US\n| death_date    = <!-- {{death date and age|deathyear|mm|dd|birthyear|mm|dd}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| residence     = Springville, Utah\n| nationality   = United States \n| citizenship   = \n| education     = [[Springville High School (Utah)|Springville High School]]\n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| home_town     = \n| height        = \n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| website       = <!-- {{URL|website}} -->\n| current_group = \n| former_groups = \n| dances        = [[contemporary dance|Contemporary]], [[Acro dance|acro]], [[Ballroom dance|ballroom]]\n| module        = \n}}\n'''Charity Anderson''' (born 2000)<ref name=qa/> is an American dancer. She specializes in [[contemporary dance|contemporary]] and [[acro dance]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.utahdanceacademy.com/charity-anderson.html|title=Charity Anderson|publisher=Utah Dance Academy|year=2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> She and partner Andres Pe\u00f1ate competed on [[World of Dance (season 2)|season 2 of ''World of Dance'']] in 2018, becoming the first in the show's history to score a perfect 100 on a routine.\n\n==Early life and family==\nCharity Anderson was born and raised in [[Springville, Utah]].<ref name=landon/> She is the daughter of Wylie and Tresa Anderson and has nine brothers and sisters.<ref name=tresa/> She is a [[Mormons|Mormon]].<ref name=qa>{{cite web |url= https://www.deseret.com/2018/9/13/20653468/q-a-utah-world-of-dance-duo-on-their-perfect-score-and-how-they-got-to-the-finals-on-a-broken-toe#springville-dance-duo-charity-and-andres-compete-on-the-world-of-dance-final-round-wednesday-night-the-18-year-old-dancers-walked-away-with-a-combined-average-score-of-94-3-earning-third-place-in-the-intense-competition-for-the-1-million-prize|title= Q&A: Utah 'World of Dance' duo on their perfect score and how they got to the finals on a broken toe|first=Lottie Elizabeth|last=Johnson|date=September 13, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=[[Deseret News]]}}</ref> Her mother studied dance at [[Brigham Young University]] and opened a small dance studio in her home in 1996.<ref name=tresa>{{cite web |url=https://www.heraldextra.com/entertainment/special/talent/drama/charisma-dance-studio-a-launching-pad-for-some-of-utah/article_fed8b56a-b91e-11e3-a7e4-0019bb2963f4.html|title=Charisma Dance Studio: A launching pad for some of Utah Valley's top talent|first=Kari|last=Kenner|date=April 2, 2014|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=[[Daily Herald (Utah)|Daily Herald]]}}</ref> As of 2014, her mother's Charisma Dance Studio employed 14 instructors and had 300 students.<ref name=tresa/> Charity and five of her 10 siblings dance competitively.<ref name=tresa/>\n\nCharity graduated from [[Springville High School (Utah)|Springville High School]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://utahvalley360.com/2018/06/06/utah-county-teens-flip-their-way-to-second-round-of-world-of-dance/|title=Utah County Teens Flip Their Way To Second Round On 'World Of Dance'|first=Rebecca|last=Lane|date=June 6, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Utah Valley 360}}</ref>\n\n==Dancing career==\nFrom the ages of 8 to 12, Anderson competed in [[ballroom dance]] with same-age partner Andres Pe\u00f1ate; the pair won the title of National Preteen Champions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.heraldextra.com/entertainment/television/utah-county-favorites-who-tore-up-the-floor-and-rocked-the-nation-on-competitive-dance/collection_b3dc0bc8-a70a-11e8-aae4-d70d0d53df4d.html#2 |title=Utah county favorites who tore up the floor and rocked the nation on competitive dance shows|first=Kari|last=Kenner|date=August 30, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Daily Herald}}</ref> She has also danced competitively with her older brother Landon; they won both the 2019<ref name=landon>{{cite web |url=https://www.inspiremore.com/siblings-win-dance-competition/|title=Sibling Dancers Win National Competition After Jaw-Dropping Cabaret Performance|first=Beverly L. |last=Jenkins|date=September 15, 2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Inspire More}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://dancebeat.com/m-blogs-en/item/1725-usamchamps2019 |title= US National Amateur Championships 2019 - From Provo, UT|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Dance Beat}}</ref> and 2020 United States National Amateur Cabaret Championships. She trains at the Center Stage dance studio in [[Orem, Utah|Orem]].<ref name=michelle/>\n\n===''World of Dance''===\n{{main|World of Dance (season 2)}}\n{{Quote box\n |width=225px\n |align=right\n |quoted=true\n |bgcolor= \n |salign=right\n |quote= [I]t was our own choreography and we had to come up with something fresh and new \u2014 something that people hadn't seen before.\n |source=\u2013Anderson on Charity & Andre's dance routines for ''[[World of Dance (season 2)|World of Dance]]''<ref name=qa/>\n}}\nAfter watching season 1 of ''[[World of Dance (season 1)|World of Dance]]'', Anderson asked Pe\u00f1ate, who also trains at her dance studio, to partner with her in [[contemporary dance]] for season 2.<ref name=qa/><ref name=michelle/> It would be their last opportunity to compete in the junior division, as both were still 17.<ref name=network>{{cite web |last1=Burtt |first1=Kristyn |title=How Charity & Andr\u00e9s Strategized Their 'World Of Dance' Performances |url=https://www.dancenetwork.tv/Catalog/Post/452/how-charity-andrs-strategized-their-world-of-dance-performances |website=Dance Network |accessdate=21 April 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421075943/https://www.dancenetwork.tv/Catalog/Post/452/how-charity-andrs-strategized-their-world-of-dance-performances |archivedate=21 April 2020 |date=8 February 2018}}</ref> The pair, billed as Charity & Andres, choreographed their own routines, taking advantage of each other's athleticism and knowledge of \"dance tricks\".<ref name=network/><ref name=sarah>{{cite web |url= https://www.heraldextra.com/entertainment/television/utah-county-acts-to-compete-on-nbc-s-world-of/article_c5585c4c-98c9-5253-8144-ac1822d9abf5.html|title=3 Utah County acts to compete on NBC's 'World of Dance' |first=Sarah|last=Harris|date=May 28, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Daily Herald}}</ref> They scored 95.3 in the Qualifying round<ref name=michelle>{{cite web |url= https://www.deseret.com/2018/6/25/20647659/11-utah-teens-competing-for-1-million-on-world-of-dance |title=11 Utah teens competing for $1 million on 'World of Dance' |first=Michelle Garrett|last=Bulsiewicz|date=June 25, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Deseret News}}</ref> and received a perfect 100 in the second Duels round.<ref name=perfect>{{cite web |url= https://www.deseret.com/2018/8/2/20650324/utah-dance-duo-make-history-on-nbc-s-world-of-dance-with-perfect-score#world-of-dance-duels-episode-210-pictured-charity-andres-photo-by-justin-lubin-nbc |title= Utah dance duo make history on NBC's 'World of Dance' with perfect score|first=Lottie Elizabeth|last=Johnson|date=August 2, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Deseret News}}</ref> This was the first perfect score in the show's history.<ref name=perfect/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.heraldextra.com/entertainment/television/springville-world-of-dance-duo-earns-first-ever-perfect-score/article_de708817-6019-5177-ad8e-d4ce557265d1.html|title=Springville 'World of Dance' duo earns first-ever perfect score|first=Sarah|last=Harris|date=August 2, 2018|work=Daily Herald}}</ref> Their dance, set to the rock hit \"[[Way Down We Go]]\" by [[Kaleo (band)|Kaleo]], included Anderson performing a blind jump onto Penate's back.<ref name=perfect/> The pair won the junior division with a score of 93, though Anderson had broken her toe during practice a few days before that dance.<ref name=qa/><ref name=lds>{{cite web |url=https://www.ldsliving.com/2-Latter-day-Saint-Dancers-Win-Junior-Division-on-World-of-Dance-Why-That-Almost-Didn-t-Happen/s/89215|title=Latter-day Saint Dancers Win on \"World of Dance\" + Why That Almost Didn't Happen|first=Katie|last=Lambert|date=September 6, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=[[Deseret Book Company|LDS Living]]}}</ref> They finished third in the finals with a combined average score of 94.3.<ref name=qa/>\n\nCharity & Andres planned to participate in the ''World of Dance'' fall tour in 2018.<ref name=network/> In April 2019, Anderson was one of seven dancers selected to back [[Derek Hough]] on his first solo tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/radiotvtalk/interview-derek-hough-dancing-with-the-stars-brings-high-energy-dance-fox-theatre-april/9RQ7ldUzrbrFxpCFKoIRxM/|title=Interview: Derek Hough  ('Dancing With the Stars') brings high energy dance to Fox Theatre April 12|first=Rodney|last=Ho|date=April 4, 2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]}}</ref> In August 2019, Charity & Andres choreographed and performed a special \"farewell dance\" for [[The Piano Guys]]' cover of [[Lewis Capaldi]]'s \"[[Someone You Loved]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-piano-guys-premiere-new-rendition-of-lewis-capaldis-hit-single-someone-you-loved-300907801.html|title=THE PIANO GUYS Premiere New Rendition of Lewis Capaldi's Hit Single \"Someone You Loved\" (press release)|author=Sony Masterworks|date=August 27, 2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> As of April 20, 2020, this video had received 8 million views.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qMG1BXo8Asg|title= Someone You Loved (Piano/Cello) Charity & Andres Farewell Dance \u2013 The Piano Guys (video)|work=YouTube|date=August 27, 2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Charity}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dancers from Utah]]\n[[Category:People from Springville, Utah]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Utah]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox dancer\n| name          = Charity Anderson\n| image         = \n| alt\t        = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|2000}}\n| birth_place   = [[Springville, Utah]], US\n| death_date    = <!-- {{death date and age|deathyear|mm|dd|birthyear|mm|dd}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| residence     = Springville, Utah\n| nationality   = United States \n| citizenship   = \n| education     = [[Springville High School (Utah)|Springville High School]]\n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| home_town     = \n| height        = \n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| website       = <!-- {{URL|website}} -->\n| current_group = \n| former_groups = \n| dances        = [[contemporary dance|Contemporary]], [[Acro dance|acro]], [[Ballroom dance|ballroom]]\n| module        = \n}}\n'''Charity Anderson''' (born 2000)<ref name=qa/> is an American dancer. She specializes in [[contemporary dance|contemporary]] and [[acro dance]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.utahdanceacademy.com/charity-anderson.html|title=Charity Anderson|publisher=Utah Dance Academy|year=2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> She and partner Andres Pe\u00f1ate competed on [[World of Dance (season 2)|season 2 of ''World of Dance'']] in 2018, becoming the first in the show's history to score a perfect 100 on a routine.\n\n==Early life and family==\nCharity Anderson was born and raised in [[Springville, Utah]].<ref name=landon/> She is the daughter of Wylie and Tresa Anderson and has nine brothers and sisters.<ref name=tresa/> She is a [[Mormons|Mormon]].<ref name=qa>{{cite web |url= https://www.deseret.com/2018/9/13/20653468/q-a-utah-world-of-dance-duo-on-their-perfect-score-and-how-they-got-to-the-finals-on-a-broken-toe#springville-dance-duo-charity-and-andres-compete-on-the-world-of-dance-final-round-wednesday-night-the-18-year-old-dancers-walked-away-with-a-combined-average-score-of-94-3-earning-third-place-in-the-intense-competition-for-the-1-million-prize|title= Q&A: Utah 'World of Dance' duo on their perfect score and how they got to the finals on a broken toe|first=Lottie Elizabeth|last=Johnson|date=September 13, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=[[Deseret News]]}}</ref> Her mother studied dance at [[Brigham Young University]] and opened a small dance studio in her home in 1996.<ref name=tresa>{{cite web |url=https://www.heraldextra.com/entertainment/special/talent/drama/charisma-dance-studio-a-launching-pad-for-some-of-utah/article_fed8b56a-b91e-11e3-a7e4-0019bb2963f4.html|title=Charisma Dance Studio: A launching pad for some of Utah Valley's top talent|first=Kari|last=Kenner|date=April 2, 2014|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=[[Daily Herald (Utah)|Daily Herald]]}}</ref> As of 2014, her mother's Charisma Dance Studio employed 14 instructors and had 300 students.<ref name=tresa/> Charity and five of her 10 siblings also dance competitively.<ref name=tresa/>\n\nCharity graduated from [[Springville High School (Utah)|Springville High School]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://utahvalley360.com/2018/06/06/utah-county-teens-flip-their-way-to-second-round-of-world-of-dance/|title=Utah County Teens Flip Their Way To Second Round On 'World Of Dance'|first=Rebecca|last=Lane|date=June 6, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Utah Valley 360}}</ref> \n\n==Dancing career==\nFrom the ages of 8 to 12, Anderson competed in [[ballroom dance]] with same-age partner Andres Pe\u00f1ate; the pair won the title of National Preteen Champions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.heraldextra.com/entertainment/television/utah-county-favorites-who-tore-up-the-floor-and-rocked-the-nation-on-competitive-dance/collection_b3dc0bc8-a70a-11e8-aae4-d70d0d53df4d.html#2 |title=Utah county favorites who tore up the floor and rocked the nation on competitive dance shows|first=Kari|last=Kenner|date=August 30, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Daily Herald}}</ref> She has also danced competitively with her older brother Landon; they won both the 2019<ref name=landon>{{cite web |url=https://www.inspiremore.com/siblings-win-dance-competition/|title=Sibling Dancers Win National Competition After Jaw-Dropping Cabaret Performance|first=Beverly L. |last=Jenkins|date=September 15, 2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Inspire More}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://dancebeat.com/m-blogs-en/item/1725-usamchamps2019 |title= US National Amateur Championships 2019 - From Provo, UT|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Dance Beat}}</ref> and 2020 United States National Amateur Cabaret Championships. She trains at the Center Stage dance studio in [[Orem, Utah|Orem]].<ref name=michelle/>\n\n===''World of Dance''===\n{{main|World of Dance (season 2)}}\n{{Quote box\n |width=225px\n |align=right\n |quoted=true\n |bgcolor= \n |salign=right\n |quote= [I]t was our own choreography and we had to come up with something fresh and new \u2014 something that people hadn't seen before.\n |source=\u2013Anderson on Charity & Andre's dance routines for ''[[World of Dance (season 2)|World of Dance]]''<ref name=qa/>\n}}\nAfter watching season 1 of ''[[World of Dance (season 1)|World of Dance]]'', Anderson asked Pe\u00f1ate, who also trains at her dance studio, to partner with her in [[contemporary dance]] for season 2.<ref name=qa/><ref name=michelle/> It would be their last opportunity to compete in the junior division, as both were still 17.<ref name=network>{{cite web |last1=Burtt |first1=Kristyn |title=How Charity & Andr\u00e9s Strategized Their 'World Of Dance' Performances |url=https://www.dancenetwork.tv/Catalog/Post/452/how-charity-andrs-strategized-their-world-of-dance-performances |website=Dance Network |accessdate=21 April 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421075943/https://www.dancenetwork.tv/Catalog/Post/452/how-charity-andrs-strategized-their-world-of-dance-performances |archivedate=21 April 2020 |date=8 February 2018}}</ref> The pair, billed as Charity & Andres, choreographed their own routines, taking advantage of each other's athleticism and knowledge of \"dance tricks\".<ref name=network/><ref name=sarah>{{cite web |url= https://www.heraldextra.com/entertainment/television/utah-county-acts-to-compete-on-nbc-s-world-of/article_c5585c4c-98c9-5253-8144-ac1822d9abf5.html|title=3 Utah County acts to compete on NBC's 'World of Dance' |first=Sarah|last=Harris|date=May 28, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Daily Herald}}</ref> They scored 95.3 in the Qualifying round<ref name=michelle>{{cite web |url= https://www.deseret.com/2018/6/25/20647659/11-utah-teens-competing-for-1-million-on-world-of-dance |title=11 Utah teens competing for $1 million on 'World of Dance' |first=Michelle Garrett|last=Bulsiewicz|date=June 25, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Deseret News}}</ref> and received a perfect 100 in the second Duels round.<ref name=perfect>{{cite web |url= https://www.deseret.com/2018/8/2/20650324/utah-dance-duo-make-history-on-nbc-s-world-of-dance-with-perfect-score#world-of-dance-duels-episode-210-pictured-charity-andres-photo-by-justin-lubin-nbc |title= Utah dance duo make history on NBC's 'World of Dance' with perfect score|first=Lottie Elizabeth|last=Johnson|date=August 2, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=Deseret News}}</ref> This was the first perfect score in the show's history.<ref name=perfect/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.heraldextra.com/entertainment/television/springville-world-of-dance-duo-earns-first-ever-perfect-score/article_de708817-6019-5177-ad8e-d4ce557265d1.html|title=Springville 'World of Dance' duo earns first-ever perfect score|first=Sarah|last=Harris|date=August 2, 2018|work=Daily Herald}}</ref> Their dance, set to the rock hit \"[[Way Down We Go]]\" by [[Kaleo (band)|Kaleo]], included Anderson performing a blind jump onto Penate's back.<ref name=perfect/> The pair won the junior division with a score of 93, though Anderson had broken her toe during practice a few days before that dance.<ref name=qa/><ref name=lds>{{cite web |url=https://www.ldsliving.com/2-Latter-day-Saint-Dancers-Win-Junior-Division-on-World-of-Dance-Why-That-Almost-Didn-t-Happen/s/89215|title=Latter-day Saint Dancers Win on \"World of Dance\" + Why That Almost Didn't Happen|first=Katie|last=Lambert|date=September 6, 2018|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=[[Deseret Book Company|LDS Living]]}}</ref> They finished third in the finals with a combined average score of 94.3.<ref name=qa/>\n\nCharity & Andres planned to participate in the ''World of Dance'' fall tour in 2018.<ref name=network/> In April 2019, Anderson was one of seven dancers selected to back [[Derek Hough]] on his first solo tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/radiotvtalk/interview-derek-hough-dancing-with-the-stars-brings-high-energy-dance-fox-theatre-april/9RQ7ldUzrbrFxpCFKoIRxM/|title=Interview: Derek Hough  ('Dancing With the Stars') brings high energy dance to Fox Theatre April 12|first=Rodney|last=Ho|date=April 4, 2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]}}</ref> In August 2019, Charity & Andres choreographed and performed a special \"farewell dance\" for [[The Piano Guys]]' cover of [[Lewis Capaldi]]'s \"[[Someone You Loved]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-piano-guys-premiere-new-rendition-of-lewis-capaldis-hit-single-someone-you-loved-300907801.html|title=THE PIANO GUYS Premiere New Rendition of Lewis Capaldi's Hit Single \"Someone You Loved\" (press release)|author=Sony Masterworks|date=August 27, 2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> As of April 20, 2020, this video had received 8 million views.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qMG1BXo8Asg|title= Someone You Loved (Piano/Cello) Charity & Andres Farewell Dance \u2013 The Piano Guys (video)|work=YouTube|date=August 27, 2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Charity}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dancers from Utah]]\n[[Category:People from Springville, Utah]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Utah]]\n", "name_user": "Yoninah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and family", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charity_Anderson"}
{"title_page": "Cesc F\u00e0bregas", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Spanish name|F\u00e0bregas|Soler}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Cesc F\u00e0bregas\n| image = Cesc Fabregas vs Maccabi Tel-Aviv, Sep 2015.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = F\u00e0bregas playing for [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in 2015\n| fullname = Francesc F\u00e0bregas Soler<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/612828 |title=Updated squads for 2017/18 Premier League confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=2 February 2018 |accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|5|4|df=y}}<ref name=\"FC Barcelona Player Profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/staff/players/Fabregas/sheet|title=Player Profile: Cesc F\u00e0bregas|publisher=FC Barcelona|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115080837/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/staff/players/Fabregas/sheet|archivedate=15 January 2013}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Arenys de Mar]], Spain\n| height = 1.79 m<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/teams/first-team/cesc-fabregas?pageTab=biography |title=Cesc Fabregas |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |accessdate=5 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005203153/https://www.chelseafc.com/en/teams/first-team/cesc-fabregas?pageTab=biography |archive-date=5 October 2018 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]\n| clubnumber = 4\n| youthyears1 = 1995\u20131997\n| youthclubs1 = [[CE Matar\u00f3|Matar\u00f3]]\n| youthyears2 = 1997\u20132003\n| youthclubs2 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| youthyears3 = 2003\n| youthclubs3 = [[Arsenal F.C. Reserves and Academy|Arsenal]]\n| years1 = 2003\u20132011\n| clubs1 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| caps1 = 212\n| goals1 = 35\n| years2 = 2011\u20132014\n| clubs2 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| caps2 = 96\n| goals2 = 28\n| years3 = 2014\u20132019\n| clubs3 = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n| caps3 = 138\n| goals3 = 15\n| years4 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs4 = [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]\n| caps4 = 31\n| goals4 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 2002\u20132003\n| nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-16 football team|Spain U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 8\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2003\u20132004\n| nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 14\n| nationalgoals2 = 7\n| nationalyears3 = 2005\n| nationalteam3 = [[Spain national under-20 football team|Spain U20]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 5\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2004\u20132005\n| nationalteam4 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 12\n| nationalgoals4 = 8\n| nationalyears5 = 2006\u2013\n| nationalteam5 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 110\n| nationalgoals5 = 15\n| nationalyears6 = 2004\u2013\n| nationalteam6 = [[Catalonia national football team|Catalonia]]\n| nationalcaps6 = 3\n| nationalgoals6 = 0\n| club-update = 23:02, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 19:07, 27 August 2017 (UTC)\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{fb|ESP}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[UEFA Euro 2008|2008]]|}}\n{{Medal|W|[[UEFA Euro 2012|2012]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Under-17 Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[2004 UEFA European Under-17 Championship|2004]]|}}\n}}\n'''Francesc F\u00e0bregas Soler''' ({{IPA-ca|\u02c8s\u025bsk \u02c8fa\u03b2\u027e\u0259\u0263\u0259s}}, {{IPA-es|\u02c8fa\u03b2\u027ee\u0263as|lang}}; born 4 May 1987) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] for [[Ligue 1]] club [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] and the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]].\n\nF\u00e0bregas came through ''[[La Masia]]'', [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]'s youth academy, leaving at 16 when he was signed by Premier League club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in September 2003. Following injuries to key midfielders in the early part of the [[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305 season]], he went on establish himself in the team. He broke several of the club's records in the process, earning a reputation as one of the best players in his position, and won the [[FA Cup]] in 2005. After a protracted transfer saga, F\u00e0bregas left London on 15 August 2011 to return to Barcelona in a deal worth up to \u00a335&nbsp;million. During his three-year spell at the [[Camp Nou]], F\u00e0bregas played alongside [[Xavi]] and [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]] and won a [[2012\u201313 La Liga|La Liga]] title, the [[2011\u201312 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]], the [[2011 FIFA Club World Cup|FIFA Club World Cup]], the [[2011 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]] and two [[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|Spanish Super Cups]]. He returned to London in June 2014 to Arsenal's cross-town rivals Chelsea for a fee of \u00a330&nbsp;million, and in his first year there he helped to secure [[League Cup]] and Premier League triumphs.\n\nInternationally, F\u00e0bregas made his debut for the Spanish national team in March 2006. He represented his country in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], [[UEFA Euro 2008]], [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]], [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]], [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]], [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup|2013 Confederations Cup]], the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]]. He was a key figure in Spain's European Championship victories in 2008 and 2012 and their 2010 World Cup triumph in which he supplied the pass for Andr\u00e9s Iniesta's winning goal in the [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final|final]]. On 12 October 2015, F\u00e0bregas earned his [[List of footballers with 100 or more caps|100th cap]] for Spain.\n\n== Early years ==\nBorn in [[Arenys de Mar]], [[Province of Barcelona|Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]],<ref name=espn>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/profile?id=38886&cc=4716 Francesc Fabregas profile] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012192119/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/profile?id=38886&cc=4716 |date=12 October 2007 }}, ESPNsoccernet, accessed 27 June 2009.</ref><ref name=ars>[http://www.arsenal.com/first-team/players/cesc-fabregas Cesc F\u00e0bregas profile] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817065158/http://www.arsenal.com/first-team/players/cesc-fabregas |date=17 August 2008 }}, Arsenal F.C., accessed 27 June 2009.</ref> to Francesc F\u00e0bregas Sr., who runs a property company, and N\u00faria Soler, the owner of a pastry company, F\u00e0bregas has supported [[FC Barcelona]] since childhood and went to his first match when he was nine months old with his grandfather.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/francesc-fabregas-spanish-marvel-blossoms-out-of-the-world-of-his-mentors-509243.html Francesc Fabregas: Spanish marvel blossoms out of the world of his mentors], ''[[The Independent]]'', accessed 31 August 2010.</ref> He began his club football career with [[CE Matar\u00f3]] before being signed for Barcelona's ''[[La Masia]]'' youth academy aged ten in 1997.<ref>[http://www.elpais.com/articulo/deportes/todo/era/sueno/elppordep/20060516elpepidep_6/Tes Cuando todo era un sue\u00f1o], ELPA\u00cdS.com, accessed 16 May 2006</ref> His first coach, Se\u00f1or Blai, reportedly did not select F\u00e0bregas for matches against Barcelona in an attempt to hide him from their scouts.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2010/mar/31/cesc-fabregas-barcelona-arsenal Cesc F\u00e0bregas faces the Barcelona Dream Team he left behind], ''The Guardian'', 31 March 2010, accessed 18 September 2010.</ref> This tactic, however, was unable to withstand Barcelona for long, and Matar\u00f3 gave in and allowed F\u00e0bregas to train with Barcelona one day per week. Eventually F\u00e0bregas joined Barcelona's academy full-time. His initial training was as a [[defensive midfielder]] playing alongside notable names such as [[Gerard Piqu\u00e9]] and [[Lionel Messi]]. Although he was a prolific scorer, sometimes scoring even more than 30 goals in a season for the club's youth teams, he did not manage to play a first-team game at the [[Camp Nou]].<ref name=uefap>[http://www.uefa.com/competitions/UCL/players/player=70072/index.html Cesc Fabregas], UEFA, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> During his time at Barcelona's youth academy, F\u00e0bregas idolised Barcelona's then-captain and number four [[Pep Guardiola]], who would later give F\u00e0bregas his shirt as consolation when F\u00e0bregas' parents divorced.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/8718064.stm The one that got away], BBC Sport, accessed 1 June 2010.</ref>\n\n== Club career ==\n\n=== Arsenal ===\n\n==== Adapting to England ====\n\n[[File:Fabregas shooting.jpg|thumb|F\u00e0bregas (left) in a game against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in 2006]]\n\nSensing that he would have limited opportunities at Barcelona,<ref name=fa>[https://archive.is/20080820045904/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/04/FACF_CescFabregasPreview.htm The Young Gunner], The Football Association, 19 May 2005, accessed 27 August 2011.</ref> F\u00e0bregas joined [[Premier League]] club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in their [[Arsenal F.C. Academy|Academy]],<ref name=\"PFA 200\">{{Cite book| last = Hugman| first = Barry J.| title = The PFA Premier & Football League Players' Records 1946\u20132005| publisher = Queen Anne Press| year = 2005| page = 200| isbn = 1-85291-665-6 }}</ref> signing for the London club on 11 September 2003.<ref name=ars/> Initially, he found life difficult in England's capital but soon struck a friendship with Spanish-speaking teammate [[Philippe Senderos]], who helped him settle down.<ref name=times>Marcotti, Gabriele and Balague, Guillem, [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premiership/arsenal/article1449871.ece \"From Barcelona to Barnet: how a rising star learnt his trade\"], ''The Times'', 28 February 2007, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> As a 16-year-old, F\u00e0bregas did not contemplate breaking into the first team immediately but looked up to senior players like [[Patrick Vieira]] and [[Gilberto Silva]], while concentrating on training and learning the English language.<ref name=times/> He nevertheless made his debut for Arsenal not long after, on 28 October 2003, in a [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] tie at home to [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]]. In doing so, he became Arsenal's youngest-ever first team player, aged 16 years and 177 days.<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/fabregas-becomes-youngest-gunner Cesc Fabregas becomes Arsenal's youngest ever player], Arsenal F.C., 27 January 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> He then became the youngest goalscorer in Arsenal's history in a later round of the League Cup, scoring in a 5\u20131 victory against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/3246940.stm Arsenal youngsters thump Wolves], BBC Sport, 2 December 2003, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> Although Arsenal went on to [[The Invincibles (football)|win the league unbeaten]] in the [[2003\u201304 in English football|2003\u201304 season]],<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/history/club-records/record-scorelines Record Scorelines], Arsenal F.C., accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> F\u00e0bregas was not awarded a winner's medal because he did not play a single league game.<ref name=stats>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/stats?id=38886&cc=4716 Francesc Fabregas history], ESPNsoccernet, accessed 18 December 2007.</ref>\n\nIt was not until the start of the [[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305 season]] that the Spaniard started making first team appearances in matches outside the League Cup. His first match of the season was against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in the [[FA Community Shield]]. Following an injury to Vieira, F\u00e0bregas stepped in and made four consecutive Premier League starts. He was praised for his performances in those games, even claiming a goal against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in a 3\u20130 victory, and becoming Arsenal's youngest-ever goalscorer in a league game.<ref>Hughes, Ian, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/3600372.stm \"Fabregas the fabulous\"], BBC Sport, 27 August 2004, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref><ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=152167&cc=4716 Arsenal 3\u20130 Blackburn], ESPNsoccernet, 25 August 2004, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> With further injuries to [[Edu (footballer, born 1978)|Edu]] and Gilberto Silva, he received more playing time in all competitions.<ref name=espn/><ref name=fa/> He signed his first [[professional]] contract with Arsenal in September 2004,<ref name=\"PFA 200\"/> which committed his long-term future to the club.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/3664918.stm Fabregas commits to Arsenal], BBC Sport, 17 September 2004, accessed 3 June 2010.</ref> In October 2004, Arsenal lost 2\u20130 to Manchester United, ending their 49-match unbeaten run in the Premier League. The match was dubbed the \"[[Battle of the Buffet]]\" after pizza was thrown at Manchester United manager [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] at the end of the match in the players' tunnel by a then-unknown Arsenal player. Speculation that the player was F\u00e0bregas<ref name=\"whohitsiralex\">{{cite news |title=Who hit Sir Alex with pizza?|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/who-hit-sir-alex-with-pizza-6955390.html |publisher=standard.co.uk |date=27 October 2004 |accessdate=11 August 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"Selfishlazy\">{{cite news |title=Selfish, lazy youngsters cost Arsenal the season \u2013 Cole |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/selfish-lazy-youngsters-cost-arsenal-the-season--cole-7201142.html |publisher=standard.co.uk |date=13 September 2006 |accessdate=11 August 2012 }}</ref> was confirmed in November 2011 by former Arsenal player [[Martin Keown]] on a phone-in show on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]].<ref name=\"Fabregasrevealed\">{{cite magazine|title=Fabregas revealed as Gunner who fired pizza at Fergie |url=http://www.people.co.uk/sport/football/news/2011/11/13/fabregas-revealed-as-gunner-who-fired-pizza-at-fergie-102039-23557693/ |magazine=The People |date=13 November 2011 |accessdate=11 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111217141021/http://www.people.co.uk/sport/football/news/2011/11/13/fabregas-revealed-as-gunner-who-fired-pizza-at-fergie-102039-23557693/ |archivedate=17 December 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"Culprit\">{{cite news |title=Fabregas confirmed as 'Battle of the Buffet' culprit who threw pizza at Sir Alex Ferguson|url=http://mancunianmatters.co.uk/content/15111678-fabregas-confirmed-battle-buffet-culprit-who-threw-pizza-sir-alex-ferguson |publisher=Mancunian Matters |date=15 November 2011 |accessdate=11 August 2012 }}</ref> In the [[2004\u201305 UEFA Champions League]], he became the second-youngest goalscorer in the competition's history after scoring the third goal against [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]] in a 5\u20131 win.<ref>Haylett, Trevor, [http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2004/round=1968/match=1077234/index.html \"Awesome Arsenal progress in style], UEFA, 7 December 2004, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> He concluded his season by winning his first honours with Arsenal when he was in the starting eleven that defeated Manchester United on [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalties]] in the [[2005 FA Cup Final]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/4558271.stm Arsenal 0\u20130 Man Utd (aet)], BBC Sport, 21 May 2005, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref>\n\n==== Making the starting eleven ====\nAfter the departure of Patrick Vieira to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], F\u00e0bregas was given the Frenchman's number 4 shirt and featured regularly in the Arsenal central midfield alongside Gilberto Silva. He made 49 appearances in all competitions during the [[2005\u201306 in English football|2005\u201306 season]].<ref name=stats/> Despite his young age, his performances came under greater scrutiny due to his increased involvement in the first team. Further, as F\u00e0bregas possessed a smaller frame and played with less aggression than Vieira, there were initially doubts over his ability to fill in the void left by the Frenchman.<ref name=hubb>Hubbard, Norman, [http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story?id=340141&root=england&cc=4716 \"Arsenal's midfield muddle\"], ESPNsoccernet, 22 August 2005, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> Nevertheless, F\u00e0bregas asserted his own style of play and impressed pundits in the Champions League against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] and Juventus.<ref name=bbc>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/4841992.stm Arsenal 2\u20130 Juventus], BBC Sport, 28 March 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref><ref>Sheringham, Sam, [https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=10000086&sid=aIRzsd9XXEPY&refer=latin_america \"Spain Teenager Fabregas Sparks World Cup Rally, Wows Maradona\"], Bloomberg, 20 June 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref><ref name=harr>Harrold, Michael, [http://www.uefa.com/magazine/news/kind=512/newsid=527164.html \"Fabregas plots Arsenal revival\"], UEFA, 13 April 2007, accessed 23 May 2007. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070518174227/http://www.uefa.com/magazine/news/kind%3D512/newsid%3D527164.html |date=18 May 2007 }}</ref> In the latter, he scored Arsenal's first goal and set up [[Thierry Henry]] for the second,<ref name=bbc/> at the same time proving that he could compete against tough, hard-tackling midfielders like Vieira.<ref name=harr/> He then played in the [[2006 UEFA Champions League Final|Final]] against his former club Barcelona, but Arsenal were defeated 2\u20131,<ref>Haslam, Andrew, [http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2005/round=2205/match=1108503/index.html \"Barca comeback denies Arsenal\"], UEFA, 17 May 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> completing a trophyless 2005\u201306 campaign for Arsenal.\n\n[[File:Fabregas celebration.jpg|thumb|upright|F\u00e0bregas celebrates a goal with his Arsenal teammates]]\n\nF\u00e0bregas' increase in exposure drew transfer speculation during the summer; Real Madrid expressed a desire to sign the Spaniard despite his long-term contract with Arsenal,<ref>Kendall, Mark, [http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11670_2382489,00.html \"Real confident of securing Cesc's signature\"], Sky Sports, 4 July 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> but Arsenal manager [[Ars\u00e8ne Wenger]] stated that Arsenal would not listen to any offers.<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/wenger-fabregas-is-not-for-sale-he-is-arsenal-rsquo-s-future Wenger: F\u00e0bregas is not for sale, he is Arsenal's future], Arsenal F.C., 12 July 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> In September 2006, with six years left on his deal, Arsenal offered a new five-year deal (with an option to extend by a further three years) to the midfielder, which he signed on 19 October 2006.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/5340362.stm F\u00e0bregas signs new Arsenal deal], BBC Sport, 19 October 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> While the contract was unusually long, F\u00e0bregas cited Arsenal's playing style and Wenger as reasons for his long-term commitment to the club.<ref>Harris, Chris, [http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/fabregas-our-style-of-play-makes-me-so-happy \"Fabregas \u2013 Our style of play makes me so happy\"], Arsenal F.C., 22 October 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref><ref>Adams, Tom, [http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11670_2393205,00.html \"Cesc staying grounded\"], Sky Sports, 27 October 2006, accessed 24 May 2007.</ref>\n\n[[File:Cesc F\u00e0bregas captain.jpg|thumb|upright|left|F\u00e0bregas was appointed captain of the team during the 2008\u201309 season]]\n\nThe [[2006\u201307 Arsenal F.C. season|2006\u201307 season]] was a learning experience for the young Arsenal squad and F\u00e0bregas. The club again failed to secure any major honours and were defeated by city rivals [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the [[Football League Cup Final 2007|League Cup Final]].<ref name=2007LeagueCupFinal>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/league_cup/6371613.stm |title=Chelsea 2\u20131 Arsenal: Match report |website=BBC Sport |date=25 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071107165839/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/league_cup/6371613.stm |archivedate=7 November 2007}}</ref> F\u00e0bregas, however, emerged as one of the key creative players for the team, playing in every single league game.<ref name=stats/><ref name=actim>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/arsenal-are-the-ultimate-second-half-team Arsenal are the ultimate 'second half' team], Arsenal F.C., accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> He kick-started Arsenal's [[UEFA Champions League 2006-07|2006\u201307 UEFA Champions League]] campaign when he scored a brace in a 3\u20130 win over [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] in a qualifier match.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/5251984.stm Dinamo Zagreb 0\u20133 Arsenal], BBC Sport, 8 June 2006, accessed 7 September 2008.</ref> In the Premier League, he notched up 13 [[assist (soccer)|assists]], which was the second-highest total in the league.<ref name=stats/><ref name=actim/> He ended the season with several individual honours, including the Golden Boy award, presented by the Italian paper ''TuttoSport'', based on a poll of leading writers across Europe.<ref>Lipton, Martin, [https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/tm_headline=he-s-fab-in-poll%26method=full%26objectid=18196769%26siteid=94762-name_page.html \"HE'S FAB IN POLL\"], ''Daily Mirror'', 2 December 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> He was also named in the 2006 [[UEFA Team of the Year]],<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/fanzone/teamoftheyear/news/newsid=497866.html Your Team of 2006 revealed], UEFA, 19 January 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> and named [[FA Premier League Player of the Month]] for January 2007.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/6348331.stm Benitez and Fabregas scoop awards], BBC Sport, 9 February 2007, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> Additionally, he was nominated for both [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]] and [[PFA Young Player of the Year]], although both awards went to Manchester United's [[Cristiano Ronaldo]].<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=215178&cc=4716 Arsenal 3\u20131 Man City: Fabregas inspires revival], ESPNsoccernet, 17 April 2007, accessed 18 April 2007.</ref> In June 2007, he was named Arsenal's Player of the Season, taking in 60% of the votes.<ref name=pots>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/-he-showed-he-is-the-ultimate-midfield-player- 'He showed he is the ultimate midfield player'], Arsenal F.C., accessed 28 June 2007.</ref>\n\nThe [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308 season]] began with much uncertainty for Arsenal. First, [[David Dein]], the club's vice-chairman, left amidst allegations of internal strife, followed by the departure of the club's all-time top goalscorer and captain, Thierry Henry, who signed for Barcelona. There was also speculation over Wenger's future with the club.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=460716&cc=4716 Wenger signs new three-year Gunners deal], ESPNsoccernet, 7 September 2007, accessed 16 September 2007.</ref> F\u00e0bregas knew that he would become the most important player for Arsenal, but stated he was ready for the challenge.<ref name=chall>[http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,,2156108,00.html How Fabregas plans to save Arsenal], ''The Guardian'', 25 August 2007, accessed 17 September 2007.</ref> He started the season well, chalking up goals and assists,<ref name=stats/> and website [[soccernet]] attributed the early success of Arsenal to the young Spaniard.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story?id=463322&root=england&cc=4716&lpos=spotlight&lid=tab1pos3 Burying the ghost of Henry]. ESPNsoccernet, 15 September 2007, accessed 17 September 2007.</ref> His start to the season also earned him the [[O2 (UK)|O<sub>2</sub>]] Player of the Month award from Arsenal fans for August, September and October,<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/fabregas-scoops-o2-player-of-the-month-award Fabregas scoops O2 Player of the Month award] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030045829/http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/fabregas-scoops-o2-player-of-the-month-award |date=30 October 2008 }}, Arsenal F.C., 5 October 2007, accessed 6 October 2007.</ref> as well as the Premier League Player of the Month for September.<ref>[http://www.premierleague.com/staticFiles/d1/a4/0,,12306~107729,00.pdf GUNNERS DUO CELEBRATE AWARDS DOUBLE] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201133946/http://www.premierleague.com/staticFiles/d1/a4/0%2C%2C12306~107729%2C00.pdf |date=1 December 2008 }}, Premier League, 19 October 2007, accessed 5 March 2008.</ref> With Arsenal leading the league table until March, F\u00e0bregas was equally instrumental in the club's [[UEFA Champions League 2007-08|2007\u201308 Champions League campaign]]; in the return leg against [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], the midfielder scored late in the game to send Arsenal into the quarter-finals.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/7272514.stm AC Milan 0 \u2013 Arsenal 2], BBC Sport, 5 March 2008, accessed 5 March 2008.</ref> Though Arsenal ended the season trophyless,<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/season-review-week-the-highlights-and-the-lowlights Season Review Week: The highlights and the lowlights], Arsenal F.C., accessed 24 May 2008.</ref> F\u00e0bregas amassed several personal awards. On 11 April 2008, F\u00e0bregas was nominated for the PFA Player of the Year and PFA Young Player of the Year awards for the second year running;<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=524778&cc=4716 Ronaldo heads shortlist for players' awards], ESPNsoccernet, 11 April 2008, accessed 12 April 2008.</ref> he was later crowned the winner of the latter, and named in the [[PFA Team of the Year#Premier League|PFA Team of the Year]]. He was also named the 2007\u201308 Arsenal.com Player of the Season.<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/fabregas-is-arsenal.com-player-of-the-season Fabregas is O2/Arsenal.com Player of the Season], Arsenal F.C., accessed 8 July 2008.</ref>\n\n==== Captaincy ====\n\n[[File:Ferdinand Fabregas.jpg|thumb|upright|F\u00e0bregas as captain during the 2008\u201309 Champions League semi-final]]\n\nOn 24 November 2008, 14 league games into the [[2008\u201309 in English football|2008\u201309 season]], F\u00e0bregas was named as the successor to [[William Gallas]] as club captain.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=595659&sec=uefachampionsleague&cc=4716 Fabregas replaces Gallas as Arsenal skipper], ESPNsoccernet, 24 November 2008, accessed 25 November 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.thesportreview.com/tsr/2008/11/captain-cescs-appointment-is-no-surpise/ Captain Cesc's appointment is no surprise], The Sport Review, 26 November 2008, accessed 22 May 2009.</ref> However, just as Arsenal were getting back into the title race after a poor start to the season, the Spaniard was ruled out for four months after sustaining a knee injury against Liverpool.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=604874&sec=england&cc=4716 Injured Fabregas ruled out for 3\u20134 months], ESPNsoccernet, 23 December 2008, accessed 24 December 2008.</ref> The Gunners eventually finished the season without any silverware, coming in fourth in the league and being knocked out at the semi-finals of the [[UEFA Champions League 2008\u201309|2008\u201309 Champions League campaign]].<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/team/stats?id=359&season=2008&league=eng.1&cc=4716 2008/2009 English Premier League: Statistics], ESPNsoccernet, accessed 1 July 2009.</ref><ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=266495&cc=4716&league=UEFA.CHAMPIONS Arsenal 1 \u2013 3 Manchester United], ESPNsoccernet, 29 April 2009, accessed 1 July 2009.</ref> In tandem with Arsenal's policy to groom its young players, the team that F\u00e0bregas led into the new season consisted mostly of the same young nucleus as before, with the likes of [[Nicklas Bendtner]], [[Ga\u00ebl Clichy]], [[Abou Diaby]], [[Den\u00edlson Pereira Neves|Den\u00edlson]], [[Samir Nasri]], [[Alex Song]] and [[Theo Walcott]] in tow.\n\n[[File:Jermaine Jenas, Cesc Fabregas & Younes Kaboul.jpg|thumb|left|F\u00e0bregas in a game against rivals [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] in November 2010]]\n\nIn the opening league game of [[2009\u201310 in English football|2009\u201310 season]], F\u00e0bregas scored a brace and managed two assists in Arsenal's 6\u20131 away win against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=269878&cc=5901&league=ENG.1 Gunners crush Toffees], ESPNsoccernet, 15 August 2009, accessed 18 August 2009.</ref> Arsenal went on to secure qualification for the [[UEFA Champions League 2009\u201310|2009\u201310 Champions League campaign]] by beating [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] over two legs, but their early momentum to the season was disrupted by consecutive league game losses to Manchester United and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. The team bounced back strongly after this setback, and with F\u00e0bregas being prolific in scoring and setting up his teammates, it went unbeaten in the next 13 games. Despite suffering four league losses even before mid-season approached, Arsenal managed to lead the league standings after 22 games. On 31 March 2010, in the Champions League first leg of the quarter-final against Barcelona, F\u00e0bregas suffered a leg fracture before scoring the equalising goal in the game which ended 2\u20132.<ref name=fract>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=764753&sec=england&cc=5901 Fabregas out for six weeks with leg fracture], ESPNsoccernet, 1 April 2010, accessed 2 April 2010.</ref> Arsenal, who were four points behind league leaders Manchester United, were deprived of their captain for the remaining six league games of the season;<ref name=fract/> they were subsequently eliminated by Barcelona in the Champions League, and fell out of the league title race. F\u00e0bregas was later named to the [[PFA Team of the Year#Premier League 3|PFA Team of the Year]].<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=777236&sec=england&cc=5901 Rooney scoops PFA Player of the Year Award], ESPNsoccernet, 25 April 2010, accessed 26 April 2010.</ref>\n\n[[File:Busquets, F\u00e0bregas & Van Persie.jpg|thumb|upright|F\u00e0bregas tries to subdue an argument between [[Sergio Busquets]] and [[Robin van Persie]].]]\n\nBefore the start of the [[2010\u201311 in English football|2010\u201311 season]], there was once again intense media speculation about the Spaniard's future, and in June 2010, a \u20ac35&nbsp;million bid from Barcelona was rejected.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/8717785.stm Arsenal reject Barcelona's bid for Cesc Fabregas], BBC Sport, 2 June 2010, accessed 15 June 2010.</ref><ref>[https://archive.is/20120525090001/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/06/04/n100604111383.html Laporta: Lines of communication open over Cesc], fcbarcelona.cat, 4 June 2010, accessed 27 June 2010.</ref> The 2010\u201311 season turned out to be an extremely competitive one in the Premier League; even though Arsenal had lost five games before mid-season, they were jostling for pole position with Manchester United and Manchester City.<ref>Roger, Martins, [https://sports.yahoo.com/soccer/news?slug=ro-eplmidtermgrades122910 \"EPL midseason surprises and disappointments\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110102201601/http://sports.yahoo.com/soccer/news?slug=ro-eplmidtermgrades122910 |date=2 January 2011 }}, Yahoo! Sports, 29 December 2010, accessed 20 January 2011.</ref> Going into late February, Arsenal were still in contention for the quadruple, but within a span of two weeks they lost in the [[2011 Football League Cup Final|League Cup final]], were eliminated by Barcelona in the Round of 16 of the [[UEFA Champions League 2010\u201311|Champions League]], and defeated in the FA Cup quarter-final.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/893940/arsene-wenger-not-questioning-arsenal-players'-steel?cc=4716 Wenger not questioning steel], ESPNsoccernet, 14 March 2011, accessed 15 March 2011.</ref> Although F\u00e0bregas did not play in the League Cup Final, it was his misplaced backheel pass during the second leg of the Champions League game against Barcelona that allowed them to level the aggregate score. Arsenal remained in contention for the league title until a series of draws in the final third of the season caused them to fall too far behind league leaders Manchester United; they ended the season fourth. The [[2011\u201312 in English football|following season]] was once again marked by uncertainty. Barcelona made several bids for F\u00e0bregas, while Nasri, Arsenal's star performer the previous campaign, was courted by Manchester City.\n\n=== Barcelona ===\n\n==== 2011\u201312 season ====\n\n[[File:Cesc F\u00e0bregas - Presentation.jpg|thumb|upright|left|F\u00e0bregas during his presentation to Barcelona]]\n\nOn 15 August 2011, Barcelona signed F\u00e0bregas for an initial fee of \u20ac29&nbsp;million with a further \u20ac5&nbsp;million in variables, plus F\u00e0bregas would pay Arsenal \u20ac1&nbsp;million a year from his wage for five years.<!-- NOTE: do not change this sourced amount. Failure to respect sourced material will result in a vandalism block. Be aware. --><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/season/2011-2012/bartomeu-thanks-cesc-for-his-efforts-to-come-to-barca|title=Bartomeu thanks Cesc for his efforts to come to Bar\u00e7a |date=15 August 2011|accessdate=7 August 2012|publisher=FC Barcelona}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/943939|title=Fabregas arrives for medical|date=15 August 2011|accessdate=13 June 2014|publisher=ESPN SOCCERNET}}</ref> ending one of the most protracted transfer sagas in recent times. Statistics show that in the five years prior to F\u00e0bregas's departure from Arsenal, F\u00e0bregas created 466 goal-scoring chances, made 86 assists and scored 48 goals, all three statistics topping those of new teammates [[Xavi]] and [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]], despite both having made more appearances in the same period.<ref>[http://football-talk.co.uk/31566/official-fabregas-is-better-than-xavi-iniesta.stm \"OFFICIAL: Fabregas Is Better Than Xavi & Iniesta\"], Football-Talk, 20 July 2011, accessed 26 July 2012.</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14482418.stm \"Cesc Fabregas completes move from Arsenal to Barcelona\"], BBC Sport, 15 August 2011, accessed 15 August 2011.</ref>\n\nF\u00e0bregas joined a team that had won three [[List of Spanish football champions|La Liga titles]] in a row and two Champions League titles in three years, and one that featured the likes of [[Lionel Messi]], Xavi, Andr\u00e9s Iniesta and [[David Villa]]. He made his debut in the second leg of the [[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]], coming on as a substitute against Real Madrid. Barcelona won the tie 3\u20132 and 5\u20134 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/aug/18/cesc-fabregas-barcelona-debut-madrid|title=Cesc F\u00e1bregas starts with a night to remember at Barcelona|newspaper=The Guardian|author=Sid Lowe|date=18 August 2011|accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/330063|title=Messi wins Super Cup|publisher=ESPNsoccernet|date=17 August 2011|accessdate=17 August 2011}}</ref> He scored his first goal in a 2\u20130 win against [[FC Porto|Porto]] as Barcelona won the [[2011 UEFA Super Cup]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/season=2011/matches/round=2000258/match=2006776/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Barcelona breeze to fourth UEFA Super Cup|publisher=UEFA.com|author=Kevin Ashby|date=26 August 2011|accessdate=27 August 2011}}</ref> and his first league goal on his league debut, a 5\u20130 home win over [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spanish-football/2011/08/29/2642052/barcelona-5-0-villarreal-messi-fabregas-alexis-sanchez-all|title=Barcelona 5-0 Villarreal: Messi, Fabregas & Alexis Sanchez all on target as champions cruise to victory|publisher=Goal.com|author=Roger Gonzalez|date=29 August 2011|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref> He went on to score three more league goals in the month of September, including a late equaliser in the 2\u20132 away draw to [[Valencia CF|Valencia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/sep/22/valencia-barcelona-la-liga|title=Late goal from Cesc F\u00e1bregas earns Barcelona a draw with Valencia|newspaper=The Guardian|date=22 September 2011|accessdate=1 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nF\u00e0bregas then spent the majority of October sidelined with a hamstring injury picked up on international duty.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/oct/01/barcelona-cesc-fabregas-injury|title=Barcelona's Cesc F\u00e1bregas out for three weeks with hamstring injury|newspaper=The Guardian|date=1 October 2011|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref> He made his return, and scored, in a 4\u20130 away victory to [[FC Viktoria Plze\u0148|Viktoria Plze\u0148]] in the [[2011\u201312 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/65997/fc-viktoria-plze%C5%88-vs-barcelona/|title=Viktoria Plzen 0-4 Barcelona: Lionel Messi breaks 200-goal barrier with hat-trick as European champions ease into the knockout stages|publisher=Goal.com|author=Charlie Scott|date=1 November 2011|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref> He then made his league return in the 2\u20132 draw away to [[Athletic Bilbao]], scoring a goal in the same match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/%2012/spanish-football/2011/11/06/2745817/athletic-bilbao-2-2-barcelona-injury-time-messi-strike|title=Athletic Bilbao 2-2 Barcelona: Injury-time Messi strike salvages point for champions at rain-soaked San Mames|publisher=Goal.com|author=Daniel Quinton-Navarro|date=6 November 2011|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref> F\u00e0bregas then went on to score a brace in a 5\u20130 home victory against [[Levante UD|Levante]] before netting in a 3\u20131 away victory against Real Madrid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2011/12/3/2608560/barcelona-vs-levante-2011-la-liga-final-score-report|title=Barcelona Vs. Levante, 2011 La Liga: Hosts Crush Levante In 5-0 Rout|publisher=SB Nation|author=Graham MacAree|date=3 December 2011|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/dec/10/real-madrid-barcelona-la-liga|title=Cesc F\u00e0bregas scores in El Cl\u00e1sico as Barcelona beat Real Madrid|newspaper=The Guardian|author=Sid Lowe|date=10 December 2011|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref> F\u00e0bregas later scored against Brazilian club [[Santos FC|Santos]] to help Barcelona to a 4\u20130 victory in the [[2011 FIFA Club World Cup]] final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/8964048/Barcelona-4-Santos-0-match-report.html|title=Barcelona 4 Santos 0: match report|publisher=The Tepegraph|author=Telegraph staff and agencies|date=18 December 2011|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nF\u00e0bregas got another brace in a 4\u20130 victory against [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]] in the [[2011\u201312 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barcablaugranes.com/2012/1/5/2683015/copa-del-rey-match-review-fc-barcelona-4-0-ca-osasuna|title=Copa del Rey: FC Barcelona 4-0 CA Osasuna: Match Review|publisher=Barca Blaugranes|author=Arron Duckling|date=5 January 2012|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref> He also scored in the semi-final of the competition against Valencia to help Barcelona to the final with a 3\u20131 win on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/feb/08/barcelona-valencia-copa-del-rey|title=Lionel Messi and Xavi see off Valencia to seal Barcelona final place|newspaper=The Guardian|author=Sid Lowe|date=8 February 2012|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref> He kept a regular run in the Barcelona side for the rest of the season, including appearances in both semi-final legs of the 3\u20132 aggregate defeat to Chelsea in the Champions League,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/17673812|title=Chelsea 1-0 Barcelona|website=BBC Sport|author=Phil McNulty|date=18 April 2012|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/17817584|title=Barcelona 2-2 Chelsea|website=BBC Sport|author=Phil Dawkes|date=24 April 2012|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref> and a substitute appearance in the 3\u20130 victory against Athletic Bilbao in the [[2012 Copa del Rey Final|Copa del Rey final]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/18216611|title=Pep Guardiola's final game: Barcelona win Copa del Rey|website=BBC Sport|date=26 May 2012|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nF\u00e0bregas ended his first season at Barcelona by winning the [[2011\u201312 Copa del Rey]], [[2011 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]], [[2011 UEFA Super Cup]] and the [[2011 FIFA Club World Cup]], notching 15 goals and 20 assists in 48 appearances and four best midfielder awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=36694&season_id=141|title=Games played by Cesc Fabregas in 2011/2012|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== 2012\u201313 season ====\nF\u00e0bregas ended his long goal drought for his club when he scored his first league goals of the season with a brace against [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in a 3\u20132 away victory. He then scored three goals in October, coming in the league, [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] and the [[2012\u201313 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]]. He scored again on 25 November in a 4\u20130 win away to Levante. On 13 January 2013, F\u00e0bregas scored in a 3\u20131 win away to [[M\u00e1laga CF|M\u00e1laga]]. F\u00e0bregas scored his first [[hat-trick]] of his career against [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] in a 5\u20130 victory on 6 April 2013. He ended his second season at Barcelona by winning the first [[2012\u201313 La Liga|league title]] of his career, with a record 100 points. Barcelona were eliminated, however, in the semi-finals of both the Copa del Rey, to rivals Real Madrid, and the Champions League, to winners [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]. F\u00e0bregas ended the season with 14 goals and 12 assists in 48 appearances in all competitions.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n==== 2013\u201314 season ====\nBarcelona began the season by winning the [[2013 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]. In the opening game of the [[2013\u201314 La Liga|league season]] on 18 August, F\u00e0bregas provided five assists in a 7\u20130 win over [[Levante UD|Levante]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Barcelona 7\u20130 Levante: Stunning debut win for Tata Martino|url=http://www.goal.com/en/match/barcelona-vs-levante/1517627/report|accessdate=12 June 2014|work=Goal.com|date=18 August 2014}}</ref> He scored 8 goals in 36 league matches, including braces in away wins over [[Granada CF|Granada]] on 10 November and [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] on 22 December, the latter including a penalty kick. He also scored the only goal of the game on 1 October as Barcelona won away at [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in the group stage of the Champions League, heading in [[Alexis S\u00e1nchez]]'s cross in the 73rd minute.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bogunya |first1=Roger |title=Bar\u00e7a show they learnt last year's lesson |url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/match-archive/2013-2014/champions-league/round-2-h/celtic_fc-barcelona/info |accessdate=12 June 2014 |publisher=[[FC Barcelona]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329181303/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/match-archive/2013-2014/champions-league/round-2-h/celtic_fc-barcelona/info |archivedate=29 March 2014  }}</ref>\n\n=== Chelsea ===\n\n{{update section|date=June 2018}}\n\n[[File:Chelsea 2 QPR 1 (15662596926).jpg|thumb|upright|F\u00e0bregas in action against [[Karl Henry]] of [[Queens Park Rangers]] in November 2014]]\n\nOn 12 June 2014, Premier League club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] signed F\u00e0bregas on a five-year contract for a fee in the region of \u20ac33&nbsp;million. Following his transfer he took the number 4 shirt, previously worn by [[David Luiz]].<ref name=chelsea>{{cite news|title=Cesc Fabregas: Chelsea sign ex-Arsenal midfielder from Barcelona|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27819204|accessdate=12 June 2014|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=12 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/3900839/title/fabregas-signs-for-chelsea |title=FABREGAS SIGNS FOR CHELSEA |date=12 June 2014 |accessdate=13 June 2014 |publisher=Chelsea FC |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613030133/http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/3900839/title/fabregas-signs-for-chelsea |archivedate=13 June 2014  }}</ref> F\u00e0bregas spoke of his transfer, saying, \"I asked Barcelona to find a way for me to leave the club. The president tried to stop the sale, but I already had my mind made up.\" He went on to say, \"If I didn't think that I'd be happy at Chelsea, I would've never made this decision. Above all, I want to be happy both professionally and personally.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11668/9351623/transfer-news-cesc-fabregas-insists-he-told-barcelona-he-wanted-to-leave|title=Cesc Fabregas insists he told Barcelona he wanted to leave|date=17 June 2014|accessdate=17 June 2014|publisher=Chelsea FC}}</ref>\n\n==== 2014\u201315 season ====\nF\u00e0bregas made his competitive debut for Chelsea on 18 August as the team began their league season away to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]; he played the full 90 minutes of a 3\u20131 victory, providing two assists.<ref>{{cite news|title=Burnley 1\u20133 Chelsea|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28735901|accessdate=18 August 2014|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=18 August 2014}}</ref> He was a nominee for the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] in August 2014, with the accolade going instead to another new Chelsea signing, [[Diego Costa]].<ref name=august>{{cite news|title=Diego Costa accepts August accolade|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2014/09/diego-costa-accepts-august-accolade.html?WT.mc_id=social_20140912_31482496|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=[[Chelsea F.C.]]|date=12 September 2014}}</ref> On 13 September 2014, after providing two assists in Chelsea's 4\u20132 victory over [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]], F\u00e0bregas became the first player ever in Premier League history to record at least one assist in six successive games; four under Chelsea and two under Arsenal during the [[2010\u201311 Arsenal F.C. season|2010\u201311 season]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Crooks|first1=Garth|title=Garth Crooks's team of the week|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/29200736|accessdate=17 September 2014|website=BBC Sport|date=14 September 2014}}</ref> Four days later, he scored his first goal for the club, opening a 1\u20131 draw at home against [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] in Chelsea's first match of the [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League group stage|Champions League group stage]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Chelsea 1\u20131 Schalke|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29225452|accessdate=17 September 2014|website=BBC Sport|date=17 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nHis first league goal for Chelsea gave them a 2\u20131 win at [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on 18 October, capping off a 19-pass move.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fifield|first1=Dominic|title=Chelsea stay top after Cesc F\u00e0bregas nets winner at Crystal Palace|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/oct/18/crystal-palace-chelsea-premier-league-match-report|accessdate=18 October 2014|work=The Guardian|date=18 October 2014}}</ref> F\u00e0bregas also completed 123 passes, the most by any player on either side.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/29580146 |title=Cesc Fabregas scored his first league goal for Chelsea as the Premier League leaders survived a late Crystal Palace fightback to maintain a five-point advantage over Manchester City. |website=BBC Sport |date=18 October 2014 |accessdate=19 October 2014 }}</ref> On 10 December, with Chelsea already through to the knockout stage as group winners, F\u00e0bregas scored an eighth-minute penalty to open a 3\u20131 Champions League victory over [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Adam|title=Chelsea 3\u20131 Sporting|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29363859|accessdate=16 April 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=10 December 2014}}</ref> Twelve days later he scored a second league goal, set up by [[Eden Hazard]] and concluding a 2\u20130 win away to Stoke.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Strickland|first1=Jamie|title=Stoke 0\u20132 Chelsea|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30474063|accessdate=16 April 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nF\u00e0bregas was fitted with a protective mask after breaking his nose in a collision with [[Charlie Adam]] during the reverse fixture on 4 April.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chelsea's Cesc Fabregas to wear face mask after breaking nose \u2013 report|url=http://www.espnfc.com/chelsea/story/2388491/chelsea-midfielder-cesc-fabregas-to-wear-face-mask-after-breaking-nose-report|accessdate=16 April 2015|publisher=ESPN|date=9 April 2015}}</ref> Eight days later, he scored the only goal of the game in the 88th minute in a victory over [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] at [[Loftus Road]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moore|first1=Glenn|title=QPR vs Chelsea match report: Man in the mask Cesc Fabregas secures vital win in Premier League title race|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/qpr-vs-chelsea-match-report-man-in-the-mask-cesc-fabregas-secures-vital-win-in-premier-league-title-race-10171035.html|accessdate=16 April 2015|work=The Independent|date=12 April 2015}}</ref> On 3 May, the day before his 28th birthday, he won his first Premier League title at the ninth attempt, following a 1\u20130 home win over Crystal Palace. During the penultimate game of the season, away at [[The Hawthorns]] against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]], F\u00e0bregas was shown the red card and booed off by fans for deliberately kicking the ball at [[Chris Brunt]]'s head while players were speaking to referee [[Mike Jones (referee)|Mike Jones]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/cesc-fabregas-sent-kicking-ball-5720196|title=Cesc Fabregas sent off for kicking the ball into West Brom player's HEAD after melee|author=James Whaling|date=18 May 2015|work=Daily Mirror|accessdate=18 May 2015}}</ref> On appeal, the suspension for this red card was cut from three matches to one.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cesc Fabregas: Chelsea player's ban cut from three games to one|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32819923|accessdate=21 May 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=20 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== 2015\u201316 season ====\nF\u00e0bregas scored his first goal of the season on 16 September, as Chelsea defeated [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]] 4\u20130 in the Champions League.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34203636 |first=Andy |last=Cryer |title=Chelsea 4\u20130 Maccabi Tel Aviv|website=BBC Sport |accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> He, Costa and [[Oscar (footballer, born 1991)|Oscar]] were jeered by the crowd in December after the dismissal of Mourinho, with the supporters believing that the trio's conduct and poor performances were more culpable for the team's poor form.<ref name=watford>{{cite news|last1=Osborne|first1=Chris|title=Chelsea 2\u20132 Watford|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/35139930|accessdate=26 December 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=26 December 2015}}</ref> His first league goal came in a 3\u20133 home draw against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on 15 January 2016<ref name=\"Chelsea 3-3 Everton\">{{cite news|title=Chelsea 3\u20133 Everton|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/35270645|accessdate=15 January 2016|website=BBC Sport|date=15 January 2016}}</ref> and his second came in a 2\u20131 away win against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] on 27 February 2016.<ref name=\"Chelsea 3-3 Everton\"/> On 19 March 2016, F\u00e0bregas scored a free-kick as well as a penalty in 2\u20132 home draw against local rivals [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/35792202 |title=Chelsea 2\u20132 West Ham |date=19 March 2016 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> F\u00e0bregas scored Chelsea's last goal of the season after converting a penalty in the 1\u20131 draw against new Premier League champions, [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36240331 |title=Chelsea 1\u20131 Leicester City:Leicester City fought back from a goal down to draw at Chelsea, the team they deposed as Premier League champions |date=15 May 2016 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==== 2016\u201317 season ====\nF\u00e0bregas was linked with a move away from London after he was an unused substitution in the [[2016\u201317 Premier League]] opener against West Ham.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/chelsea-transfer-news-cesc-fabregas-considers-chelsea-exit-after-being-left-on-the-bench-a7193861.html |title=Chelsea transfer news: Cesc Fabregas 'considers' Chelsea exit after being left on the bench against West Ham |date=16 August 2016 |newspaper=Independent}}</ref> On 20 August 2016, F\u00e0bregas once again started on the bench against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]], entering the match in the second half to replace [[Nemanja Mati\u0107]] and creating an assist for Diego Costa, who scored the winner in a 2\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/watford-vs-chelsea/356352|title=Watford 1\u20132 Chelsea: Diego Costa controversially seals second win |date=19 August 2016 |publisher=SkySports}}</ref> In the post-match press conference, F\u00e0bregas earned the praise of manager, Conte, for his inspiring performance in the comeback win as well as the attitude he shows during training sessions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/chelsea/story/2934192/cesc-fabregas-display-for-chelsea-at-watford-delights-antonio-conte |title=Cesc Fabregas display for Chelsea at Watford delights Antonio Conte |date=20 August 2016 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> F\u00e0bregas's first two goals of the season came in an [[2016\u201317 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] tie against Leicester City on 20 September, both coming within two minutes of each other in extra time to win the game 4\u20132, the victory moving Chelsea on to the Round of 16.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.us/report?gameId=466015 |title=\nCesc Fabregas hits two in extra-time as Chelsea advance past Leicester |work=ESPN FC |date=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter a month long absence due to an injury, F\u00e0bregas played a full 90 minute to for [[Chelsea F.C. Reserves and Academy|Chelsea u23]] against Southampton u23 on 21 November 2016. During the match, he provided two assists to fellow first team player, [[Michy Batshuayi]], and helped earn a 3\u20132 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2016/11/pl2-report--chelsea-v-southampton.html |title=PL2 report: Chelsea 3 Southampton 2 |date=21 November 2016 |publisher=Chelsea F.C.}}</ref> F\u00e0bregas saw his first league action since September in a game against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on 3 December 2016. Chelsea were trailing 1\u20130 when F\u00e0bregas picked out [[Diego Costa]] with a long ball into the box. Costa brought the ball down and fired it into the net to equalise.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/match/14173 |title=Manchester City 1 \u2013 3 Chelsea |publisher=premierleague.com |date=3 December 2016}}</ref> F\u00e0bregas came off the bench against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on 11 December 2016 and immediately made an impact on the deadlocked match, finding Diego Costa once again with a long ball that led to the winning goal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/match/14182 |title=Chelsea 1 \u2013 0 West Bromwich Albion |publisher=premierleague.com |date=11 December 2016}}</ref> On 14 December 2016, F\u00e0bregas led Chelsea to their tenth consecutive league victory with his first league goal of the season, scoring in the 40th minute against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/match/14193 |title=Sunderland 0 \u2013 1 Chelsea |publisher=premierleague.com |date=14 December 2016}}</ref> In his fifth league start of the season, on 31 December 2016, F\u00e0bregas recorded his 100th Premier League assist in his 293rd appearance in Chelsea's 4\u20132 home victory over [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/dec/31/chelsea-stoke-city-premier-league-match-report |title=Willian double sinks brave Stoke and extends Chelsea run to 13 straight wins |date=31 December 2016 |website=The Guardian}}</ref> he became the fastest player in Premier League history to reach this landmark, taking 74 fewer appearances than [[Ryan Giggs]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11668/11527780/cesc-fabregas-in-guinness-world-records-for-reaching-100-pl-assists |title=Cesc Fabregas in Guinness World Records for reaching 100 PL assists |publisher=Sky Sports |date=17 October 2018 |accessdate=20 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nOn 4 February 2017, F\u00e0bregas scored against former club Arsenal when he collected goalkeeper Petr Cech\u2019s poor clearance and chipped the ball back over him. He [[Goal celebration|did not celebrate]] the goal out of respect to his former club.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea 3 Arsenal 1: Eden Hazard emphasises superiority of Antonio Conte's leaders with sensational goal |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/02/04/chelsea-vs-arsenal-premier-league-live-score-updates/ |accessdate=19 October 2018 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref> On 25 February, F\u00e0bregas marked his 300th Premier League appearances with a goal and an assist as Chelsea defeated [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] 3\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/match/14290|title=Chelsea 3 \u2013 1 Swansea City|last=|first=|date=25 February 2017|website=premierleague.com|access-date=26 February 2017}}</ref> In the same match, he also reached 102 assists in the Premier League, equalling [[Frank Lampard]] as the league's second-highest provider of all time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/stats/all-time|title=Premier League Club Records, All-Time Team & Player Stats|website=www.premierleague.com|access-date=26 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Subsequent seasons ====\n\nIn the 2017\u201318 season, F\u00e0bregas made 49 appearances in all competitions, scoring three goals in a campaign which saw Chelsea win the [[2018 FA Cup Final|FA Cup]] against [[Manchester United]]. He played the entire 90 minutes in the final.\n\nF\u00e0bregas opened his account for the 2018\u201319 season, scoring the winner against [[Derby County]] in the fourth round of the [[EFL Cup]]. The Blues triumphed 3\u20132 at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2018/10/31/report--?cardIndex=0-7|title=REPORT: CHELSEA 3 DERBY COUNTY 2|website=www.chelseafc.com|access-date=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Monaco ===\nOn 11 January 2019, F\u00e0bregas signed for [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] on a contract lasting until mid-2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asmonaco.com/cesc-fabregas-a-las-monaco/|title=Cesc Fabregas \u00e0 l'AS Monaco|website=AS Monaco|access-date=11 January 2019|date=11 January 2019|language=fr}}</ref> On 13 January, Fabregas made his league debut in a 1\u20131 draw against Marseille.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46858846|title=Marseille 1\u20131 Monaco|website=BBC Sport|access-date=13 January 2019}}</ref> On 2 February, Fabregas scored his first league goal of the season for Monaco in a 2\u20131 win against Toulouse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47105527|title=Monaco 2\u20131 Toulouse|website=BBC Sport|access-date=2 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== International career ==\n\n=== Youth team ===\n\nAlthough he features regularly for the [[Spain national football team]], F\u00e0bregas' international career began at youth level. At the [[2003 FIFA U-17 World Championship]] held in Finland, he finished as top scorer of the tournament despite playing in midfield, and was voted Player of the Tournament.<ref name=uefap/> Spain finished runners-up in the tournament to Brazil.<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=102/edition=6946/news/newsid=88795.html Brazil roar past brave Spain, Argentina take third] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080803040633/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament%3D102/edition%3D6946/news/newsid%3D88795.html |date=3 August 2008 }}, FIFA, 30 August 2003, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> F\u00e0bregas was next involved in the [[UEFA European Under-17 Football Championship|2004 UEFA U-17 European Championship]], where Spain also finished runners-up.<ref name=uefa17>Haslam, Andrew, [http://www.uefa.com/competitions/under17/news/kind=2/newsid=522833.html \"2004: Cesc Fabregas\"], UEFA, accessed 9 July 2008. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080526211523/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/under17/news/kind%3D2/newsid%3D522833.html |date=26 May 2008 }}</ref> He was named the Golden Player of the tournament by FIFA.<ref name=uefa17/>\n\n=== Senior team ===\n\nAfter emerging as one of Arsenal's key players in only his second season at the club, it did not take long for F\u00e0bregas to be called up to the senior squad. Noting his impressive performances in Arsenal's 2006 Champions League campaign, Spain coach [[Luis Aragon\u00e9s]] named the teenager in the team for a [[friendly match|friendly]] against [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]].<ref name=Spain>Harris, Chris, [http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/fabregas-why-i-feel-part-of-the-spain-family- \"Fabregas \u2013 Why I feel part of the Spain 'family'\"], Arsenal F.C., 28 March 2007, accessed 24 May 2007.</ref> In that game, F\u00e0bregas became the youngest player [[cap (sport)|capped]] for Spain in 70 years, beating [[Sergio Ramos]]' record.<ref name=espn/> He received favourable reviews for his d\u00e9but, and was involved in the build-up to Spain's first goal in the 3\u20132 victory over the Ivorians.<ref name=espn/><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/4765086.stm Ivory Coast suffer defeat], BBC Sport, 2 March 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref>\n\n==== 2006 World Cup ====\nOn 15 May 2006, F\u00e0bregas was selected for the Spanish [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] squad. During the tournament, he came on as a second-half substitute in Spain's first two group matches, contributing an assist to striker [[Fernando Torres]] in their 3\u20131 victory against [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4853264.stm Spain 3\u20131 Tunisia], BBC Sport, 19 June 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> He then started alongside Spain's reserve players (including then-Arsenal teammate [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Reyes]]) in Spain's third group match against [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4853438.stm Saudi Arabia 0\u20131 Spain], BBC Sport, 23 June 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> He earned a starting role in Spain's first knockout-stage match against [[France national football team|France]], in place of [[Marcos Senna]], but Spain lost 3\u20131.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991524.stm Spain 1\u20133 France], BBC Sport, 27 June 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> F\u00e0bregas also became the youngest player in Spanish football history to participate in a [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] when he came on as a substitute for [[Luis Garc\u00eda (footballer, born 1978)|Luis Garc\u00eda]] after 77 minutes in the 4\u20130 victory against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] on 13 June 2006; he was then 19 years and 41 days old.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4852902.stm Spain 4\u20130 Ukraine], BBC Sport, 14 June 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> He was later nominated for the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Best Young Player Award|Gillette Young Player]] of the World Cup, but [[Germany national football team|Germany]]'s [[Lukas Podolski]] won the award.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/sports/worldcup2006/storyview.html?/story/worldcup2006/national/2006/07/07/fifa-youngplayer-podolski.html Germany's Podolski named top young player], CBC.ca, 7 July 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref>\n\n==== UEFA Euro 2008 ====\n\n[[File:Spain Euro 08 celebration 2.jpg|thumb|F\u00e0bregas celebrating Spain's Euro 2008 championship]]\n\nIn [[UEFA Euro 2008]], F\u00e0bregas was handed the [[Number (sports)|squad number]] 10, rather than 18 which he had previously held.<ref>Veysey, Wayne, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2008/05/28/sfnars228.xml \"Cesc Fabregas ready to talk tough with Arsenal\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 28 May 2008, accessed 10 June 2008.</ref> Despite featuring mostly as a substitute, the midfielder made a considerable impact in Spain's campaign. He scored his first international goal in that competition in Spain's 4\u20131 win over [[Russia national football team|Russia]] and also had an assist in that game.<ref name=cescteam>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/cesc-in-euro-2008-team-of-the-tournament Cesc in Euro 2008 Team of the Tournament], Arsenal F.C., accessed 6 August 2008.</ref> Spain won all three of their group games and met [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in the quarter-finals. In that match, F\u00e0bregas scored the winning penalty in the [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] after the teams remained deadlocked 0\u20130 after extra time.<ref>[http://soccernet-akamai.espn.go.com/report?id=232283&cc=4716 Spain beat Italy in penalty shootout] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080626132140/http://soccernet-akamai.espn.go.com/report?id=232283&cc=4716 |date=26 June 2008 }}, ESPNsoccernet, 22 June 2008, accessed 23 June 2008.</ref> In the semi-finals, Spain defeated Russia 3\u20130 with F\u00e0bregas providing two assists.<ref name=cescteam/> The midfielder made the starting eleven in the [[UEFA Euro 2008 Final|Final]] against Germany where Spain prevailed 1\u20130; this was Spain's first major title since 1964.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=232286&cc=4716 Germany 0\u20131 Spain: Torres ends Spain's pain], ESPNsoccernet, 30 June 2008, accessed 30 June 2008.</ref> For his efforts, F\u00e0bregas was named in the Team of the Tournament, a 23-man squad selected by the UEFA Technical Team.<ref name=cescteam/>\n\n==== 2009 Confederations Cup ====\n\nAfter missing out for several months due to his injury, F\u00e0bregas regained his place as a regular in [[Vicente del Bosque]]'s squad. In June, he was named in the team for the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]]. He scored his second international goal in a 5\u20130 win against [[New Zealand national football team|New Zealand]] in the competition's group stage.<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/matches/round=250116/match=66203/summary.html Torres stars in Spanish stroll] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090617043847/http://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/matches/round%3D250116/match%3D66203/summary.html |date=17 June 2009 }}, FIFA, accessed 15 June 2009.</ref> In the semi-finals against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] (which F\u00e0bregas started), Spain suffered a shock 2\u20130 loss, and its 15-game winning streak came to an end.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=270153&cc=4716 Altidore's goal leads U.S. to stunning upset], ESPNsoccernet, 24 June 2009, accessed 26 June 2009.</ref>\n\n==== 2010 World Cup ====\n\n[[File:Cesc F\u00e0bregas and Giorgio Chiellini Euro 2012 final.jpg|thumb|F\u00e0bregas during the [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final]]]]\n\nF\u00e0bregas was selected as a part of del Bosque's 23-man squad for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/8695232.stm Spain omit Marcos Senna from 2010 World Cup squad], BBC Sport, 20 May 2010, accessed 22 May 2010.</ref> With del Bosque preferring a starting midfield of [[Sergio Busquets]], [[Xabi Alonso]], [[Xavi]] and [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]], F\u00e0bregas did not start in any of Spain's games in the competition. He featured as a substitute in four of their seven matches, in which Spain lost their opening game before winning the next six en route to [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final|the final]]. In the Final itself, F\u00e0bregas set up the extra-time winner for Iniesta to win Spain the World Cup for the first time in their history.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=264123&cc=4716&league=FIFA.WORLD&ver=global Iniesta sinks Dutch with late strike], ESPNsoccernet, 11 July 2010, accessed 13 July 2010.</ref>\n\n==== UEFA Euro 2012 ====\n\nF\u00e0bregas was selected as a part of del Bosque's 23-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2012]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18227019\n| title=Spain name Fernando Torres in 23-man squad|date=27 May 2012|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 June 2012 }}</ref>\nF\u00e0bregas started in the centre of the front three of a 4\u20133\u20133 formation against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in Spain's opening [[UEFA Euro 2012 Group C|Group C]] match, essentially acting as a false 9. In the 64th minute he scored the equaliser after Italy had taken the lead in the 61st minute; the game finished in a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18180099|title=Spain 1\u20131 Italy |date=10 June 2012|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 June 2012 }}</ref> He then scored his second goal of the tournament in the next group stage match against [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Ireland]], which ended in a 4\u20130 win to Spain.<ref name=\"esp-irl report\">{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/newsfiles/euro/2012/2003332_fr.pdf |title=Full-time report Spain-Republic of Ireland |work=Union of European Football Associations |format=PDF |date=14 June 2012 |accessdate=14 June 2012 }}</ref> When Spain faced [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] in the semi-finals and the game remained scoreless at the end of extra time, F\u00e0bregas scored the winning penalty of the shootout as Spain prevailed 4\u20132.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/euro-2012/euro-2012-defending-champion-spain-advances-final-beating-portugal-4-2-penalties-article-1.1103477 |title=Euro 2012: Defending champion Spain advances to another final after beating Portugal 4\u20132 on penalties |work=Daily News|location=New York |date=27 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> In the [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final|final]] against Italy, F\u00e0bregas started and provided the assist to [[David Silva]] for the game's opening goal, en route to a 4\u20130 Spain victory.<ref name=\"Spain 4-0 Italy\">{{cite news| first = Phil| last = McNulty| title = Spain 4\u20130 Italy| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18355496| website = BBC Sport| date = 1 July 2012| accessdate = 11 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==== 2013 Confederations Cup ====\n\nF\u00e0bregas was named in the provisional squad in the lead up to the [[2013 Confederations Cup]] by del Bosque.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futaa.com/football/article/confed-cup-spain-name-provisional-squad-for-nigeria-others|title=Confed Cup:Spain name provisional squad for Nigeria, others|date=27 May 2013|work=futaa.com|accessdate=16 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614091029/http://www.futaa.com/football/article/confed-cup-spain-name-provisional-squad-for-nigeria-others|archivedate=14 June 2013}}</ref> He made two starts in the competition and one substitute appearance, all during the group stage of the competition, and assisting a goal in Spain's opening group match against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], which Spain won 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 FIFA Confederations Cup \u2013 Group B \u2013 Spain vs. Uruguay: 2\u20131|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/97895/spain-vs-uruguay/report?|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref> Spain won all their group matches, only conceding a goal and scoring 15. Spain advanced to the final of the competition for the first time, after a lengthy and difficult semi-final clash in a re-match against their opponents of the [[Euro 2012 final|European Championship Final]] of the previous year, [[Italy national football team|Italy]]. The match ended 0\u20130 after extra time and Spain won 7\u20136 in the resulting penalty shoot-out,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/matches/round=255207/match=300222468/summary.html |title=Spain edge dramatic shootout to reach Final |publisher=FIFA |date=27 June 2013 |accessdate=4 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418233757/http://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/matches/round%3D255207/match%3D300222468/summary.html |archivedate=18 April 2015  }}</ref> but were eventually defeated 3\u20130 in the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup Final|final]] by hosts and defending champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/23093784|title=Brazil 3\u20130 Spain|website=BBC Sport|author=Ben Smith|date=1 July 2013|accessdate=2 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== 2014 World Cup ====\n\nF\u00e0bregas was named in Spain's 30-man provisional squad for the World Cup,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27394287|title=World Cup 2014: Diego Costa and Fernando Torres in Spain squad|website=BBC Sport|date=13 May 2014|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> and was also included in the final list for the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27647635|title=World Cup 2014: Spain drop Alvaro Negredo and Jesus Navas|website=BBC Sport|date=31 May 2014|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> He made his debut in the tournament in the opening 1\u20135 defeat to the Netherlands, replacing [[David Silva]] for the last 12 minutes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25285043|title=Spain 1\u20135 Netherlands|website=BBC Sport|date=13 June 2014|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> With Spain already eliminated, he played 22 minutes of 3\u20130 win against [[Australia national association football team|Australia]] in the last group game, this time in place of [[Santi Cazorla]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25285263|title=Australia 0\u20133 Spain|website=BBC Sport|last1=Chowdhury|first1=Saj|date=23 June 2014|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==== UEFA Euro 2016 ====\n\nOn 31 March 2015, F\u00e0bregas [[Captain (association football)|captained]] Spain for the first time, in their 0\u20132 friendly defeat to the Netherlands at the [[Johan Cruyff Arena|Amsterdam Arena]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Internationals: Belgium hold on, Fabregas captains Spain|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2015/03/internationals--belgium-hold-on--fabregas-captains-spain.html|accessdate=12 June 2015|publisher=Chelsea F.C.|date=31 March 2015}}</ref> He earned his [[List of men's footballers with 100 or more international caps|100th cap]] on 12 October 2015, becoming the tenth Spaniard to do so, in a [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]] match against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] with Spain already qualified.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Myson|first1=Chris|title=Fabregas makes 100th Spain appearance|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/88/spain/2015/10/12/16259312/fabregas-makes-100th-spain-appearance|accessdate=13 October 2015|publisher=Goal.com|date=12 October 2015}}</ref> In his milestone match at the [[Olimpiyskiy National Sports Complex|Olympic Stadium]] in [[Kiev]], he won a first-half penalty when fouled by [[Oleksandr Kucher]], but his spot kick was saved by [[Andriy Pyatov]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ukraine 0\u20131 Spain: Fabregas misses penalty on 100th appearance|url=http://www.goal.com/en/match/ukraine-vs-spain/1653387/report|accessdate=13 October 2015|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]] |date=12 October 2015}}</ref> He started all of Spain's matches at the finals, being substituted in each of the [[UEFA Euro 2016 Group D|three group games]] and playing the entirety of the [[UEFA Euro 2016 knockout phase#Italy vs Spain|defeat by Italy]] in the Round of 16 which ended their participation.\n\n==== 2018 World Cup ====\n\nF\u00e0bregas was not selected for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup squads#Spain|Spain squad]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] (his Chelsea colleagues [[Pedro (footballer, born 1987)|Pedro]], [[\u00c1lvaro Morata]] and [[Marcos Alonso Mendoza|Marcos Alonso]] were also overlooked after the club's disappointing season);<ref>{{cite web|title=Spain World Cup squad: Julen Lopetegui announces 23-man selection for Russia|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/spain-world-cup-squad-2018-russia-confirmed-revealed-23-morata-fabregas-bellerin-a8361401.html|work=[[The Independent]] |date=21 May 2018|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> he instead joined the [[BBC]] as a studio analyst for the tournament.<ref name=bbcwc18>{{cite web|title=World Cup 2018: Cesc Fabregas joins BBC's punditry line-up|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/amp/football/44435725|website=BBC Sport |date=11 June 2018|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Style of play ==\n\n=== Arsenal and Chelsea ===\n\n[[File:Second half (5131080394).jpg|thumb|F\u00e0bregas and [[Marouane Chamakh]] preparing to kick off in 2010. F\u00e0bregas was a regular [[Set piece (football)|set-piece]] taker for Arsenal.]]\n\nOriginally brought to Arsenal as a youth to slowly develop via the League Cup, F\u00e0bregas was unexpectedly deployed as Arsenal's starting [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] following injuries to fellow midfielders [[Patrick Vieira]], [[Gilberto Silva]] and Edu during the 2004\u201305 season. While [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] Vieira served as his role model and mentor,<ref>Townsend, Nick, [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4159/is_20051002/ai_n15644739 \"Spanish marvel blossoms\"], ''The Independent'', 2 October 2005, accessed 17 September 2007. {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> he styled his game after his childhood hero and compatriot [[Pep Guardiola]], whose shirt number 4 he would inherit in his subsequent move to Barcelona in 2011.<ref name=times/> Because he was of a different mould from his Arsenal predecessors who played in the same position,<ref name=times/><ref name=hubb/> this led to criticisms of his lightweight frame and less aggressive style of play, due to his development in the [[La Masia|Barcelona Youth Academy]],<ref name=hubb/><ref name=harr/> with former teammate [[Ashley Cole]] criticising the Spaniard as \"an unproven featherweight\" in his autobiography.<ref>Macintosh, Iain, \"Completely Fab\", ''The New Paper'', 29 September 2007.</ref>\n\nHowever, it did not take long for F\u00e0bregas to become one of the most coveted and celebrated young talents in the game with his success at Arsenal. Functioning mostly as a [[playmaker]] and renowned for his passing range, he was described as the general of Arsenal's first team, bringing vision, creativity, and an innate understanding of timing and space to Arsenal's intricate passing game, displaying maturity that belied his age.<ref name=espn/><ref name=ars/><ref name=uefap/><ref name=fa/><ref name=pots/><ref name=chall/><ref name=skates>Smith, Alan, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2007/01/20/sfnsmi20.xml \"Fabregas puts his skates on in chase for perfection\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 20 January 2007, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref><ref>McIlvanney, Hugh, [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2094-2104071,00.html \"F\u00e0bregas a leader in waiting\"], ''The Times'', 26 March 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> He was the main creative force when he was at Arsenal, as exemplified by his 16 assists in all competitions in the 2006\u201307 season.<ref name=stats/> Between 2006\u201307 and 2010\u201311, F\u00e0bregas created the most chances in the top-division leagues of England, Spain, Italy, Germany and France.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14491850.stm The magic of Cesc Fabregas], BBC Sport, 11 August 2011, accessed 15 August 2011.</ref>\n\nAt Arsenal, F\u00e0bregas also often assumed responsibility for [[Set piece (football)|set pieces]], taking [[corner kick|corners]], [[Direct free kick|free kicks]] and [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalties]]. By his own admission, scoring was a weaker part of his game in his first few seasons at Arsenal; wasteful finishing also being symptomatic of the larger problem surrounding Arsenal in the 2005\u201306 and 2006\u201307 seasons.<ref name=skates/> This changed initially in the 2007\u201308 season when he scored 11 goals in his first 16 games, and Arsenal manager Wenger claimed that the Spaniard's previous inability to score was down to a mental state, and even compared the Spaniard to [[Michel Platini]], a French midfielder renowned for scoring.<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/wenger-fabregas-has-the-vision-of-platini Wenger: Fabregas has the vision of Platini], Arsenal F.C., 19 September 2007, accessed 4 January 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/wenger-this-team-is-blossoming-and-growing- Wenger: 'This team is blossoming and growing'], Arsenal F.C., 15 September 2007, accessed 17 September 2007.</ref> There were also concerns raised over the large number of games F\u00e0bregas was playing for club and country at such a young age,<ref name=Spain/><ref>van Wijk, Jim, [http://sport.independent.co.uk/football/premiership/article2401632.ece \"Fabregas in need of rest after season of hard work\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927194419/http://sport.independent.co.uk/football/premiership/article2401632.ece |date=27 September 2007 }}, ''The Independent'', 29 March 2007, accessed 24 May 2007.</ref> but while he initially avoided long spells on the sidelines, he played significantly fewer games due to injury in his last three seasons with Arsenal.\n\nAt Chelsea, F\u00e0bregas played a similar [[Playmaker|playmaking]] role in midfield, using his technique, ball control, vision, and passing ability to dictate the tempo of his team's play, while he was supported by defensive midfielders, in order to give him more space and time on the ball, due to his own lack of pace, stamina, defensive skills, and athleticism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/chelsea/story/2200896/chelseas-cesc-fabregas-believes-his-good-form-in-the-premier-league-is-due-to-his-deployment-his-favoured-central-midfield-role|title=Cesc Fabregas happy pulling the strings from Chelsea's midfield|publisher=ESPN FC|last=Palmer|first=Kevin|date=15 December 2014|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/club/chelsea/363/blog/post/3262677/how-slow-cesc-fabregas-thrives-among-midfield-pace-and-athleticism |title=How slow Cesc Fabregas thrives among midfield pace and athleticism |work=ESPN FC |last1=Hurrey |first1=Adam |date=8 November 2017 |accessdate=30 July 2019 }}</ref> In this [[Midfielder#Deep-lying playmaker|deeper creative role]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/cesc-fabregas-says-he-thriving-deeper-chelsea-role-1470915|title=Cesc Fabregas Says He is Thriving in Deeper Chelsea Role|website=International Business Times|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> he excelled in Chelsea's new style of play under Mourinho,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/cesc-fabregas-believes-chelsea-success-4816953|title=Cesc Fabregas believes Chelsea success down to Jose Mourinho playing him in the right position|publisher=The Mirror|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> where he proved to be an effective [[Assist (football)|assist]]-provider.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/player/38886/cesc-fabregas|title=Cesc F\u00e0bregas|publisher=ESPN FC|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/players/cesc-fabregas/11370990/Chelseas-Cesc-Fabregas-My-favourite-assists.html|title=Chelsea's Cesc Fabregas: My favourite assists|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/11256429/Chelsea-midfielder-Cesc-Fabregas-I-am-playing-the-best-football-of-my-life.html|title=Chelsea midfielder Cesc Fabregas: I am playing the best football of my life|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/barclays-premier-league/story/2267016/chelseas-cesc-fabregas-thierry-henry-assist-record-for-arsenal-not-an-obsession|title=Chelsea's Cesc Fabregas: Thierry Henry assist record 'not an obsession'|publisher=ESPN FC|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Barcelona and Spain ===\n\n[[File:Cesc F\u00e0bregas Euro 2012 vs France 02.jpg|left|thumb|upright|F\u00e0bregas playing for Spain at the [[UEFA Euro 2012]]]]\n\nAt Barcelona, F\u00e0bregas continued to play a prominent [[midfield]] and [[Playmaker|playmaking]] role, although he was moved into a more offensive position than that which he had occupied at Arsenal. His new role with Barcelona was comparable to that which he had played with the Spanish national team. He effortlessly fit into [[Pep Guardiola]]'s 4\u20133\u20133 formation, participating in the midfield's trademark \"[[tiki-taka]]\" patient, attacking, build-up style of play, also associated with the Spanish national squad under [[Luis Aragon\u00e9s]] and [[Vicente del Bosque]]. F\u00e0bregas was used in a variety of different roles under Guardiola, scoring several goals and providing many assists. Due to the presence of [[Xavi]], [[Sergio Busquets]] and [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]] in the three-man midfield, as well as the emerging [[Thiago Alc\u00e2ntara|Thiago]], F\u00e0bregas was often employed out of position as a [[Forward (association football)#Winger|winger]], or even as a supporting [[Forward (association football)|forward]] under Guardiola. He regularly performed in the role that [[Lionel Messi]] had often occupied during the previous season, functioning as a [[Forward (association football)#False 9|false-9]] in a [[Formation (association football)#4\u20136\u20130|4\u20136\u20130 formation]] (a role which he would also play for Spain at [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]] under Del Bosque),<ref>{{cite web|title=False nine Fabregas shows his importance, and more|url=http://chroniclesofalmunia.wordpress.com/2012/06/11/false-nine-fabregas-shows-his-importance-and-more/|accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref> whilst Messi would play as a right winger or [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|second forward]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Guardiola's Barcelona-Reinventing Total Football|url=http://www.thefalse9.com/2012/04/guardiolas-barcelona-reinventing-total.html|accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref> F\u00e0bregas was, however, still used in deeper roles on occasion, as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking]], deep-lying or central playmaking midfielder, in particular under Guardiola's immediate successors, [[Tito Vilanova]] and [[Gerardo Martino]].\n\n== Outside football ==\n\n=== Personal life ===\nF\u00e0bregas married his long time girlfriend Daniella Semaan in May 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wright|first1=Chris|title=Chelsea's Cesc Fabregas marries Daniella Semaan before FA Cup final|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/blog/the-toe-poke/65/post/3499877/chelseas-cesc-fabregas-marries-daniella-semaan-before-fa-cup-final|website=ESPN}}</ref> Together they have three children, daughters Lia (born 2013),<ref>{{cite news | url = http://m.guardian.co.uk/football/blog/2013/may/11/fame-fortune-sportsman-family-childbirth | title = They have fame and often fortunes but what of a sportsman's family? | work = guardian.co.uk | accessdate = 12 May 2013}}</ref> Capri (born 2015),<ref>{{cite web|last1=Long|first1=Sam|title=Chelsea midfielder Cesc Fabregas becomes a father for the second time|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/chelsea-midfielder-cesc-fabregas-becomes-a-father-for-the-second-time-10381122.html|website=Standard}}</ref> and son Leonardo (born 2017).<ref>{{cite web|title=Cesc Fabregas shares picture with his partner and newborn son|url=http://www.thesportreview.com/tsr/2017/04/cesc-fabregas-son-chelsea-latest-news/|website=Sports Review}}</ref> In July 2013, F\u00e0bregas won a court case over the marital home with Semaan's ex-husband.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/10213603/Cesc-Fabregas-wins-court-battle-with-girlfriends-ex-husband-over-marital-home.html|title=Cesc Fabregas wins court battle with girlfriend's ex-husband over marital home|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=31 July 2013 |accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019 he was banned from driving in the UK for six months after being caught speeding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-49113717|title=Footballer Fabregas banned from driving|date=25 July 2019|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n=== Sponsorship ===\nIn 2011, F\u00e0bregas signed a sponsorship deal with German sportswear and equipment supplier, [[Puma SE|Puma]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.footballboots.co.uk/3724-official-fabregas-to-wear-puma-boots.html | title = Official: Fabregas to wear Puma boots | publisher = Football Boots | accessdate = 30 September 2011 }}</ref> He appeared in an advert for the new Puma PowerCat 1.12 in September 2011 and was one of the flagship wearers of Puma's PowerCat range of football boots.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.footballboots.co.uk/8107-yellow-custom-powercats-for-fabregas.html | title = Yellow Custom PowerCats For Fabregas| publisher = FootballBoots.co.uk | accessdate = 30 September 2011 }}</ref> When the PowerCat was succeeded by the evoPower, again F\u00e0bregas was the forefront of Puma's marketing campaign. In January 2014, the brand launched a C4 evoPower boot,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.footballboots.co.uk/22579-c4-fabregas-evopower.html | title = PUMA launch special C4 evoPOWER for Fabregas| publisher = FootballBoots.co.uk | accessdate = 3 January 2014 }}</ref> specifically designed for just F\u00e0bregas to wear.\n\n=== Other projects ===\nF\u00e0bregas starred in his own one-time only television programme, called ''\"The Cesc F\u00e0bregas Show: Nike Live\"'', that aired on 19 May 2008. The programme was sponsored by [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] and was shown on [[Sky Sports]]. The show featured F\u00e0bregas in several sketches with then Arsenal teammates like [[Philippe Senderos]] and Nicklas Bendtner, as well as coach Ars\u00e8ne Wenger, F\u00e0bregas' parents and ''[[Little Britain]]'' star [[Matt Lucas (comedian)|Matt Lucas]].<ref>[http://inside.nike.com/blogs/nikefootball-en_SG/tags/nikelive?view=all NIKELIVE] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714183226/http://inside.nike.com/blogs/nikefootball-en_SG/tags/nikelive?view=all |date=14 July 2011 }}, NikeLiveFabregas.com, accessed 19 April 2008.</ref>\n\n===Punditry===\nFor the 2018 World Cup, F\u00e0bregas was a pundit for the [[BBC]]'s coverage. He featured alongside [[Rio Ferdinand]], [[Alan Shearer]] and [[Gary Lineker]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44435725|title=Cesc Fabregas joins BBC's punditry line-up|date=11 June 2018|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n[[File:Fabregas newcastle emirates.jpg|thumb|upright|F\u00e0bregas before a match against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in January 2008]]\n\n{{updated|match played 7 March 2020|<ref name=stats/><ref>{{cite news | title =Cesc F\u00e0bregas Premier League Player Profile | url =http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/players/profile.overview.html/francesc-fabregas| work = [[Premier League]] official website | accessdate = 10 February 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"SW\"/>}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|National Cup<ref group=\"nb\">Includes cup competitions such as the [[FA Cup]], [[Copa del Rey]], and [[Coupe de France]]</ref>\n!colspan=2|League Cup<ref group=\"nb\">Includes cup competitions such as the [[EFL Cup]] and [[Coupe de la Ligue]]</ref>\n!colspan=2|Europe\n!colspan=2|