ast=Page |first=Justin |date=2013-11-08 |website=Laughing Squid |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> and creatively choreographed knitting-themed music videos.<ref name=\"at\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.apartmenttherapy.com/should-we-be-wearing-more-shawls-12-questions-for-knitter-designer-stephen-west-242489 |title=Should We Be Wearing More Shawls? 17 Questions for Knitter-Designer Stephen West |last=Zimmerman |first=Edith |date=2017-03-27 |website=[[Apartment Therapy]] |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n==Works==\n* ''Westknits at Home'' (2014) \u2013 {{ISBN|9780985299057}}\n* ''Westknits Bestknits 1: Shawls'' (2016) \u2013 {{ISBN|9780985131753}}\n* ''Westknits Bestknits 2: Sweaters'' (2017) \u2013 {{ISBN|9780985131777}}\n* ''Westknits Bestknits 3: Shawl Evolution''\n* ''Hiberknitting'' (2019) \u2013 {{ISBN|9780985131791}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:West, Stephen}}\n[[Category:University of Illinois alumni]]\n[[Category:People in knitting]]\n[[Category:American fashion designers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American textile artists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Writers from Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:American choreographers]]\n", "name_user": "Rachaelknits", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_West_(designer)"}
{"title_page": "Alix d'Unienville", "text_new": "{{short description|British spy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Expand French|Alix d'Unienville|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Alix d'Unienville\n|birth_name= Alix Marrier d'Unienville\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_date={{birth date|1918|5|08|df=y}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|2015|11|10|1918|5|08|df=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Vacoas-Phoenix]], [[British Mauritius|Mauritius]]\n|death_place=[[Paris]], France\n|nickname=Agent Myrtil/Marie-France{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n|allegiance=United Kingdom, France\n|branch=[[Bureau central de renseignements et d'action|BCRA]] & [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]], [[French Resistance]]\n|serviceyears=1943\u20131944\n|rank=Field agent and resistance operative\n|unit=\n|commands= SOE RF Section networks\n}}\n\n'''Alix Marrier d'Unienville''', [[Member of the Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (8 May 1918 \u2013 10 November 2015) was a French-British agent in the Free French (RF) Section of the [[Special Operations Executive]] (SOE), during [[World War II]] .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2015/11/13/97001-20151113FILWWW00287-deces-d-alix-d-unienville-premiere-femme-prix-albert-londres.php|title=D\u00e9c\u00e8s d'Alix d'Unienville, premi\u00e8re femme prix Albert Londres|work=Le Figaro|language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nD'Unienville was born in [[Mauritius]] to a wealthy French aristocratic family who moved back to France when she was six. She was brought up in a [[ch\u00e2teau]] near [[Vannes]] in [[Brittany]]. She held dual French and British citizenship. After managing to escape to England in 1940, she was employed writing propaganda leaflets at the [[Free French]] headquarters at [[Carlton House Terrace#Carlton Gardens|Carlton Gardens]], London before the [[Bureau Central de Renseignements et d'Action]] recruited her and directed her to the SOE for training.<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/12005980/Alix-dUnienville-SOE-agent-obituary.html|title=Alix d\u2019Unienville, SOE agent \u2014 obituary|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=22 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nCommissioned into the [[Women's Auxiliary Air Force]], she began her SOE training in June 1943, passing through the special training schools at [[Beaulieu, Hampshire|Beaulieu]]. On 31 March 1944, she parachuted into [[Loir-et-Cher]] from a Halifax aircraft with millions in francs for the Gaullist delegate-general to distribute.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Stevenson |first1=William |title=Spymistress: The True Story of the Greatest Female Secret Agent of World War II |date=2011 |publisher=Skyhorse Publishing, Inc. |isbn=9781611452310 |page=416 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wEGOrE6acYYC&pg=PT416 |accessdate=17 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Adopting the alias Aline Bavelan, her cover story was she was born on the island of [[R\u00e9union]] in 1922, moved to France in 1938 to study and was now the wife of a prisoner of war.<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news |title=Alix d'Unienville |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/alix-dunienville-dsrwl5n86tz |accessdate=17 August 2018 |work=The Times |date=3 December 2015 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nShe worked in Paris, known by the codename Myrtil to the intelligence-officers & signallers in London, and the codename Marie-France to her colleagues in the Resistance. She was successful until 6 June 1944 when she was arrested with \"Tristan\" ([[Pierre-Henri Teitgen]]) outside [[Le Bon March\u00e9]] in Paris.<ref name=\"alliancefrancaise\">{{cite web |title=Alix Marrier d'Unienville |url=http://www.alliancefrancaise.london/Alix-Marrier-dUnienville.php |publisher=Alliance Fran\u00e7aise de Londres |accessdate=17 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref> She was taken to [[Avenue Foch]] for interrogation and was searched. They found and took away her [[cyanide]] pill.<ref name=obit/> She was held in [[Fresnes prison]] in solitary confinement. She pretended to be mentally ill to escape from Fresnes and to be transferred to [[Sainte-Anne Hospital Center|Saint-Anne hospital]]. This plan was foiled by the Gestapo, who transferred her to [[Piti\u00e9-Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re Hospital|La Piti\u00e9]], a place associated with brutal atrocities of the [[Gestapo]].<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n\nD'Unienville, by once again eating and talking, was able to get herself transferred briefly to Saint-Anne, and then to the prison camp at [[Romainville]], where she and another woman, [[Annie Herv\u00e9]], hatched a plan to escape over the walls using a rope they made out of black curtains. The attempt was abandoned when Herv\u00e9 was deported to Germany.\n\nShe was in the last convoy to be sent from Romainville towards Germany, but she was able to escape when the prisoners were sent across a road bridge over the [[Marne (river)|Marne]] because the rail bridge had been destroyed by Allied bombing. She was then able to hide in two villages before being liberated by the Americans, whereupon she was able to return to Paris. \n\nAfter the war d'Unienville was employed as a war correspondent for US forces in south east Asia before she worked as an air hostess for [[Air France]] and became a writer of fiction and nonfiction.\n\n==Decorations==\nD'Unienville was appointed a Military [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] ([[MBE (Order of the British Empire)|MBE]]) by the British government. She was awarded the [[Legion d'honneur]] and the [[Croix de guerre]] by France.<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\n<center>\n[[File:Order of the British Empire (Military) Ribbon.png|90px]]\n{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=39-45 Star BAR.svg|width=103}}\n{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=France and Germany Star BAR.svg|width=103}}\n[[File:Ribbon - War Medal.png|x29px]]\n\n{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Legion Honneur Chevalier ribbon.svg|width=103}}\n{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Croix de Guerre 1939-1945 ribbon.svg|width=103}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-align=center\n|Member of the [[Order of the British Empire]]\n|[[1939\u20131945 Star]]\n|[[France and Germany Star]]\n|[[War Medal 1939\u20131945|War Medal]]\n|-align=center\n|colspan=2|[[Legion of Honour|L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]<br>(Chevalier)\n|colspan=2|[[Croix de guerre 1939\u20131945 (France)|Croix de Guerre (France)]]\n|}\n</center>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Binney|first=Marcus |title=The Women Who Lived for Danger|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nk4Xvso_dd4C|year=2012|publisher=Hodder & Stoughton|isbn=978-1-4447-5643-2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Unienville, Alix d'}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Female wartime spies]]\n[[Category:French Special Operations Executive personnel]]\n[[Category:Women's Auxiliary Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Mauritian emigrants to France]]\n[[Category:Albert Londres Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Croix de Guerre 1939\u20131945 (France)]]\n[[Category:20th-century French writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British spy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Expand French|Alix d'Unienville|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Alix d'Unienville\n|birth_name= Alix Marrier d'Unienville\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_date={{birth date|1918|5|08|df=y}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|2015|11|10|1918|5|08|df=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Vacoas-Phoenix]], [[British Mauritius|Mauritius]]\n|death_place=[[Paris]], France\n|nickname=Agent Myrtil/Marie-France{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n|allegiance=United Kingdom, France\n|branch=[[Bureau central de renseignements et d'action|BCRA]] & [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]], [[French Resistance]]\n|serviceyears=1943\u20131944\n|rank=Field agent and resistance operative\n|unit=\n|commands= SOE RF Section networks\n}}\n\n'''Alix Marrier d'Unienville''', [[Member of the Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (8 May 1918 \u2013 10 November 2015) was a French-British agent in the Free French (RF) Section of the [[Special Operations Executive]] (SOE), during [[World War II]] .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2015/11/13/97001-20151113FILWWW00287-deces-d-alix-d-unienville-premiere-femme-prix-albert-londres.php|title=D\u00e9c\u00e8s d'Alix d'Unienville, premi\u00e8re femme prix Albert Londres|work=Le Figaro|language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nD'Unienville was born in [[Mauritius]] to a wealthy French aristocratic family who moved back to France when she was six. She was brought up in a [[ch\u00e2teau]] near [[Vannes]] in [[Brittany]]. She held dual French and British citizenship. After managing to escape to England in 1940, she was employed writing propaganda leaflets at the [[Free French]] headquarters at [[Carlton House Terrace#Carlton Gardens|Carlton Gardens]], London before the [[Bureau Central de Renseignements et d'Action]] recruited her and directed her to the SOE for training.<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/12005980/Alix-dUnienville-SOE-agent-obituary.html|title=Alix d\u2019Unienville, SOE agent \u2014 obituary|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=22 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nCommissioned into the [[Women's Auxiliary Air Force]], she began her SOE training in June 1943, passing through the special training schools at [[Beaulieu, Hampshire|Beaulieu]]. On 31 March 1944, she parachuted into [[Loir-et-Cher]] from a Halifax aircraft with millions in francs for the Gaullist delegate-general to distribute.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Stevenson |first1=William |title=Spymistress: The True Story of the Greatest Female Secret Agent of World War II |date=2011 |publisher=Skyhorse Publishing, Inc. |isbn=9781611452310 |page=416 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wEGOrE6acYYC&pg=PT416 |accessdate=17 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Adopting the alias Aline Bavelan, her cover story was she was born on the island of [[R\u00e9union]] in 1922, moved to France in 1938 to study and was now the wife of a prisoner of war.<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news |title=Alix d'Unienville |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/alix-dunienville-dsrwl5n86tz |accessdate=17 August 2018 |work=The Times |date=3 December 2015 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nShe worked in Paris, known by the codename Myrtil to the intelligence-officers & signallers in London, and the codename Marie-France to her colleagues in the Resistance. She was successful until 6 June 1944 when she was arrested with \"Tristan\" ([[Pierre-Henri Teitgen]]) outside [[Le Bon March\u00e9]] in Paris.<ref name=\"alliancefrancaise\">{{cite web |title=Alix Marrier d'Unienville |url=http://www.alliancefrancaise.london/Alix-Marrier-dUnienville.php |publisher=Alliance Fran\u00e7aise de Londres |accessdate=17 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref> She was taken to [[Avenue Foch]] for interrogation and was searched. They found and took away her [[cyanide]] pill.<ref name=obit/> She was held in [[Fresnes prison]] in solitary confinement. She pretended to be mentally ill to escape from Fresnes and to be transferred to [[Sainte-Anne Hospital Center|Saint-Anne hospital]]. This plan was foiled by the Gestapo, who transferred her to [[Piti\u00e9-Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re Hospital|La Piti\u00e9]], a place associated with brutal atrocities of the [[Gestapo]].<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n\nD'Unienville, by once again eating and talking, was able to get herself transferred briefly to Saint-Anne, and then to the prison camp at [[Romainville]], where she and another woman, [[Annie Herv\u00e9]], hatched a plan to escape over the walls using a rope they made out of black curtains. The attempt was abandoned when Herv\u00e9 was deported to Germany.\n\nShe was in the last convoy to be sent from Romainville towards Germany, but she was able to escape when the prisoners were sent across a road bridge over the [[Marne (river)|Marne]] because the rail bridge had been destroyed by Allied bombing. She was then able to hide in two villages before being liberated by the Americans, whereupon she was able to return to Paris. \n\nAfter the war d'Unienville was employed as a war correspondent for US forces in south east Asia before she worked as an air hostess for [[Air France]] and became a writer of fiction and nonfiction.\n\n==Decorations==\nD'Unienville was appointed a Military [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] ([[MBE]]) by the British government. She was awarded the [[Legion d'honneur]] and the [[Croix de guerre]] by France.<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\n<center>\n[[File:Order of the British Empire (Military) Ribbon.png|90px]]\n{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=39-45 Star BAR.svg|width=103}}\n{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=France and Germany Star BAR.svg|width=103}}\n[[File:Ribbon - War Medal.png|x29px]]\n\n{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Legion Honneur Chevalier ribbon.svg|width=103}}\n{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Croix de Guerre 1939-1945 ribbon.svg|width=103}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-align=center\n|Member of the [[Order of the British Empire]]\n|[[1939\u20131945 Star]]\n|[[France and Germany Star]]\n|[[War Medal 1939\u20131945|War Medal]]\n|-align=center\n|colspan=2|[[Legion of Honour|L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]<br>(Chevalier)\n|colspan=2|[[Croix de guerre 1939\u20131945 (France)|Croix de Guerre (France)]]\n|}\n</center>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Binney|first=Marcus |title=The Women Who Lived for Danger|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nk4Xvso_dd4C|year=2012|publisher=Hodder & Stoughton|isbn=978-1-4447-5643-2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Unienville, Alix d'}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Female wartime spies]]\n[[Category:French Special Operations Executive personnel]]\n[[Category:Women's Auxiliary Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Mauritian emigrants to France]]\n[[Category:Albert Londres Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Croix de Guerre 1939\u20131945 (France)]]\n[[Category:20th-century French writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Paradoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "dab", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alix_d%27Unienville"}
{"title_page": "Alistair Brownlee", "text_new": "{{short description|British triathlete}}\n{{For|the radio presenter|Ali Brownlee}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Alistair Brownlee\n| honorific_suffix = [[MBE (Order of the British Empire)|MBE]]\n| image = Alistair Brownlee (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Brownlee at [[Our Greatest Team Parade]] in 2012\n| country = England \\ Great Britain\n| nickname = Al\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1988|04|23}}<ref name=Corus>{{Cite web|url=http://www.corustriathlon.com/en/elite/corus_british_triathlon_team/alistair_brownlee|title=Alistair Brownlee|publisher=Corus|access-date=15 June 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610021057/http://www.corustriathlon.com/en/elite/corus_british_triathlon_team/alistair_brownlee|archivedate=10 June 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Dewsbury]], West Yorkshire, England\n| residence = [[Bramhope]], West Yorkshire, England<ref name=Corus />\n| height = 1.84 m<ref name=\"AB profile\" />\n| weight = 70 kg<ref name=\"AB profile\" />\n| turnedpro = \n| education = [[Bradford Grammar School]], [[University of Leeds]] & [[Leeds Metropolitan University]]\n| club = Bingley Harriers<ref>{{cite news|title=Top results for multisporters at Regional Cross Country Champs |location=UK |publisher=British Triathlon |date=26 January 2009 |url=http://www.britishtriathlon.org/news/article.php?id=10071 |quote=Alistair Brownlee (Bingley Harriers) started his year strongly with a tenth place position at Sherdley Park |access-date=16 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090129151000/http://www.britishtriathlon.org/news/article.php?id=10071 |archivedate=29 January 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref><br />[[Leeds Metropolitan University]]\n| team = [[Corus Group plc|Corus]]\n| coach = Malcolm Brown<br />Jack Maitland<ref name=\"LeedsMet1\"/>\n| coaching = \n| other_interests = \n| show-medals = yes\n| medaltemplates =  \n{{MedalCountry | {{GBR2}} }}\n{{MedalSport| Men's [[Triathlon]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold  | [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London]] | [[Triathlon at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's|Triathlon]]}}\n{{MedalGold  | [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Triathlon at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's|Triathlon]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[ITU Triathlon World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2009 ITU World Championship Series|2009 Gold Coast]]|Elite}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2011 ITU Triathlon Team World Championships|2011 Lausanne]]|Team}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2011 ITU World Championship Series|2011 Beijing]]|Elite}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2014 ITU Triathlon Team World Championships|2014 Hamburg]]|Team}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2011 ITU Sprint Distance Triathlon World Championships|2011  Lausanne]]|Sprint}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Ironman 70.3|Ironman 70.3 World Championship]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2019 Ironman 70.3 World Championship|2019 Nice]]| Individual}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2018 Ironman 70.3 World Championship|2018 Port Elizabeth]]| Individual}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Triathlon Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| 2010 [[Athlone]]|Elite}}\n{{MedalGold| 2011 [[Pontevedra]]|Elite}}\n{{MedalGold| 2014 [[Kitzbuhel]]|Elite}}\n{{MedalGold| 2019 [[Weert]]|Elite}}{{MedalSilver| 2009 [[Holten]]|Elite}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[ITU Triathlon World Championships|ITU Triathlon Junior World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2006 ITU Triathlon World Championships|2006 Lausanne]]|Junior}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2008 ITU Triathlon World Championships|2008 Vancouver]]|U23}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2007 ITU Triathlon World Championships|2007 Hamburg]]|Junior}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Triathlon Championships|European Junior Triathlon Championships]]}}{{MedalBronze| 2006 [[Autun]]|Junior}}\n{{MedalGold| 2007 [[Copenhagen]]|Junior}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[duathlon]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[ITU Duathlon World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2006 Corner Brook|Junior}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[aquathlon]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[ITU Aquathlon World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| Cozumel 2016|Elite}}\n {{MedalCountry | {{ENG}} }}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[triathlon]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2014 Commonwealth Games|2014 Glasgow]] | [[Triathlon at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's|Men's race]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2014 Commonwealth Games|2014 Glasgow]] | [[Triathlon at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Mixed relay|Mixed team relay]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Gold Coast]] | [[Triathlon at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Mixed relay|Mixed team relay]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Alistair Edward Brownlee''', [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (born 23 April 1988) is a British [[triathlete]]. He is the only athlete to hold two Olympic titles in the triathlon event, winning gold medals in the [[Triathlon at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's|2012]] and [[Triathlon at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's|2016]] Olympic Games and the only Man to have won Olympic Gold whilst going into the event as favourite for the title. He is also a two-time [[ITU Triathlon World Championships|Triathlon World Champion]] (2009, 2011), a two-time World Team Champion (2011, 2014), a four-time European Champion (2010, 2011, 2014, 2019), and the 2014 [[Triathlon at the 2014 Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth]] champion.\n\nHis brother, [[Jonathan Brownlee]], is also a triathlete, placing second in the 2016 Olympics, third in the 2012 Olympics, winning the 2012 World Championship and the World Sprint Triathlon Championship in 2010 and 2011, as well as accompanying his brother in their World and Commonwealth mixed team relay victories.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/36690920|title=Rio Olympics 2016: Alistair Brownlee wins triathlon gold, brother Jonny second|date=18 August 2016|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|access-date=18 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nBrownlee was appointed [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the 2013 New Year Honours for services to triathlon.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60367 |date=29 December 2012 |page=24 |supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/sites/default/files/resources/NY2013-honours-London-2012.pdf|title= 2013 New Year's Honours|access-date=29 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nBrownlee was educated at [[Bradford Grammar School]],<ref name=ITUprofile>{{Cite web|url=http://www.triathlon.org/?call=TVRFeQ==&id=MjU5Nw==&keep=sh |title=Alistair Brownlee |publisher=triathlon.org |access-date=15 June 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080612212805/http://triathlon.org/?call=TVRFeQ%3D%3D&id=MjU5Nw%3D%3D&keep=sh |archivedate=12 June 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> a co-educational independent school in the city of [[Bradford]] in Yorkshire. He then started a medicine degree at [[Girton College, Cambridge]],<ref name=\"Three times a winner\">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/columnists/paul_kimmage/article7069674.ece |title=Alastair Brownlee: three times a winner |date=21 March 2010 |access-date=21 March 2010 |newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]] |first=Paul |last=Kimmage | location=London}}</ref> but left after just the first term having decided instead to study Sports Science and Physiology at the [[University of Leeds]], where he gained his degree in 2010.<ref name=\"Three times a winner\"/><ref name=ABws>{{cite web |title=Alistair Brownlee's professional website |url=http://www.alistairbrownlee.com/profile.htm |publisher=Professional Sports Group |access-date=15 September 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://olympics.leeds.ac.uk/athlete-profiles/profile.php?profile_id=3|title=Alistair Brownlee's student profile|publisher=University of Leeds Olympic Programme|access-date=15 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090513092333/http://olympics.leeds.ac.uk/athlete-profiles/profile.php?profile_id=3|archive-date=13 May 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He also completed an MSc in Finance in 2013 at [[Leeds Metropolitan University]].<ref name=ABws /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lmu.ac.uk/carnegie/sport/index.htm|title=Brownlee is the world champion|publisher=Leeds Metropolitan University|access-date=15 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926034558/http://www.lmu.ac.uk/carnegie/sport/index.htm|archive-date=26 September 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.tri247.com/index.php?component=user&msgid=ignore&command=display&display=news_details&id=11832&%region_id=&category=&region_id=&category= |title=Alistair Brownlee graduates from Leeds Met |last= |first= |date=23 July 2013 |website=Tri247.com |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n\nHis father Keith was a runner, while his mother Cathy was a swimmer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/athletes/jonathan-brownlee/690712|title=Jonathan Brownlee|website=nbcolympics.com|access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref> He has two younger brothers, Jonathan and Edward. His younger brother [[Jonathan Brownlee]] is also a triathlete, winning the bronze medal at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] and the silver medal at the [[2016 Summer Olympics]], and his youngest brother Edward is also a keen sportsman, but prefers rugby and water polo over the triathlon.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/education/brownlee-brother-keeps-up-gold-standard-1-4859831|title=Brownlee brother keeps up gold standard|newspaper=[[The Yorkshire Post]]|date=24 August 2012|accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nBrownlee was introduced to triathlon at a young age by his uncle, Simon Hearnshaw, who regularly competed in the sport. As a junior, he was a successful [[fell running|fell]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/sport/microsites/T/triathlon/brownlee.html |title=Alistair Brownlee |publisher=Channel 4|access-date=15 June 2008}}</ref> and [[cross country running|cross country]] [[running|runner]], coming second in the Junior English Cross Country Championships<ref>{{ Cite web|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/2078863.Brownlee_storms_to_second_in_Nationals/|title=Brownlee Storms To Second in Nationals}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.britishtriathlon.org/news/article.php?id=9594|title=Medals for Triathletes at National Cross Country Championships|publisher=British Triathlon Federation|access-date=5 November 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005145346/http://www.britishtriathlon.org/news/article.php?id=9594|archive-date=5 October 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and winning the Yorkshire County title on several occasions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/1965103.Brownlee_brothers_double_as_Yorkshire_champions/|title=Brownlee Brothers Double As Yorkshire Champions}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://freespace.virgin.net/bob.jackson/yxc2003.htm#Boys15|title=U15boys Yorkshire Results 2003|access-date=5 November 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724220940/http://freespace.virgin.net/bob.jackson/yxc2003.htm#Boys15|archive-date=24 July 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe has said that \"It was only when I won the World Junior Championships in 2006 that I made the conscious decision to really focus on triathlon\".<ref name=\"tcs.cam.ac.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcs.cam.ac.uk/interviews/0027213-tcs-sport-exclusive-interview-olympic-gold-medallist-alistair-brownlee-mbe.html|title=Interview: Olympic Gold Medallist \u2013 Alistair Brownlee MBE|work=The Cambridge Student}}</ref> This was when Brownlee left Cambridge to move back to Yorkshire, focus on triathlon and study at the University of Leeds. He described his decision to leave Cambridge to a student newspaper there in 2013, saying \"trying to fit 30+ hours of training around my degree was pretty impossible. I decided that triathlon was my true passion, so I moved back to study at Leeds on a less demanding course, and in a city where the sport was well supported at the time by British Triathlon\".<ref name=\"tcs.cam.ac.uk\"/> He was a member of the triathlon club based at Leeds Metropolitan University's [[Headingley Stadium|Carnegie High Performance centre]],<ref name=\"LeedsMet1\"/> and was coached by Carnegie Director of Sport Malcolm Brown, and in swimming by Jack Maitland.<ref name=\"LeedsMet1\"/>\n\n==Triathlon career==\n[[File:Alistair Brownlee Hyde Park 2011.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Alistair Brownlee wins the Hyde Park Triathlon, London, August 2011]] \nBrownlee represented [[Great Britain at the 2008 Summer Olympics]] in the triathlon event, finishing in 12th place and first British competitor. During the 2008 season, his best world cup finish was 3rd place in [[Madrid]] and he also won the under-23 world [[championship]].\n\nHe won the 2009 [[ITU Triathlon World Championship]], winning all five of the season's [[2009 ITU Triathlon World Championships|ITU World Championship Series]] events in which he competed. He was victorious in Madrid, Washington D.C, Kitzb\u00fchel and London before winning the 2009 season [[Grand Final]], held on Australia's [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] on 12 September<ref name=DT1>{{cite news |title=Alistair Brownlee wins ITU triathlon grand final and 2009 overall title |trans-title=Alistair Brownlee is one of the 26 athletes the BBC is following ahead of London 2012 as part of the series World Olympic Dreams.|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/triathlon/6178273/Alistair-Brownlee-wins-ITU-triathlon-grand-final-and-2009-overall-title.html |newspaper= The Daily Telegraph |access-date=12 September 2009 | location=London | first=Gareth A | last=Davies | date=12 September 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090915193726/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/triathlon/6178273/Alistair-Brownlee-wins-ITU-triathlon-grand-final-and-2009-overall-title.html| archivedate= 15 September 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Brownlee claims world triathlon title |url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-sport/brownlee-claims-world-triathlon-title-20090912-flg8.html |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=12 September 2009 |date=12 September 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426172243/http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-sport/brownlee-claims-world-triathlon-title-20090912-flg8.html |archive-date=26 April 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and thereby became the first person ever to win the ITU world Triathlon titles for Junior Men (2006), Under 23 Men (2008) and Senior Men (2009).<ref>{{cite web |title= Alistair Brownlee sponsorship profile |url=http://www.boardmanbikes.com/boardman/boardman_Alistair_Brownlee.html |publisher= Boardman Bikes|access-date=14 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2010 off season, Brownlee sustained a [[stress fracture]] of the [[femur]] and was not able to return to competition until June, which made defence of his ITU title almost impossible.<ref name=\"BBC fracture\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/triathlon/8538141.stm|title=Triathlon star Alistair Brownlee to miss season start|access-date=26 June 2011|newspaper=BBC Sports|date=26 February 2010}}</ref> He did however mark his return to competitive triathlon with a convincing win in Madrid, followed a month later with the European Triathlon Union (ETU) Championships title.<ref name=Athlone2010>{{cite web|url=http://etu.triathlon.org/en/results/result/2010_athlone_etu_triathlon_european_championships/4862/|title=2010 Athlone ETU Triathlon European Championships : Elite Men : Results|access-date=26 June 2011}}</ref> Collapsing with exhaustion at the London race<ref name=MailCollapse>{{cite news|last=Skerry|first=Steve|title=Triathlon marred as Alistair Brownlee collapses in Hyde Park|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-1297620/Triathlon-marred-Alistair-Brownlee-collapses-Hyde-Park.html|access-date=26 June 2011|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=26 July 2010|location=London}}</ref> in late July, meant that despite winning the final race of the [[2010 ITU Triathlon World Championships|2010 ITU Series]] in Budapest, he lost his overall World Championship title to [[Francisco Javier G\u00f3mez Noya|Javier G\u00f3mez]].\n\nIn the April opening event of the 2011 [[ITU]] Championship season in Sydney, Brownlee suffered a heavy fall while in the lead which brought early disappointment and a 29th-place finish.<ref name=Leeds>{{cite web|title=Jonny Brownlee 2nd in ITU Dextro World Series Sydney|url=http://sport.leeds.ac.uk/news.asp?itemTitle=Brownlee+brothers+win+Gold+%26+Silver&section=300&sectionTitle=Latest+University+2012+news&itemid=673|publisher=University of Leeds|access-date=26 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317124936/http://sport.leeds.ac.uk/news.asp?itemTitle=Brownlee+brothers+win+Gold+&+Silver&section=300&sectionTitle=Latest+University+2012+news&itemid=673|archive-date=17 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This was contrasted with outstanding success when, in the space of just twenty-one days during June 2011, he convincingly won the next two ITU series events (in Madrid<ref name=Madrid2011>{{cite web|title=2011 Dextro Energy Triathlon \u2013 ITU World Championship Series Madrid : Elite Men : Results|url=http://wcs.triathlon.org/results/results/2011_dextro_energy_triathlon_-_itu_world_championship_series_madrid/5977/|publisher=International Triathlon Union (ITU)|access-date=26 June 2011}}</ref> and Kitzb\u00fchel<ref name=kitzbuhel2011>{{cite web|title=2011 Dextro Energy Triathlon \u2013 ITU World Championship Series Kitzb\u00fchel: Elite Men : Results|url=http://wcs.triathlon.org/results/results/2011_dextro_energy_triathlon_-_itu_world_championship_series_kitzbuhel/5980/|publisher=International Triathlon Union ITU|access-date=26 June 2011}}</ref>) and, following a puncture whilst in the lead and having to make up more than 30 seconds on the new leaders, successfully defended his European title at the 2011 Pontevedra ETU Triathlon European Championships and shared the podium with his brother Jonathan, who took the silver medal.<ref name=\"BBC b2b\">{{cite news|last=Williams|first=Ollie|title=Alistair Brownlee leads brother Jonny to European one-two|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/front_page/13917463.stm|access-date=26 June 2011|newspaper=BBC Sports|date=25 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=ETUb2b>{{cite news|title=Alistair Brownlee (GBR) wins back-to-back European titles|url=http://etu.triathlon.org/en/results/result/2011_pontevedra_etu_triathlon_european_championships/6551/|access-date=26 June 2011|newspaper=European Triathlon Union (ETU)|date=25 June 2011}}</ref> Alistair won the 2011 ITU world title, after winning the Grand Final in Beijing and the gold medal at the London 2012 Olympics,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18902984|title=Olympics triathlon: Alistair Brownlee wins Britain's 19th gold|access-date=7 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120809081700/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18902984|archive-date=9 August 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> while his brother took the bronze medal.\n\nBrownlee won the Commonwealth Games Triathlon in 2014, controlling the race with his brother from the start, before pulling away on the first lap of the run in dominating style; Jonathan took the silver medal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/commonwealth-games/28468544|title=Glasgow 2014: Alistair Brownlee wins gold, brother Jonny silver|date=24 July 2014|access-date=26 July 2014|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC}}</ref> Brownlee also took gold in the mixed triathlon team relay at the 2014 Commonwealth Games, with brother Jonathan, [[Vicky Holland]] and [[Jodie Stimpson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/commonwealth-games/28500696|title=Glasgow 2014: England power to triathlon team relay success|date=26 July 2014|access-date=26 July 2014|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nAt the final race of the 2016 World Triathlon Series in Cozumel, Mexico, his brother Jonathan, who had been leading comfortably as they headed into the final kilometre of the 10&nbsp;km run, began to show the effects of heat and exhaustion, weaving across the course and appearing to be on the verge of collapse. Alistair abandoned his own chance of winning the race, instead opting to assist his brother over the line, finally pushing him to a second-place finish and coming in third himself. The South African [[Henri Schoeman]], who had won bronze behind the Brownlees in Rio, overtook the Brownlee brothers to win the race.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/sep/19/alistair-brownlee-jonny-world-triathlon-series|title=Alistair Brownlee gives up chance to win triathlon and helps brother over line|date=19 September 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=19 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nBrownlee made his long-course debut at the half-iron distance Challenge Mogan-Gran Canaria triathlon in April 2017, which he won in a time of 4:03:09, finishing over eight minutes ahead of the runner-up.<ref>{{cite web|website=Triathlete.com |url=http://www.triathlete.com/2017/04/news/alistair-brownlee-set-half-iron-distance-debut_300820 |title=Alistair Brownlee's Half-Iron Distance Debut Set for Saturday|date= 19 April 2017|access-date=19 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/triathlon/39678393 |title=Alistair Brownlee: Olympic triathlon champion wins on long-distance debut |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=24 April 2017 |website=[[bbc.co.uk]] |access-date=29 July 2017}}</ref> He took another win the following month when he triumphed in the North American Ironman 70.3 Championships in [[St. George, Utah]], which secured his place in the Ironman 70.3 World Championship in September 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/triathlon/39832307 |title=Alistair Brownlee wins on Ironman 70.3 debut at North American Championships |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=6 May 2017 |website=[[bbc.co.uk]]|access-date=29 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Titles==\n* Seven time Yorkshire Cross Country Champion (U13\u2013Senior)\n* Seven time Yorkshire fellrunning champion\n* 2006 Junior European Duathlon Champion\n* 2006 Junior World Champion<ref name=\"LeedsMet1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.leedsmet.ac.uk/carnegie/ept/9539.htm |title=Alistair Brownlee World Champion |publisher=Leeds Metropolitan University |access-date=15 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070706234331/http://www.leedsmet.ac.uk/carnegie/ept/9539.htm |archivedate=6 July 2007 }}</ref><ref name=Lausanne2006>{{cite web|title=2006 Lausanne ITU Triathlon World Championships : Junior Men : Results|url=http://www.triathlon.org/results/results/2006_lausanne_itu_triathlon_world_championships/736/|publisher=International Triathlon Union (ITU)|access-date=27 June 2011}}</ref>\n* 2007 Junior European Champion<ref name=Copenhagen2007>{{cite web|title=2007 Copenhagen ETU Triathlon European Championships : Junior Men : Results|url=http://etu.triathlon.org/en/results/result/2007_copenhagen_etu_triathlon_european_championships/1723/|publisher=European Triathlon Union (ETU)|access-date=27 June 2011}}</ref>\n* 2007 Junior World Vice-Champion<ref name=Hamburg2007>{{cite web|title=2007 Hamburg BG Triathlon World Championships : Junior Men : Results|url=http://etu.triathlon.org/en/results/result/2007_hamburg_bg_triathlon_world_championships/1590/|publisher=European Triathlon union (ETU)}}</ref>\n* 2008 U23 World Champion<ref name=\"Vancouver2008\">{{cite web|title=2008 Vancouver BG Triathlon World Championships : U23 Men : Results|url=http://www.triathlon.org/results/results/2008_vancouver_bg_triathlon_world_championships/2930/|publisher=International Triathlon Union (ITU)|access-date=27 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"University of Leeds\">{{Cite web|title= Brownlee is World Champion Triathlete|url= http://www.leeds.ac.uk/sport/pages/news/june/brownlee.htm}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* 2009 Hyde Park Triathlon Champion<ref name=\"beeb\">{{Cite news|title= Brownlee wins Hyde Park triathlon| url=  http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/triathlon/8194218.stm | work=BBC News | date=15 August 2009 | access-date=1 January 2010}}</ref>\n* 2009 British National Elite Duathlon Champion\n* 2009 ITU World Champion<ref name=\"DT1\" />\n* 2010 ETU European Champion<ref name=\"Athlone2010\" />\n* 2011 World Team Champion \n* 2011 ETU European Champion<ref name=\"ETUb2b\" />\n* 2011 ITU World Champion<ref name=\"DT1\" />\n* 2012 World Team Champion \n* 2012 Olympic Champion\n* 2014 European Champion\n* 2014 World Team Champion \n* 2014 Commonwealth Games Champion\n* 2014 Commonwealth Games Team Gold\n* 2016 Olympic Champion\n* 2016 Aquathlon Champion<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.triathlon.org/news/article/alistair_brownlee_mariya_shorets_aquathlon_champs|title=Alistair Brownlee, Mariya Shorets Aquathlon Champs|last=Greene|first=Erin|date=14 September 2016|access-date=5 January 2018|publisher=International Triathlon Union}}</ref>\n\n==ITU competitions==\nIn the six years from 2005 to 2010, Alistair Brownlee took part in 31 ITU competitions and achieved 24 top ten positions, among which were 13 gold medals, 5 silver medals, and 2 bronze medals.\n\n*2008, won the U23 World Championship and placed 12th at the Olympic Games in Beijing.\n*2009, won the Dextro Energy World Championship Series placing first in almost all of the circuit's triathlons (i.e. Madrid, Washington DC, Kitzb\u00fchel, London, and Gold Coast).\n*2010, opened the season with the European Championship gold medal but subsequently had to put up with a stress fracture of the femur.\n*2011, won the World Championship Series triathlons in Madrid and Kitzb\u00fchel, leading the ITU World Championship ranking, and crowned himself again European Elite Champion.\n\nThe following list is based upon the official ITU rankings and the ITU ''Athlete's Profile Page.''<ref>See http://archive.triathlon.org/zpg/zresults-ath-dtl.php?id=MjU5Nw==# {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812051308/http://archive.triathlon.org/zpg/zresults-ath-dtl.php?id=MjU5Nw== |date=12 August 2011 }}. Retrieved 12 July 2011.</ref>\nUnless indicated otherwise, the following events are triathlons (Olympic Distance) and refer to the ''Elite'' category.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Date !! Competition !! Place !! Rank\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:right\" |&nbsp; 23 July 2005 &nbsp; || European Championships (Junior)  || Alexandroupoli(s)<ref>The 2005 European Championships are missing in the profile pages of all participating athletes but the results can be found in this hidden place: http://www2.triathlon.org/etu-website/ns/events/2005/alexandroupoli/results-alexandroupolis2005-jm.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225144802/http://www2.triathlon.org/etu-website/ns/events/2005/alexandroupoli/results-alexandroupolis2005-jm.pdf |date=25 December 2015 }}. Retrieved 12 July 2011.</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:right\"| 19\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:right\" |&nbsp; 24 July 2005 &nbsp; || European Championships (Junior Relay)  || Alexandroupoli(s)<ref>The 2005 European Championships are missing in the profile pages of all participating athletes but the results can be found in this hidden place: http://www2.triathlon.org/etu-website/ns/events/2005/alexandroupoli/results-alexandroupolis2005-jtm.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728125312/http://www2.triathlon.org/etu-website/ns/events/2005/alexandroupoli/results-alexandroupolis2005-jtm.pdf |date=28 July 2011 }}. Retrieved 12 July 2011.</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:right\"| 6\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:right\" |&nbsp; 10 September 2005 &nbsp; || World Championships (Junior) || Gamagori\n|style=\"text-align:right\"| 41\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:right\" |&nbsp; 23 June 2006 &nbsp; || Europe